hild Genius vs Celebrities: SU2C Special'' (2016, [[Channel Four]]) \n* ''Back in Time For Brixton'' (2016, [[BBC Two]]) \n* ''Six Wives With Lucy Worsley'' (2016, [[BBC One]]) \n* ''Victorian Bakers at Christmas'' (2016, [[BBC Two]])\n* ''[[The World's Most Extraordinary Homes]]'' (2017, [[BBC Two]])\n* ''Further Back in Time For Dinner'' (2017, [[BBC Two]]) \n* ''Lawless Oceans'' (2017, [[National Geographic Channel]])\n* ''Little Big Shots'' (2017, [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]) \n* ''Me and My Dog: The Ultimate Contest'' (2017, [[BBC Two]]) \n* ''Long Lost Family: What Happened Next'' (2017, [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]) \n* ''The Sweet Makers''  (2017, [[BBC Two]]) \n* ''Long Lost Family 7'' (2017, [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]) \n* ''My Family, Partition & Me'' (2017, [[BBC One]]) \n* ''Mysteries of the Missing'' (2017) \n* ''Blitz: The Bombs that Changed Britain'' (2017, [[BBC Two]]) \n* ''The Sweet Makers at Christmas'' (2017, [[BBC Two]]) \n* ''Dope'' (2017, [[Netflix]]) \n* ''Child Genius vs Celebrities Christmas Special'' (2017, [[Channel 4]]) \n* ''Rome Unpacked'' (2018, [[BBC Two]]) \n* ''Back in Time for Tea'' (2018, [[BBC Two]]) \n* ''100 Years Younger in 21 Days'' (2018, [[Channel 4]]) \n* ''The Ruth Ellis Files: A Very British Crime Story'' (2018, [[BBC Four]]) \n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://www.walltowall.co.uk/}}\n\n{{Warner Bros.}}\n\n[[Category:Warner Bros.]]\n[[Category:Television production companies of the United Kingdom]]\n\n[[ro:Wall to Wall]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Refimprove|date=July 2017}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Wall to Wall Media\n| logo = WTW Logo Purple 2015 WB.png\n| type = Subsidiary\n| key_people = Leanne Klein (CEO)<ref>http://www.walltowall.co.uk/people.aspx</ref>\n| industry = TV Production\n| products = ''Child Genius'' <br>  ''[[New Tricks]]'' <br> ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (UK TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]''  ''[[Long Lost Family (UK TV series)|Long Lost Family]]'' <br> ''[[Drugs, Inc.]]'' <br> Underworld, Inc. <br> UK's Best Part-Time Band ''[[Frontier House]]'' <br> ''[[George Orwell: A Life in Pictures]]'' <br> ''[[Colonial House (TV series)|Colonial House]]'' <br> ''[[The Edwardian Country House]]'' <br> ''[[Man on Wire]]'' <br> ''[[Ancient Egyptians (TV series)|Ancient Egyptians]]'' <br> ''[[Smallpox 2002]]'' <br> ''[[The Day Britain Stopped]]''<br>[[Back in Time for...]]\n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = [[Warner Bros. Television Productions UK]] ([[WarnerMedia]])\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.walltowall.co.uk/}}\n| footnotes = \n| foundation = London, 1987\n| location = London (UK)\n}}\n\n'''Wall to Wall Media''', part of [[Warner Bros. Television Productions UK]] (formerly [[Shed Media]] Group), is an independent television production company that produces event specials and drama, factual entertainment, science and history programmes for broadcast by networks in both the United Kingdom and United States.\n\nIn January 2009, Wall to Wall's first feature film ''[[Man on Wire]]'' won a [[BAFTA]] award for Outstanding British Film and followed this success with an [[Academy Award]] for Best Documentary Feature. Previously, the company had won a [[Peabody Award]] in 2000 for ''The 1900 House''.<ref>[[The 1900 House|60th Annual Peabody Awards]], May 2001.</ref>\n\nWall to Wall joined the [[Shed Media]] Group in November 2007.\n\nThe company's name derives from negative references made in the mid-1980s, by then [[Director-General of the BBC|BBC Director-General]] [[Alasdair Milne]] and in the title of a book by ''[[Financial Times]]'' journalist Chris Dunkley, to \"wall-to-wall ''[[Dallas (1978 TV series)|Dallas]]''\" as a possible aftereffect of the coming deregulation of UK broadcasting.  Future [[BBC Two|BBC2]] controller [[Jane Root]], among the company's founders, considered this a negative, puritanical and conservative view of the medium's possibilities (ref. ''[[NME]]'', 17 May 1986) and the name \"Wall to Wall Television\" was adopted as a conscious celebration of the medium, which its founders considered the [[The Establishment|\"establishment\"]] of the time to be frightened of.\n\n==Programming==\n===Current productions===\n*''[[Long Lost Family (UK TV series)|Long Lost Family]]'': six series for [[ITV (TV network)|ITV-]] total 43 episodes with more in production.\n*[[Back in Time for...|''Back in Time For''...]]: five series for [[BBC Two]] \u2013 total 22 episodes, with more in production.\n*''[[Child Genius (UK TV series)|Child Genius]]'': four series plus a documentary, Celebrity Special and a \"Five Years On\" special for [[Channel 4]] \u2013 total 18 episodes with more in production. \n*[[Who Do You Think You Are? (UK TV series)|''Who Do You Think You Are?'']]: twelve series plus adoption special for [[BBC One]] \u2013 total 110 episodes, with more in production.\n*''500 Questions:'' First series for ITV.\n\n===Filmography===\n{{columns-list|\n*''[[The Media Show]]'' (1987, [[Channel 4]])\n*''[[The Human Face]]'' (1991 [[BBC One]]) \n*''[[A Statement of Affairs]]'' (1992, [[ITV1]])\n*''You Me and It'' (1992, [[BBC]])\n*''New Nightmares'' (1992, [[Channel 4]])\n*''Fellini Film Talk'' (1992, [[Channel 4]]) \n*''Dark Horses'' (1992, [[Channel 4]])\n*''For Love Or Money'' (1992, [[Channel 4]]) \n*''Grow Your Greens, Eat Your Greens'' (1992, [[Channel 4]]) \n*''Big City'' (1993, [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV1]]) \n*''Claws, Jaws & Dinosaurs'' (1993, [[Channel 4]]) \n*''Baby It's You (TV Series)'' (1994, [[Channel 4]]/[[TLC (TV channel)|The Learning Channel]])\n*''The Great Ape Trial'' (1995, [[Channel 4]])\n*''The Real X-Files'' (1995, [[Channel 4]]/[[Discovery Channel]])\n*''Down by the River'' (1995, [[ITV Meridian]]) \n*''Heartland'' (1995, [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV 1]]) \n*''Slice of Life'' ([[BBC Two]])\n*''Sophie's Meat Course'' (1995, [[Channel 4]])\n*''The 