ecretary at War]]'', New York, [[Alfred A. Knopf]], 2014.\n* [[Thomas Powers]], \"The War without End\" (review of [[Steve Coll]], ''Directorate S: The CIA and America's Secret Wars in Afghanistan and Pakistan'', Penguin, 2018, 757 pp.), ''[[The New York Review of Books]]'', vol. LXV, no. 7 (19 April 2018), pp.&nbsp;42\u201343. \"Forty-plus years after our failure in [[Vietnam]], the [[United States]] is again fighting an endless war in a faraway place against a culture and a people we don't understand for political reasons that make sense in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]], but nowhere else.\" (p.&nbsp;43.)\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|War in Afghanistan (2001\u201314)}}\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-south-asia-12024253 Afghanistan profile \u2013 A chronology of key events] as provided by [[BBC]]\n* [http://wardiary.wikileaks.org/ 75,000 documents on Wikileaks]\n\n{{War in Afghanistan}}\n{{War on Terrorism}}\n{{Taliban}}\n{{Post-Cold War Asian conflicts}}\n{{American conflicts}}\n{{George W. Bush}}\n{{Barack Obama}}\n{{Donald Trump}}\n{{Ongoing military conflicts}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:War in Afghanistan (2001-14)}}\n[[Category:War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|01]]\n[[Category:Afghanistan conflict (1978\u2013present)|.]]\n[[Category:2000s in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:2010s in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:2000s conflicts]]\n[[Category:2010s conflicts]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Australia|Afghanistan 2001]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Canada|Afghanistan 2001]]\n[[Category:Wars involving France|Afghanistan 2001]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Georgia (country)|Afghanistan 2001]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Germany|Afghanistan 2001]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Norway|Afghanistan 2001]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Pakistan|Afghanistan 2001]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Poland|Afghanistan 2001]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Tajikistan|Afghanistan 2001]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the United Kingdom|Afghanistan 2001]]\n[[Category:Wars involving the United States|Afghanistan 2001]]\n[[Category:2001 in Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Invasions of Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Invasions by the United States]]\n[[Category:Invasions by Australia]]\n[[Category:Invasions by Canada]]\n[[Category:Invasions by the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Afghanistan\u2013Pakistan relations]]\n[[Category:Afghanistan\u2013United States relations]]\n[[Category:21st century in Afghanistan]]\n", "name_user": "70.29.45.69", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/War_in_Afghanistan_(2001%E2%80%93present)"}
{"title_page": "Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport\n| nativename = {{lang|id|<small>Bandar Udara Internasional Soekarno\u2013Hatta</small>}}\n| image = Soekarno-Hatta International Airport.png\n| image2 = Soekarno-Hatta Airport aerial view.jpg|\n| image-width = 250\n| image2-width = 250\n| caption2 = \n| location = [[Tangerang]], [[Banten]]\n| hub = * [[Batik Air]]\n* [[Cardig Air]]\n* [[Citilink]]\n* [[Garuda Indonesia]]\n* [[Indonesia AirAsia]]\n* [[Lion Air]]\n* [[Nam Air]]\n* [[Sriwijaya Air]]\n* [[AirAsia]]\n| focus_city = \n| elevation-m = 10\n| metric-elev = \n| pushpin_label = '''CGK'''/WIII\n| r1-length-f = 12,008\n| r1-surface = Concrete\n| metric-rwy = \n| IATA = CGK\n| ICAO = WIII\n| WMO = 96749\n| type = Public\n| owner = [[Government of Indonesia]]\n| operator = [[Angkasa Pura|PT Angkasa Pura II]]\n| city-served = [[Jakarta metropolitan area]]\n| opened = {{start date|df=yes|1985|05|01}}\n| elevation-f = 32\n| coordinates = {{coord|6|07|32|S|106|39|21|E|region:ID-BT|display=it}}\n| website = http://www.soekarnohatta-airport.co.id/\n| image_map = Java Locator.svg\n| image_map_caption = [[Java]] region in Indonesia\n| pushpin_map = Jakarta Metropolitan Area#Indonesia Java#Indonesia#Southeast Asia#Asia\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport in [[Banten]] , [[Indonesia]]\n| r1-number = 07R/25L \n| r1-length-m = 3,660\n| r2-number = 07L/25R \n| r2-length-f = 11,811\n| r2-length-m = 3,600\n| r2-surface = Asphalt Concrete\n| r3-number = 06/24\n| r3-length-f = 9,843\n| r3-length-m = 3,000\n| r3-surface = Asphalt Concrete\n| stat-year = 2018\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 66,908,159 {{increase}} 6.2% <ref>{{cite web|url=https://aci.aero/news/2019/03/13/preliminary-world-airport-traffic-rankings-released/|title=Preliminary world airport traffic rankings released}}</ref>\n| stat2-header = Aircraft Movements\n| stat2-data = 447,390 {{increase}} 8%\n| stat3-header = Cargo (metric tonnes)\n| stat3-data = 953,606 {{increase}} 16.73% <ref>{{cite web|url=https://cms.angkasapura2.co.id/NUWEB_PUBLIC_FILES/angkasapura2/Annual_01_05_2019__10_15_07.pdf|title=Annual Report 2018}}</ref>\n| stat4-header = Economic & Social impact\n| stat4-data = {{nowrap|$5.1 billion & 705 thousand<ref name=CGK_ESI>{{cite web |url=http://www.ecquants.com/2012_CGK.aspx |title=Soekarno\u2013Hatta International airport \u2013 Economic and social impacts |publisher=Ecquants |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref><!--end nowrap:-->}}\n| footnotes = Source: [[List of the busiest airports in Indonesia]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.angkasapura2.co.id/en/informasi/berita-detail/bandara-changi-terbaik-soetta-berkembang-pesat-1240|title=Bandara Changi Terbaik, Soetta Berkembang Pesat - PT Angkasa Pura II|last=(Persero)|first=PT Angkasa Pura II|website=www.angkasapura2.co.id|access-date=18 March 2017}}</ref> Passenger and Aircraft Movements from [[Airports Council International|ACI]]<ref name=\"stats\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aci.aero/media/afc782a2-a258-4c49-a700-fea9047d15fb/News/Releases/2013/PR_260313_Prelim_2012_World_Traffic_Rankings-final_pdf|title=Preliminary 2012 World Airport Traffic and Rankings|publisher=Airports Council International|date=26 March 2013}}</ref> <br>Cargo from Angkasa Pura II Airports Company<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.angkasapura2.co.id/commercial/?CdAirport=CGK|title=Halaman Tidak Ditemukan \u2013 PT Angkasa Pura II|author=PT Angkasa Pura II (Persero)|work=PT Angkasa Pura II (Persero)|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport''' ({{lang-id|Bandar Udara Internasional Soekarno\u2013Hatta}}) {{Airport codes|CGK|WIII}}, abbreviated '''SHIA'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaindonesia.com/read/2011/05/17/226706/4/2/Bandara-Soekarno-Hatta-Raih-Dua-Penghargaan|title=Bandara Soekarno Hatta Raih Dua Penghargaan|publisher=Media Indonesia|date=17 May 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522081641/http://www.mediaindonesia.com/read/2011/05/17/226706/4/2/Bandara-Soekarno-Hatta-Raih-Dua-Penghargaan|archivedate=22 May 2011}}</ref> or '''Soetta''' or [[Cengkareng]] airport ({{lang-id|Bandara Cengkareng}}) (hence the [[IATA]] designator \"CGK\"),<!--<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.okezone.com/read/2011/01/05/337/410506/singkatan-bandara-soetta-lecehkan-proklamator|title=Singkatan Bandara Soetta Lecehkan Proklamator|publisher=Okezone.com|date=5 January 2011|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>--> is the primary airport serving the [[Jakarta metropolitan area]] on the island of [[Java]] in [[Indonesia]]. Named after the first president and vice-president of Indonesia, [[Soekarno]] and [[Mohammad Hatta]], the airport is located at [[Benda, Tangerang]], which is about 20&nbsp;km northwest of [[Central Jakarta]]. Together with [[Halim Perdanakusuma International Airport]], they served over 80 million passengers in 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2018/01/07/soekarno-hatta-airport-serves-63m-passengers-in-2017.html|title=Soekarno-Hatta airport serves 63m passengers in 2017|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe airport commenced domestic operations on 1 May 1985 replacing the old over-capacity [[Kemayoran Airport]]. The airport was expanded in 1991 to replace [[Halim Perdanakusuma International Airport]] for international flights, which still serves domestic charter, VIP, private flights, and re-opened as a second commercial airport for domestic flights to relieve pressure over Soekarno-Hatta airport that is currently running overcapacity. The airport served 66.9 million passengers in 2018, ranked as [[List of busiest airports by passenger traffic|18th busiest airport]] in the world by [[Airports Council International]], and the busiest in Southeast Asia.<ref>{{cite news|URL=https://edition.cnn.com/travel/article/worlds-busiest-airports-2018-preliminary/index.html|title=This is the world's busiest airport|newspaper=CNN|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indonesia-investments.com/business/business-columns/jakarta-s-soekarno-hatta-international-airport-world-s-8th-busiest-airport/item1674?|title= Jakarta\u2019s Soekarno-Hatta International Airport World\u2019s 8th Busiest Airport|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref> According to air travel intelligence company [[OAG (company)|OAG]], the airport ranked as the 7th most connected airport in the world, and ranked first as '[[Airline hub|megahub]]' airport in Asia-Pacific region as per connectivity index, ahead of Japan's [[Tokyo Haneda Airport]] and Australia's [[Sydney Airport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2016/12/03/soekarno-hatta-named-asia-pacifics-most-connected-airport.html |title=Soekarno-Hatta named Asia-Pacific's most connected airport |date=3 December 2016}}</ref> The airport ranked as the 7th most connected airport as '[[Airline hub|megahub]]' in the world in 2017 again by air travel intelligence company [[OAG (Air Travel Intelligence)|OAG]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2017/10/07/soekarno-hatta-among-worlds-largest-megahub-airports-in-2017.html|title=Soekarno-Hatta among world's largest megahub airports in 2017|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=7 October 2017}}</ref> The airport ranked as the 2nd most connected Low-Cost Megahub airport as '[[Airline hub|megahub]]'  in the world in 2018 by air travel intelligence company [[OAG (Air Travel Intelligence)|OAG]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2018/09/19/asia-pacific-leading-airports-perform-strongly-on-the-oag-megahub-international-index-2018/|title=Asia Pacific's leading airports perform strongly on the OAG Megahub International Index 2018|newspaper=The Star|accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe airport often struggles to accommodate all flights at its current limit of 81 aircraft movements per hour.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2017/07/27/flight-frequency-increased-to-meet-increasing-demand-minister.html|title=Flight frequency increased to meet increasing demand: Minister|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=28 July 2017}}</ref> Although overcapacity, after a survey [[Airport Council International|ACI]] in 2012 declared that Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport is being operated safely.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://megapolitan.kompas.com/read/2012/05/04/2122363/ACI|title=ACI: Soekarno-Hatta Aman dan Laik Operasi}}</ref> The two existing runways suffer from pavement and strength issues, which limits the airport's capacity to serve large aircraft. To reduce congestion and to achieve a target to handle 100 flights/hour, the third runway opened in August 2019. Upgrades of the existing two runways for safety and to accommodate wide-bodied aircraft are almost complete .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2016/06/13/soekarno-hattas-3rd-runway-to-be-constructed-in-2017.html|title=Soekarno-Hatta's 3rd runway to be constructed in 2017}}</ref> The airport will be able to serve 100 million passengers annually by 2025 after completion of ongoing development work.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2018/04/16/soekarno-hatta-airport-to-serve-100m-passengers-in-2025.html|title=Soekarno-Hatta airport to serve 100m passengers in 2025|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nUsed between 1928 and 1985, [[Kemayoran Airfield]] was considered unsatisfactory{{when|date=May 2014}} because it was too close to the major [[Halim Perdanakusuma International Airport|Halim Perdanakusuma]] Indonesian military airport. The civil airspace in the area became increasingly restricted, while air traffic increased rapidly, posing problems for international air traffic. In 1969, a senior communication officers meeting in [[Bangkok]] expressed these concerns.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} [[File:Jakarta Airport Dept area.jpg|thumb|Departure area at Terminal 2]]\n\nIn the early 1970s, with the help of [[USAID]], eight potential locations were analyzed for a new international airport, namely [[Kemayoran]], Malaka, [[Babakan]], [[Jonggol]], [[Halim Perdanakusuma Airport|Halim]], [[Curug, Tangerang|Curug]], [[South Tangerang]] and North Tangerang.{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}} Finally, the North Tangerang site was chosen; it was also noted that Jonggol could be used as an alternative airfield. Meanwhile, as an interim step, the Indonesian government upgraded the Halim Perdanakusuma airfield for use for passenger services. The old Kemayoran site was closed in 1985, and the land was later used for commercial and housing purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jakarta.go.id/eng/news/2012/08/kemayoran-tower|title=Kemayoran Tower \u2013 News|publisher=Department of Communication, Informatics and Public Relations of Jakarta Capital City|date=28 August 2012|accessdate=4 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220043406/http://www.jakarta.go.id/eng/news/2012/08/kemayoran-tower|archivedate=20 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1974 and 1975, a [[Canada|Canadian]] consortium, consisting of Aviation Planning Services Ltd., ACRESS International Ltd., and Searle Wilbee Rowland (SWR), won a bid for the new airport feasibility project. The feasibility study started on 20 February 1974, with a total cost of 1 million [[Canadian dollars]]. The one-year project proceeded with an Indonesian partner represented by PT Konavi. By the end of March 1975, the study revealed a plan to build three inline runways, three international terminal buildings, three domestic buildings, and one building for [[Hajj]] flights. Three stores for the domestic terminals would be built between 1975 and 1981 at a cost of [[US$]]465 million and one domestic terminal including an apron from 1982\u20131985 at a cost of US$126 million. A new terminal project, named the Jakarta International Airport Cengkareng, began.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.angkasa-online.com/12/04/lain/lain12.htm|title=Riwayat Pembangunan Cengkareng|magazine=Angkasa|issue=4|date=January 2002|accessdate=18 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020122074831/http://www.angkasa-online.com/12/04/lain/lain12.htm|archivedate=22 January 2002|language=id}}</ref>\n\n===Design===\n[[File:Soekarno-Hatta T2 Garden.JPG|thumb|Tropical gardens fill the spaces between Javanese-styled [[pendopo]] waiting and boarding pavilions.]]\nThe airport's terminal 1 and 2 were designed by [[Paul Andreu]], a French architect who also designed [[Paris\u2013Charles de Gaulle Airport]]. One of the characteristics of the airport is the incorporation of the local architecture into the design and the presence of tropical gardens between the waiting lounges. These unique characteristics earned the airport the 1995 [[Aga Khan Award for Architecture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.akdn.org/agency/akaa/sixthcycle/indonesia.html|title=Aga Khan Award for Architecture \u2013 The Sixth Award Cycle, 1993\u20131995|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020615033619/http://www.akdn.org/agency/akaa/sixthcycle/indonesia.html|archivedate=15 June 2002}}</ref> The runways run northeast-southwest. There are two parallel runways, on the north and south side. The airport terminal took the plan of spanning fan, with the main entrances of terminals connected to a series of waiting and boarding pavilions via corridors. These waiting and boarding pavilions are connected to the airplanes through [[jet bridge|boarding bridges]]. Terminal 1 is on the southern side of the airport, while Terminal 2 and 3 are on the north side.\n\nThe airport concept is described as \"garden within the airport\" or \"airport in the garden\", as tropical decorative and flower plants fill the spaces between corridors, waiting and boarding pavilions. The boarding pavilions demonstrate local [[Indonesian architecture|Indonesian vernacular architecture]], particularly the roof, in the [[Java]]nese stepped-roof ''[[pendopo]]'' and ''[[joglo]]'' style. The interior design displays the diversity of Indonesian art and culture, with ethnic decorative elements taken from wooden carvings of Java, Bali, Sumatra, Dayak, [[Toraja]] to Papua. Another example is the railings of stairs, doors, and gates, which show the [[kala (time)|kala]]-[[Makara (Hindu mythology)|makara]] (giant head and mythical fish-elephant creature) theme typical in [[Candi of Indonesia#Kala-Makara|ancient Indonesian temples]] such as [[Borobudur]]. Terminal 3, however, has a different architectural style\u2014unlike the ethnic-inspired Indonesian vernacular architecture of terminals 1 and 2, terminal 3 uses the contemporary modern style of large glass windows with metal frames and columns.\n\n===Project phases===\n[[File:Soekarno-Hatta Garuda Ticket Box.JPG|thumb|Soekarno\u2013Hatta ticket office ( Not available from 1 March 2015 )]]\n\nTime was needed to allocate land and also determine the provincial border.{{clarify|date=May 2014}} Authorities at [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol]] were consulted about the airport plans, and concluded that the proposal was rather expensive and over-designed. The cost rose because of using a decentralized system. The centralized system was seen as a more suitable option. The team, however, chose the latter, similar to [[Orly Airport]], [[Lyon Satolas Airport|Lyon Satolas]], [[Hannover Airport]] and [[Kansas City International Airport|Kansas City Airport]] due to its simplicity and effectiveness.\n\nOn 12 November 1976, the building project tender was won by the French Aeroport de Paris. 6 months later, the final design was agreed on by the Indonesian government and Aeroport de Paris with a fixed cost of about 22,323,203 French francs and Rp. 177,156,000 equivalent to 2,100,000 francs. The work was scheduled to take 18 months. The government-appointed PT. Konavi as the local partner. The plan included 2 runways with taxiways, one access road in the east and one in the west (closed to public use) for airport services, 3 terminals capable of accommodating 3 million passengers per year, and 1 module for international flights and 2 for domestic. \"An airport inside a garden\" was chosen as the design idea.\n\nOn 20 May 1980, a four-year contract was signed. Sainraptet Brice, SAE, Colas together with PT. Waskita Karya were chosen to be the developers. Ir. [[Karno Barkah]] was appointed the project director, responsible for the airport's construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ahmad.web.id/sites/apa_dan_siapa_tempo/profil/K/20030623-38-K_2.html|title=Apa dan Siapa \u2013 KARNO BARKAH|publisher=Tempo|via=Ahmad.web.id}}</ref> On 1 December 1980, the Indonesian government signed a contract for Rp. 384.8 billion with developers. The cost structure was: Rp140,450,513,000 from the state budget, 1,223,457 francs donated by France and US$15,898,251 from the United States. The airport structure was completed exactly four years later. It was finally opened on 1 May 1985 for domestic flights, and the second circular terminal was opened exactly six years later for international operations.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border: #999 solid 1px; text-align: lcenter; margin-bottom: 0; margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"background: #8B8589;\" | '''Phases of Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport Project'''\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background:#d3d3d3;\"\n|-\n!Phase!!Year!!Description!!Status\n|-\n|Phase 1||1 May 1985|| Opening of Terminal 1 with a capacity of 9 million passengers per annum||Completed\n|-\n|Phase 2||11 May 1991||Opening of Terminal 2 with a capacity of 18 million passengers per annum||Completed\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Phase 3|| rowspan=\"2\" |15 Apr 2009||Construction of Terminal 3 phase 1 with a capacity of 22 million passengers per annum||Completed\n|-\n|Fully built new Freight Terminal (on northwest section)||In progress\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |Phase 4|| rowspan=\"6\" |9 Aug 2016||Completion of Terminal 3 with a capacity of 43 million passengers per annum||Completed\n|-\n|Construction of Airport Railway ||Completed\n|-\n|Construction of third runway ||Completed\n|-\n|Fully built integrated building{{clarify|date=May 2014}}||In Progress\n|-\n|Additional 500m to the third runway ||Completed\n|-\n|Construction of Terminal 4<ref>{{cite web|url=https://seasia.co/2018/01/31/runway-3-terminal-4-to-add-capacity-of-jakarta-airport|title=Runway 3, Terminal 4 to Add Capacity of Jakarta Airport|publisher=seasia.co|author=Akhyari Hananto}}</ref> ||Designing<ref>{{cite web|url=https://money.kompas.com/read/2019/12/28/152800426/desain-terminal-4-bandara-soekarno-hatta-mulai-dirancang|title=Desain Terminal 4 Bandara Soekarno-Hatta Mulai Dirancang}}</ref>\n|-\n|Phase 5||2022||Refurbishment of Terminal 1 & Terminal 2 to increase capacity to 61 million passengers per annum||In progress\n|}\n\n===Plans===\nThe capacity of the airport has increased from 22 million in 2014 to 62 million in 2017, but the airport handled more than 63 million passengers in 2017. Therefore, plans to build the fourth passenger terminal is already underway. [[Angkasa Pura|Angkasa Pura II]], as the operator, designed Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport to have 3 passenger terminals, 1 new freight terminal (cargo village) and an 'Integrated Building', that will be built in between Terminal 1 and 2. Also, there will be an increase in apron capacity from 125 airplanes to 174 airplanes.\n\nAn airport train to [[Manggarai Station]] and a [[people mover]] for ground transportation to, from and inside the airport were also planned. The free Skytrain began operations in September 2017 while the airport train started commercial service in December 2017.\n\nIn the first stage, Terminal 3 will be expanded. Terminal 1 and Terminal 2 will be integrated with green walls{{clarify|date=May 2014}} and the airport will have a convention hall, shopping center, hotel, playground, recreational facilities and parking area for 20,000 vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/07/25/jakarta\u2019s-airport-be-world-class-\u2018aerotropolis\u2019.html |title=Jakarta\u2019s airport to be world-class \u2018aerotropolis\u2019 |date=25 July 2011 |work=The Jakarta Post |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304093018/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/07/25/jakarta%E2%80%99s-airport-be-world-class-%E2%80%98aerotropolis%E2%80%99.html |archivedate=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nTo anticipate a surge in passenger numbers, at least a ten percent increase each year, the government made plans to build a third runway. By May 2019 the construction progress reached 70 percent. 2500 meters of the runway began operational on 15 August 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/soekarno-hatta-third-runway-enters-service-460310/|title=Soekarno-Hatta third runway enters service|author=Ellis Taylor|date=August 16, 2019}}</ref> The third runway will be expanded to 3000 metres by the end of 2019. With the opening of the third runway, capacity was increased to 114 flights per hour, up from 81 flights per hour.\n\nInitially, Angkasa Pura II planned for an expansion that will use about {{convert|1000|ha|acres}} from 10 villages in the Teluk Naga and [[Kosambi]] subdistricts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/04/07/govt-prepares-soekarno-hatta-airport-expansion.html|title=Govt prepares Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport expansion|work=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://koran-jakarta.com/index.php/detail/view01/83180 |title=Bandara Soeta Butuh Investasi Rp11,7 Triliun |date=10 February 2012}}</ref> The expansion plan was rejected by the Tangerang Municipal Government because the residents living around the airport would lose their jobs. The local government offered another location such as in [[Balaraja]], but Angkasa Pura II corporate secretary said that building a new airport would not be an easy task, as it requires a thorough study.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/08/04/tangerang-rejects-soekarno-hatta-airport-expansion-plan.html|title=Tangerang rejects Soekarno\u2013Hatta airport expansion plan|work=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> Finally, Angkasa Pura II only used 134 hectares of land and appraisal will be used to buy the land.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wartakota.tribunnews.com/2016/10/14/sebanyak-2459-bidang-di-tangerang-tegusur-terkait-pembangunan-runway-3-bandara |title=Sebanyak 2.459 Bidang di Tangerang Tegusur, Terkait Pembangunan Runway 3 Bandara |date=14 October 2016}}</ref> It can be done due to a new design for the third runway.\n\nTo accommodate 86 aircraft movements per hour from the current 72 movements per hour, since 2016 the airport authority has been developing an east cross taxiway costing Rp 1,150 billion ($86.1 million) to connect the existing Runway 1 and Runway 2.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3418450/2-runway-bandara-cengkareng-akan-dihubungkan-lewat-timur |title=2 Runway Bandara Cengkareng Akan Dihubungkan Lewat Timur |author=Rina Atriana |date=9 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Terminals==\nThere are three main terminal buildings; Terminal 1, Terminal 2 and Terminal 3. The airport also has a dedicated freight terminal for domestic and international cargo.\n\nAfter renovations and expansions of Terminal 3, the current capacity of Soekarno\u2013Hatta is 51 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://interaktif.print.kompas.com/terminal_3|title=Selamat Datang di Gerbang Indonesia|work=[[Kompas.com]]|accessdate=2 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921202532/http://interaktif.print.kompas.com/terminal_3|archivedate=21 September 2016}}</ref> but the airport served 54 million passengers in 2015, making it the 18th busiest airport in the world, and the busiest airport in the [[Southern Hemisphere]]. There are non-stop flights to a large number of destinations in Asia and Australia, and several flights to Europe daily, ranking as the 17th most connected airport in the world, and the largest megahub in Asia according to OAG.<ref>{{cite news|title= Soekarno\u2013Hatta airport named Asia's largest megahub |newspaper=The Jakarta Post |location=Jakarta |date=6 October 2015 |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2015/10/06/soekarno-hatta-airport-named-asias-largest-megahub.html }}</ref>\n\nTerminal 1 and Terminal 2 are currently under renovation, which will cost Rp 3.2 trillion ($235.2 million). The renovation works is targeted to be completed by 2021. The revitalization project is expected to double the number of passengers of the two terminals up to 36 million a year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://jakartaglobe.id/business/ap-ii-spend-rp-3-2t-soekarno-hatta-airport-revitalization/|title=AP II to Spend Rp 3.2t on Soekarno-Hatta Airport Revitalization|newspaper=Jakarta Globe|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref> Terminal 1 caters to domestic [[Low cost carrier]], while Terminal 2 caters to international [[Low cost carriers]]. Terminal 3 will become a full-service terminal for both domestic and international flights.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2018/08/10/soekarno-hatta-airports-terminal-1-2-converted-into-lcc-terminals.html|title= Soekarno-Hatta Airport\u2019s Terminal 1, 2 converted into LCC terminals|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref> The airport operator AP II has undertaken plan to build a fourth terminal at Soekarno-Hatta, which is expected to be completed by 2024.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/land-acquisition-for-new-soetta-runway-in-inodnesia-stays-on-track |title=Land acquisition for new Soetta runway in Indonesia stays on track|newspaper=The Straits Time|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Terminal 1===\nTerminal 1 is the first terminal built and was opened in 1985. It is located on the southern side of the airport, opposite Terminal 2. Terminal 1 has 3 sub-terminals, each equipped with 25 check-in counters, 5 baggage carousels, and 7 gates. It has the capacity to handle 9 million passengers per annum.\n\nThe gates in Terminal 1 have a prefix of A, B or C. The gates are A1\u2013A7, B1\u2013B7 and C1\u2013C7. In the latest masterplan, Terminal 1 will have its capacity increased to 18 million passengers per annum. Terminal 1 is used for domestic flights except for those operated by [[Garuda Indonesia]], [[Sriwijaya Air]], [[NAM Air]], [[Indonesia AirAsia]]. Terminal 1A is home to [[Lion Air]] domestic flights (except to [[Sumatra]] & [[Bali]]). Terminal 1B is home to [[Lion Air]] domestic flights (only to [[Sumatra]] and [[Bali]]). Terminal 1C is home to [[Citilink]] (domestic flights) and [[Trigana Air Service]]. The terminal was converted into a domestic [[Low-cost carrier terminal|low-cost carrier terminal (LCCT)]] in 2019.\n\n===Terminal 2===\n[[File:CGK T2 check in.jpg|thumb|Check In Area Terminal 2]]\nTerminal 2 is the second terminal built, and was opened in 1991. It is located on the north-western side of the airport, opposite Terminal 1. Like Terminal 1, it has three sub-terminals, labeled as D, E and F, each of which has seven gates and 25 check-in counters. Terminal 2 caters to umrah (minor haj) flights and was converted into an international [[Low cost carrier terminal|low-cost carrier terminal (LCCT)]] in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2018/07/23/soekarno-hattas-terminal-2-to-be-used-for-low-cost-carriers.html|title=Soekarno-Hatta's Terminal 2 to be used for low-cost carriers|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=23 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2018/02/07/international-flights-to-move-to-soekarno-hatta-terminal-3-by-may.html|title=International flights to move to Soekarno-Hatta Terminal 3 by May|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=20 June 2018}}</ref> Currently, Terminal 2 Domestic (2D & 2E) is home to [[Sriwijaya Air]], [[Nam Air]], [[Indonesia AirAsia]], and [[Batik Air]]'s domestic flights, while Terminal 2 International (2F) is an international LCCT for [[AirAsia]], [[Indonesia AirAsia]], [[Thai AirAsia]], [[Sriwijaya Air]], [[Lion Air]], [[Malindo Air|Malindo]], [[Thai Lion Air]], [[Citilink]], [[Jetstar Asia Airways]], [[Cebu Pacific]] and [[Scoot]] international flights.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2019/08/13/2019-list-of-all-airlines-operating-at-soekarno-hatta-airport.html|title=2019 list of all airlines operating at Soekarno-Hatta airport|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tribunnews.com/amp/bisnis/2019/04/26/mulai-1-mei-terminal-2f-bandara-soekarno-hatta-hanya-untuk-penerbangan-lcc|title=Mulai 1 Mei, Terminal 2F Bandara Soekarno-Hatta Hanya untuk Penerbangan LCC|newspaper=Tribun News|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Terminal 3===\n{{Main|Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport Terminal 3}}\n[[File:CGK Terminal 3 13.jpg|thumb|right|The departure lounge at Terminal 3.]]\n\nTerminal 3 is the airport's newest and largest terminal. It is used as a base for Garuda Indonesia and serves as a full-service terminal for both international and domestic flights.\n\nThe original Terminal 3 was officially opened for international flights on 15 November 2011, when all [[Indonesia AirAsia]] flights started using Terminal 3 as its new base for international, as well as domestic flights. It was built to cater to low-cost carriers. The terminal was located on the north-eastern side of the airport.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.destinasian.com/airline-news/airasia/airasia-jakarta-terminal-3/ |title=In Jakarta AirAsia Routes All Flights to Terminal 3 |date=16 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 August 2016, a new passenger terminal named 'Terminal 3 Ultimate', was officially opened. The original Terminal 3 was revamped and integrated into the new Terminal 3 Ultimate. The terminal was built at a cost of 4.7 trillion rupiah. It has a floor area of {{convert|422804|m2|abbr=on|sp=us}} and was built to handle 25 million passengers per annum. Unlike Terminal 1 and 2, the Terminal 3 Ultimate architectural style is vastly different, using an eco-friendly contemporary modern design.<ref>[http://finance.detik.com/read/2016/06/04/094523/3225351/4/jadi-hadiah-lebaran-bagaimana-persiapan-terminal-3-ultimate-bandara-soetta Jadi Hadiah Lebaran, Bagaimana Persiapan Terminal 3 Ultimate Bandara Soetta?] www.detik.com</ref> It is equipped with 10 international gates, 18 domestic gates, 112 check-in counters, 41 aerobridges and 10 bus gates.<ref>[http://finance.detik.com/read/2016/04/21/170247/3193572/4/penumpang-tiba-di-terminal-3-ultimate-tak-akan-kehujanan-dan-kepanasan-kenapa Penumpang Tiba di Terminal 3 Ultimate Tak Akan Kehujanan dan Kepanasan, Kenapa?] www.detik.com</ref><ref>[http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/ekonomi/2016/01/27/358754/terminal-3-bandara-soekarno-hatta-nyaris-rampung-mei-digunakan Terminal 3 Bandara Soekarno\u2013Hatta Nyaris Rampung, Mei Digunakan] www.pikiran-rakyat.com</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the terminal's west pier (Pier 1) was extended. 8 new aerobridges were added, with 7 catering to wide-body aircraft and 1 catering to narrow-body aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tangerangonline.id/2018/10/28/terminal-3-pier-1-extension-bandara-soetta-mulai-diuji-coba/ |title=Terminal 3 Pier 1 Extension Bandara Soetta Mulai Diuji Coba |work=tangerangonline.id |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tangerangonline.id/2018/05/21/tambah-garbarata-ap-ii-kembangkan-pier-1-terminal-3-bandara-soetta |title=Tambah Garbarata, AP II Kembangkan Pier 1 Terminal 3 Bandara Soetta |work=tangerangonline.id |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTerminal 3 is equipped with BHS level 5 to detect bombs, an Airport Security System (ASS) which can control up to 600 CCTVs to detect faces who are available in the security register, an Intelligence Building Management System (IBMS) which can control uses of water and electricity (eco-green), rainwater system to produce clean water from rain, a recycled water system to produce toilet water from used toilet water, and illumination technology control to illuminate the terminal depending on the weather surrounding the terminal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.detik.com/berita/3229721/ini-fasilitas-canggih-yang-ada-di-terminal-3-ultimate-bandara-soekarno-hatta |title=Ini Fasilitas Canggih yang Ada di Terminal 3 Ultimate Bandara Soekarno-Hatta |author=Jabbar Ramdhani |date=10 June 2016}}</ref> Terminal 3 will be able to serve 60 airplanes from the current 40 airplanes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://megapolitan.kompas.com/read/2014/11/17/15163911/Agar.Penumpang.Lebih.Aman.dan.Nyaman.di.Bandara.Soekarno-Hatta |title=Agar Penumpang Lebih Aman dan Nyaman di Bandara Soekarno-HattaYYY |author=Pingkan Elita Dundu |date=17 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Terminal 4===\nAngkasa Pura II has undertaken a plan to build Terminal 4, which will be located on the north side of runway 1,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nasional.kompas.com/read/2016/08/03/18184311/angkasa.pura.ii.persiapkan.pembangunan.terminal.4.bandara.soekarno-hatta|title=Angkasa Pura II Persiapkan Pembangunan Terminal 4 Bandara Soekarno-Hatta}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnnindonesia.com/ekonomi/20160804115050-92-149157/ap-ii-ancang-ancang-bangun-terminal-4/|title=AP II Ancang-ancang Bangun Terminal 4}}</ref> south of Terminal 3, and east of Terminal 1. Terminal 4 will be built at the 4th stage as part of the development of the airport. The terminal will be built on 130 hectares of land, which will be able to serve 45 million passengers annually.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2019/10/10/angkasa-pura-ii-to-begin-construction-on-soekarno-hatta-airports-terminal-4-in-2021.html|title=Angkasa Pura II to begin construction on Soekarno-Hatta airport\u2019s Terminal 4 in 2021|accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref> The terminal will be designed in the form of an 'H' and use eco-friendly and modern design, similar to the design of Terminal 3. The terminal is expected to be operational by 2024.\n\n===Freight Terminal===\nThe freight terminal is located on the east side of terminal 1. This terminal was used to handle cargo at the Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport, both domestic and international cargo. In the latest master plan, the freight terminal will move to the west side of terminal 2 and have a larger capacity.\n\n'''Navigation Aids'''\n\nRunway 07L/25R and 07R/25L are equipped with [[Instrument landing system|Instrument Landing System (ILS)]]. The runways are also equipped with [[VOR/DME]].\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport-dest-list\n|[[AirAsia]] |[[Senai International Airport|Johor Bahru]]<ref>https://www.anna.aero/2017/01/12/airasia-adds-fourth-international-route-johor-bahru/</ref><ref>https://www.johornow.com/english/airasia-jb-jakarta-direct-flight-january-2017/</ref><ref>https://bisnis.tempo.co/read/834888/airasia-kembali-buka-rute-penerbangan-jakarta-johor-bahru/full&view=ok</ref>, [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[Penang International Airport|Penang]]\n|[[Air China]] |[[Beijing Capital International Airport|Beijing\u2013Capital]]\n|[[All Nippon Airways]] |[[Haneda Airport|Tokyo\u2013Haneda]], [[Narita International Airport|Tokyo\u2013Narita]]\n|[[Asiana Airlines]] |[[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]]\n|[[Batik Air]] |[[Pattimura Airport|Ambon]], [[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Sultan Iskandar Muda International Airport|Banda Aceh]], [[Radin Inten II International Airport|Bandar Lampung]], [[Don Mueang International Airport|Bangkok\u2013Don Mueang]],<ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/287602/batik-air-plans-bangkok-launch-from-late-dec-2019/</ref> [[Banyuwangi Airport|Banyuwangi]], [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Kalimarau Airport|Berau]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Jalaluddin Airport|Gorontalo]], [[Guilin Liangjiang International Airport|Guilin]], [[Sultan Thaha Airport|Jambi]], [[Sentani International Airport|Jayapura]], [[Haluoleo Airport|Kendari]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]],<ref>http://m.harnas.co/2019/10/22/batik-air-buka-rute-cengkareng-kuala-lumpur</ref>  [[Kunming Changshui International Airport|Kunming]], [[El Tari International Airport|Kupang]], [[Komodo Airport|Labuan Bajo]], [[Silampari Airport|Lubuklinggau]], [[Syukuran Aminuddin Amir Airport|Luwuk]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]], [[Rendani Airport|Manokwari]], [[Zainuddin Abdul Madjid International Airport|Mataram\u2013Lombok]], [[Kualanamu International Airport|Medan]], [[Nanning Wuxu International Airport|Nanning]], [[Minangkabau International Airport|Padang]], [[Tjilik Riwut Airport|Palangkaraya]], [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport|Palembang]], [[Mutiara SIS Al-Jufrie Airport|Palu]], [[Sultan Syarif Kasim II International Airport|Pekanbaru]], [[Penang International Airport|Penang]], [[Aji Pangeran Tumenggung Pranoto Airport|Samarinda]], [[Achmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]], [[Domine Eduard Osok Airport|Sorong]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[Taoyuan International Airport|Taipei\u2013Taoyuan]],<ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/286633/batik-air-plans-taipei-service-in-dec-2019/</ref> [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]], [[Juwata International Airport|Tarakan]], [[Sultan Babullah Airport|Ternate]], [[Yogyakarta International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013International]]<br>'''Charter:''' [[Haikou Meilan International Airport|Haikou]]\n|[[Cathay Pacific]] |[[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]]\n|[[Cebu Pacific]] |[[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|Manila]]\n|[[China Airlines]] |[[Taiwan Taoyuan International Airport|Taipei\u2013Taoyuan]]\n|[[China Eastern Airlines]] |[[Shanghai Pudong International Airport|Shanghai\u2013Pudong]]\n|{{nowrap|[[China Southern Airlines]]}} |[[Guangzhou Baiyun International Airport|Guangzhou]], [[Shenzhen Bao'an International Airport|Shenzhen]]\n|[[Citilink]] |[[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Radin Inten II International Airport|Bandar Lampung]], [[Banyuwangi Airport|Banyuwangi]], [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Fatmawati Soekarno Airport|Bengkulu]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Sultan Thaha Airport|Jambi]], [[Sentani International Airport|Jayapura]], [[Kertajati International Airport|Kertajati]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Citilink adds new domestic sectors in Dec 2019/Jan 2020 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/288664/citilink-adds-new-domestic-sectors-in-dec-2019jan-2020/ |website=Routesonline |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref> [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[Komodo Airport|Labuan Bajo]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Abdul Rachman Saleh Airport|Malang]], [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]], [[Kualanamu International Airport|Medan]], [[Minangkabau International Airport|Padang]], [[Tjilik Riwut Airport|Palangkaraya]], [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport|Palembang]], [[Depati Amir Airport|Pangkal Pinang]], [[Sultan Syarif Kasim II International Airport|Pekanbaru]], [[Penang International Airport|Penang]], [[Phnom Penh International Airport|Phnom Penh]], [[Supadio International Airport|Pontianak]],<ref>https://www.citilink.co.id/best-fare/terbang-ke-pontianak</ref> [[Aji Pangeran Tumenggung Pranoto Airport|Samarinda]], [[Achmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Sisingamangaraja XII International Airport|Silangit]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[Adisumarmo International Airport|Surakarta/Solo]], [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]], [[Yogyakarta International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013International]]<ref name=\"Garuda_YIA\">{{cite web |title=Starting on March 29th 2020, Garuda Indonesia Group Serves All Flights From and Toward Yogyakarta Through Yogyakarta International Airport |url=https://www.garuda-indonesia.com/id/en/news-and-events/ga-group-layani-penerbangan-dari-dan-ke-yia.page? |website=Garuda Indonesia |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] |[[Dubai International Airport|Dubai\u2013International]]\n|[[Ethiopian Airlines]] |[[Addis Ababa Bole International Airport|Addis Ababa]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|[[Etihad Airways]] |[[Abu Dhabi International Airport|Abu Dhabi]]\n|[[EVA Air]] |[[Taiwan Taoyuan International Airport|Taipei\u2013Taoyuan]]\n|[[Flynas]] |'''Charter:''' [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|Jeddah]]\n|[[Garuda Indonesia]] |[[Pattimura Airport|Ambon]], [[Amsterdam Schiphol Airport|Amsterdam]], [[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Sultan Iskandar Muda International Airport|Banda Aceh]], [[Radin Inten II International Airport|Bandar Lampung]], [[Suvarnabhumi Airport|Bangkok\u2013Suvarnabhumi]], [[Syamsudin Noor International Airport|Banjarmasin]], [[Banyuwangi Airport|Banyuwangi]], [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Fatmawati Soekarno Airport|Bengkulu]], [[Frans Kaisiepo Airport|Biak]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Guangzhou Baiyun International Airport|Guangzhou]], [[Binaka Airport|Gunungsitoli]], [[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]], [[Sultan Thaha Airport|Jambi]], [[Sentani International Airport|Jayapura]], [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|Jeddah]], [[Haluoleo Airport|Kendari]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[El Tari International Airport|Kupang]], [[Komodo Airport|Labuan Bajo]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Abdul Rachman Saleh Airport|Malang]], [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]], [[Zainuddin Abdul Madjid International Airport|Mataram\u2013Lombok]], [[Kualanamu International Airport|Medan]], [[Prince Mohammad bin Abdulaziz Airport|Medina]], [[Melbourne Airport|Melbourne]], [[Mopah Airport|Merauke]], [[Kansai International Airport|Osaka\u2013Kansai]], [[Minangkabau International Airport|Padang]], [[Tjilik Riwut Airport|Palangkaraya]], [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport|Palembang]], [[Mutiara SIS Al-Jufrie Airport|Palu]], [[Pangkal Pinang Airport|Pangkal Pinang]], [[Sultan Syarif Kasim II International Airport|Pekanbaru]], [[Perth Airport|Perth]], [[Supadio International Airport|Pontianak]]<ref>http://beritatrans.com/2013/08/20/penerbangan-garuda-pontianak-jakarta-jadi-8-kali-sehari/</ref>, [[Aji Pangeran Tumenggung Pranoto Airport|Samarinda]], [[Achmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]], [[Shanghai Pudong International Airport|Shanghai\u2013Pudong]], [[Ferdinand Lumban Tobing Airport|Sibolga]], [[Sisingamangaraja XII International Airport|Silangit]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]], [[Domine Eduard Osok Airport|Sorong]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[Adisumarmo International Airport|Surakarta/Solo]], [[Sydney Airport|Sydney]], [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]], [[Raja Haji Fisabilillah International Airport|Tanjung Pinang]], [[Sultan Babullah Airport|Ternate]], [[Haneda Airport|Tokyo\u2013Haneda]], [[Yogyakarta International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013International]]<ref name=\"Garuda_YIA\"/> <br>'''Charter:''' [[Christmas Island Airport|Christmas Island]]\n|[[Indonesia AirAsia]]| [[Don Mueang International Airport|Bangkok\u2013Don Mueang]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Senai International Airport|Johor Bahru]]<ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/285931/indonesia-airasia-expands-malaysia-network-in-4q19/</ref><ref>https://bisnis.tempo.co/read/834888/airasia-kembali-buka-rute-penerbangan-jakarta-johor-bahru/full&view=ok</ref>, [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[Lombok International Airport|Mataram\u2013Lombok]], [[Kualanamu International Airport|Medan]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Indonesia AirAsia resumes Jakarta \u2013 Medan Kualanamu in March 2020 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/289265/indonesia-airasia-resumes-jakarta-medan-kualanamu-in-march-2020/ |website=Routesonline |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>, [[Penang International Airport|Penang]], [[Ahmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]], [[Domine Eduard Osok Airport|Sorong]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]], [[Yogyakarta International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013International]]<ref>{{cite web |title=AirAsia to move its operations in Yogyakarta to Yogyakarta International Airport, Kulon Progo starting 29 March 2020 |url=https://newsroom.airasia.com/news/2020/3/19/airasia-to-move-its-operations-in-yogyakarta-to-yogyakarta-international-airport-kulon-progo-starting-29-march-2020 |website=AirAsia |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Japan Airlines]] |[[Narita International Airport|Tokyo\u2013Narita]]\n|[[Jet Asia Airways]] |[[Suvarnabhumi Airport|Bangkok\u2013Suvarnabhumi]]\n|[[Jetstar Asia Airways]] |[[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]] \n|[[KLM]] |[[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol|Amsterdam]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]]\n|[[Korean Air]] |[[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]]\n|[[Lion Air]] |[[Pattimura Airport|Ambon]], [[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Sultan Iskandar Muda International Airport|Banda Aceh]], [[Radin Inten II International Airport|Bandar Lampung]], [[Syamsudin Noor International Airport|Banjarmasin]], [[Banyuwangi Airport|Banyuwangi]], [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Fatmawati Soekarno Airport|Bengkulu]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Sultan Thaha Airport|Jambi]], [[Sentani International Airport|Jayapura]], [[Haluoleo Airport|Kendari]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[El Tari International Airport|Kupang]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Abdul Rachman Saleh Airport|Malang]], [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]], [[Zainuddin Abdul Madjid International Airport|Mataram\u2013Lombok]], [[Kualanamu International Airport|Medan]], [[Minangkabau International Airport|Padang]], [[Tjilik Riwut Airport|Palangkaraya]], [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport|Palembang]], [[Depati Amir Airport|Pangkal Pinang]], [[Mutiara SIS Al-Jufrie Airport|Palu]], [[Sultan Syarif Kasim II International Airport|Pekanbaru]], [[Supadio International Airport|Pontianak]],<ref>https://www.amp.kontan.co.id/news/lion-air-tambang-jadwal-terbang-pontianak-jakarta</ref> [[Achmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[Adisumarmo International Airport|Surakarta/Solo]], [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]], [[Raja Haji Fisabilillah International Airport|Tanjung Pinang]], [[Juwata International Airport|Tarakan]], [[Sultan Babullah Airport|Ternate]],<ref>https://agent.lionair.co.id/LionAirAgentsPortal/Default.aspx/</ref> [[Yogyakarta International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013International]]<ref>https://agent.lionair.co.id/LionAirAgentsPortal/Default.aspx</ref>  <br>'''Charter:''' [[Sanya Phoenix International Airport|Sanya]]\n|[[Malaysia Airlines]]| [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]]\n|[[Malindo Air]]| [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]]\n|[[NAM Air]]| [[Silampari Airport|Lubuklinggau]], [[Muara Bungo Airport|Muara Bungo]], [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport|Palembang]], [[Pangkal Pinang Airport|Pangkal Pinang]], [[Supadio International Airport|Pontianak]]<ref>https://www.flynamair.com/about</ref><ref>https://jambi.antaranews.com/berita/308789/seputar-nam-air-yang-patut-anda-ketahui</ref>, [[H. Asan Airport|Sampit]], [[Achmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]]\n|[[Oman Air]]| [[Muscat International Airport|Muscat]]\n|[[Philippine Airlines]]| [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|Manila]] \n|[[Qantas]]| [[Sydney Airport|Sydney]]\n|[[Qatar Airways]]| [[Hamad International Airport|Doha]]\n|[[Royal Brunei Airlines]]| [[Brunei International Airport|Bandar Seri Begawan]]\n|[[Saudia]]| [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|Jeddah]], [[Prince Mohammad bin Abdulaziz Airport|Medina]], [[King Khalid International Airport|Riyadh]]\n|[[Scoot]]| [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|[[Shenzhen Airlines]]| [[Shenzhen Bao'an International Airport|Shenzhen]] \n|[[Singapore Airlines]]| [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|[[SriLankan Airlines]]| [[Bandaranaike International Airport|Colombo\u2013Bandaranaike]]\n|[[Sriwijaya Air]]| [[Radin Inten II International Airport|Bandar Lampung]], [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Sultan Thaha Airport|Jambi]], [[Sentani International Airport|Jayapura]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Abdul Rachman Saleh Airport|Malang]], [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]], [[Kualanamu International Airport|Medan]], [[Minangkabau International Airport|Padang]], [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport|Palembang]], [[Depati Amir Airport|Pangkal Pinang]]<ref>https://www.airmagz.com/54069/jelang-imlek-2020-sriwijaya-air-tambah-rute-penerbangan.html</ref>, [[Supadio International Airport|Pontianak]]<ref>https://www.airmagz.com/54069/jelang-imlek-2020-sriwijaya-air-tambah-rute-penerbangan.html</ref>, [[Achmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Sisingamangaraja XII International Airport|Silangit]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[Adisumarmo International Airport|Surakarta/Solo]], [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]], [[Raja Haji Fisabilillah International Airport|Tanjung Pinang]], [[Yogyakarta International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013International]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Mulai Tanggal 29 Maret 2020 Penerbangan Sriwijaya Air dari/ke Yogyakarta Pindah ke Yogyakarta International Airport (YIA) |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B9RD5mxJcB9/ |website=Sriwijaya Air Official Instagram |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>  <br>'''Charter:''' [[Haikou Meilan International Airport|Haikou]], [[Nanning Wuxu International Airport|Nanning]], [[Zhangjiajie Hehua International Airport|Zhangjiajie]]\n|[[Thai Airways]]| [[Suvarnabhumi Airport|Bangkok\u2013Suvarnabhumi]]\n|[[Thai Lion Air]]| [[Don Mueang International Airport|Bangkok\u2013Don Mueang]] \n|[[Trigana Air Service]]| [[Iskandar Airport|Pangkalan Bun]]\n|[[Turkish Airlines]]| [[Istanbul New Airport|Istanbul]]\n|[[Uzbekistan Airways]]| [[Tashkent International Airport|Tashkent]] \n|[[Vietnam Airlines]]| [[Tan Son Nhat International Airport|Ho Chi Minh City]]\n|[[XiamenAir]]| [[Fuzhou Changle International Airport|Fuzhou]], [[Xiamen Gaoqi International Airport|Xiamen]]\n}}\n\n===Cargo===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%;width:78%\"\n|- style=\"background:lightgrey;\"\n! style=\"width:22%;\"|Airlines|| class=\"unsortable\"|Destinations\n|- \n|[[ANA Cargo]] || [[Narita International Airport|Tokyo\u2013Narita]]<ref name=\"NH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anacargo.jp/en/int/news/schedule/2014/140430.html|title=Expand Freighter Network from May 14th, 2014|publisher=ANA Cargo|date=30 April 2014| accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref>\n|- \n|[[Asialink Cargo Airlines]] || [[Depati Amir Airport|Pangkal Pinang]]<ref>http://www.asialinkcargo.co.id</ref>\n|-\n|[[Cardig Air]] || [[Tan Son Nhat International Airport|Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Shenzhen Bao'an International Airport|Shenzhen]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardigair.com/site/schedule.php |title=Cardig Air Scheduled Timetable |publisher=Cardigair.com |date= |accessdate=1 January 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Cargolux]] || [[Luxembourg Airport|Luxembourg]], [[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]]\n|-\n|[[Cathay Pacific Cargo]] || [[Noi Bai International Airport|Hanoi]], [[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]], [[Penang International Airport|Penang]]\n|-\n|[[China Airlines Cargo]] || [[Taiwan Taoyuan International Airport|Taipei\u2013Taoyuan]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]]\n|-\n|[[FedEx Express]] || [[Guangzhou Baiyun International Airport|Guangzhou]], [[Tan Son Nhat International Airport|Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]], [[Bangkok-Suvarnabhumi]]\n|-\n|[[K-Mile Air]] || [[Bangkok-Suvarnabhumi]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|-\n|[[Korean Air Cargo]] || [[Tan Son Nhat International Airport|Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Penang International Airport|Penang]], [[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]]\n|- \n|[[MASkargo]] || [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]] \n|- \n|[[My Indo Airlines]] || [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]], [[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Ahmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]]\n|-\n|[[Qantas Freight]] || [[Sydney Airport|Sydney]] \n|-\n|[[Singapore Airlines Cargo]] || [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|-\n|[[Raya Airways]] || [[Sultan Abdul Aziz Shah Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013Subang]]\n|-\n|[[Tri-MG Intra Asia Airlines]] || [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===Busiest routes===\nJakarta\u2013Singapore is one of the world's busiest international air routes; passenger numbers of this route is growing fast. It was the second busiest international route in Asia after Hong Kong\u2013Taipei in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/changis-busiest-routes-set-to-grow-further|title=Changis busiest routes set to growfurther}}</ref> [[Singapore Airlines]] alone operates more than 70 weekly flights between Jakarta & Singapore. Jakarta Soekarno-Hatta\u2013Surabaya route is ranked ninth busiest in the world by [[IATA]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.traveller.com.au/worlds-busiest-air-routes-the-busiest-route-in-the-world-will-surprise-you-gtemeg|title=The busiest-route in the world will surprise you}}</ref> Jakarta\u2013Singapore, and Jakarta\u2013Kuala Lumpur routes are ranked within the top ten of world's busiest international air routes in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/spore-kl-route-is-worlds-busiest-global-air-link|title=Singapore-KL route is world's busiest global air link|newspaper=The Straits Times|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===New traffic procedure===\nTo ease congestion, the airport authority implemented a new traffic procedure, the 72 Improved Runway Capacity (IRC 72), to handle 72 planes per hour. This limited a plane to 30\u201345 minutes only for arrival and unloading of passengers, to allow other planes to use the parking space. Gradually it has been implemented and on 26 June 2014 IRC 72 has been implemented fully for the period of 00:00 am to 01:30 am, 02:00 am to 10:00 am and 11:30 pm to 00:00 am with occupancy periods for aircraft are reduced from 110 seconds to 90 seconds of takeoff and from 65 seconds to 50 seconds for landing. The low time is from 04:00pm to 10:00pm with only maximum 32 flights/hour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.tempo.co/read/news/2014/06/26/056588302/Soekarno-Hatta-Airport-Increases-Runway-Capacity |title=Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport Increases Runway Capacity |date=26 June 2014 |publisher=Tempo.co}}</ref> By 2015, IRC 72 will become IRC 86 with the opening of the new terminal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.tempo.co/read/news/2014/02/21/056556275/Air-Traffic-Procedures-Restructured |title=Air Traffic Procedures Restructured |author=Maria Yuniar |date=21 February 2014 |publisher=Tempo.co}}</ref> As a comparison, [[London Heathrow Airport]], which has 2 runways like SHIA, can handle 100 flights per hour, so the target for SHIA has been revised to 92 flights per hour by 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.tempo.co/read/news/2014/04/25/056573110/Soekarno-Hatta-Airport-Ready-to-Serve-72-Flights-per-Hour |title=Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport Ready to Serve 72 Flights per Hour |author=Ananda Putri |date=25 April 2014 |publisher=Tempo.co}}</ref> As of July 2017, maximum flight frequency at Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport had been increased to 81 take-offs and landings per hour to accommodate increasing demand from aviation companies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2017/07/27/flight-frequency-increased-to-meet-increasing-demand-minister.html|title=Flight frequency increased to meet increasing demand: Minister|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=28 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Airport facilities==\nTerminals 1 and 2 were designed to resemble a traditional ''joglo'' Javanese construction. The approach has been emphasized by the inclusion of well-maintained gardens located near all boarding areas. Terminal 3 and other new airport buildings use an eco-friendly and modern design.\n\n===Aircraft maintenance===\nMaintenance facilities for aircraft in Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport are supported by [[GMF AeroAsia]] (Garuda Maintenance Facility).\nThey include {{convert|480000|m2|sqft|sp=us}} of built-up structures, including four hangars, a spares warehouse, workshops, utility buildings, a ground support equipment building, chemical stores, an engine test cell, and management offices. In addition, [[GMF AeroAsia]] has an apron capable of handling up to 50 aircraft, taxiways, a run-up bay, and a waste treatment area, taking up {{convert|1150000|m2|sqft|sp=us}}.\n\nHangar 1 was built in 1991 and was designed for [[Boeing 747]]s. It has two full docks and is {{convert|22000|m2|sqft|sp=us}}. Hangar 2 is {{convert|23000|m2|sqft|sp=us}} and has 3 aircraft bays. It can perform minor A and B checks. It can hold up to one narrow body and one wide-body jet. Hangar 3 is also {{convert|23000|m2|sqft|sp=us}}. It normally holds up to 3 narrow-body aircraft but can be configured to hold up to one wide-body and one narrow body. It has 7 bays with 4 full docks, 6 roof-mounted cranes and one bay designed for [[McDonnell Douglas MD-11]]s, [[McDonnell Douglas DC-10]]s, and wide-body [[Airbus A330]]s aircraft. Hangar 4 is {{convert|67022|m2|sqft|sp=us}}. The Hangar 4 was opened in 2015 and was designed for narrow-body aircraft like B737s and A320s. It can handle 16 narrow-body aircraft at one time.\n\n===Golf course===\nThere is a golf course at the Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport supported by the Cengkareng Golf Club. The golf course has been open since 1999. It is located on the left side of the airport main gate by the Sheraton Bandara Hotel. The Cengkareng Golf Club is in the {{convert|102|ha|acres|adj = on}} Soewarna Business Park at Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport. In 2005 and 2008, this golf course was used for [[Indonesia Open (golf)|Indonesia Open]], a part of the [[PGA European Tour]]. There are 18 holes in the golf course.\n\n===Airport hotel===\nSoekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport has a hotel, the Bandara International Hotel, managed by [[AccorHotels]]. The Bandara International Hotel, which is located on the left side of the main exit road from the airport, has 4 floors with 220 guest rooms. The airport now has other hotels, including budget such as Ibis Styles, Pop! Hotels, Swiss-Belhotel, Orchard Hotel, Swiss-Belinn, Ibis Budget, and Amaris as an alternative. Terminal 3 of the airport has a Digital Airport Hotel or [[Capsule hotel]] with 120 rooms, which has Alpha-type and Beta-type rooms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.tempo.co/read/news/2018/08/08/056920640/Soekarno-Hatta-Airports-Capsule-Hotel-Can-be-Booked-Online|title= Soekarno Hatta Airport`s Capsule Hotel Can be Booked Online|newspaper=Tempo|accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Lounges===\nThere are five airport lounges in the departure area. The Jasa Angkasa Semesta (JAS) Lounge is available for first and business class passengers of [[Cathay Pacific]], [[Qantas]], [[EVA Air]], [[Saudia]], and [[Singapore Airlines]]. The Pura Indah Lounge is available for first and business class passengers of [[Singapore Airlines]], [[KLM]], [[Malaysia Airlines]], [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]], [[Cathay Pacific]], and [[China Airlines]]. The new Garuda Indonesia lounge is available for their business class and first-class passengers only, as well as GECC and GarudaMiles gold and above cardholders. The BNI Executive Lounge is located next to the Garuda Indonesia Lounge, the lounge serves passengers from all airlines. Other lounges are available outside of the departures area, operated by companies such as [[Indosat]], Sapphire, PT Mandara Jasindo Sena, [[Telkomsel]], and [[XL Axiata]]. Since 2013, the only lounge in Terminal 1 was opened named Batik Air Business Class Lounge inside the waiting room C7. The Garuda Indonesia lounge has been moved to Terminal 3 Ultimate.\n\n===Other facilities===\n[[File:Jakarta Airport 200507-1.jpg|thumb|Shopping area at Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport]]\nThe airport contains the head office of [[Garuda Indonesia]], Garuda Indonesia Management Building, located within the Garuda Indonesia City Center.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.garuda-indonesia.com/news/2009/07/23/president-susilo-bambang-yudhoyono-officially-opens-new-head-office-and-the-unveiling-of-new-garuda-indonesia-concept-of-service |title=President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono Officially Opens New Head Office and the Unveiling of New Garuda Indonesia Concept of Service |publisher=Garuda Indonesia |date=23 July 2009 |accessdate=16 September 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231210258/http://www.garuda-indonesia.com/news/2009/07/23/president-susilo-bambang-yudhoyono-officially-opens-new-head-office-and-the-unveiling-of-new-garuda-indonesia-concept-of-service |archivedate=31 December 2010}}</ref> [[Angkasa Pura]] II's head office is on the airport property.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angkasapura2.co.id/profile.php?isi=20&bhs=ina |title=Informasi Perusahaan |publisher=[[Angkasa Pura]] II |accessdate=16 September 2010 |quote=Kantor Pusat PT (Persero) Angkasa Pura II Bandara Internasional Jakarta Soekarno\u2013Hatta}}</ref>\n\nThere are 21 reading corners located in the waiting rooms of Terminal 2D, 2E and 2F.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://medan.tribunnews.com/2013/07/23/pojok-baca-kini-hadir-di-bandara-soekarno-hatta |title=Pojok Baca Kini Hadir di Bandara Soekarno Hatta |date=23 July 2013}}</ref> Shopping areas are also available in all terminals. Duty-free shops, souvenir shops, restaurants, and a cafeteria can be found there. There is a new \"Shopping Arcade\" located in terminal 1C. There are no shops in the arrival zones of the terminals, except for Terminal 3, where several cafes and fast-food restaurant chains are located.\n\nLintasarta, Internux (via YelloChat Free WiFi) and Telkom Indonesia have provided WiFi networks for the airport. The three networks allow users to connect to another network if a specific one is operational. Since November 2013, Terminal 2 has free WiFi covering the whole terminal and free WiFi for Terminal 1 is servicing as of July 2014. Terminal 3 now has free WiFi covering since November 2014.\n\nTo handle the overcrowding of smoking rooms being used, airport authorities have drawn up plans to build a smoking area in a garden near the rest area in Terminal 1A. It was opened in January 2015 and it will be developed to other terminals, if necessary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wartakota.tribunnews.com/2014/12/23/taman-khusus-merokok-dibangun-di-bandara|title=Taman Khusus Merokok Dibangun di Bandara|date=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Ground transportation==\nThere are several transportation options available for access to the airport: local airport terminal shuttles, trains, buses, taxi services of various kinds, and cars. There is a free shuttle bus service and people maneuver system ''Skytrain'' to connect the terminals of the airport.\n\n===Bus===\nSeveral bus companies, including the state-owned [[Perum DAMRI]] and private company Primajasa,<ref>{{cite news |last=Atriana |first=Rina |date=9 August 2016 |title=Transportasi di T3 Ultimate Bandara Soetta: Taksi, Damri hingga Shuttle Bus |url=https://news.detik.com/berita/3271710/transportasi-di-t3-ultimate-bandara-soetta-taksi-damri-hingga-shuttle-bus |work=detikNews |access-date=18 June 2017 |language=id}}</ref> provide services to various destinations from the airport. ''Jabodetabek Airport Connexion'' which consist of [[Perum DAMRI]],[[Perum PPD]], Big Bird dan Sinar Jaya Megah Langgeng serve routes from the airport to certain malls and hotels in [[Jabodetabek|Greater Jakarta]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wartakota.tribunnews.com/2017/05/30/dari-hotel-atau-mal-ke-bandara-soetta-bisa-naik-ini |title=Dari Hotel atau Mal ke Bandara Soetta Bisa Naik Ini |author=Max Agung Pribadi |date=30 May 2017}}</ref> The buses operate from 06.00 to 23.00 with routes:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wartakota.tribunnews.com/2017/05/30/blue-bird-luncurkan-bus-bandara-soeta-jabodetabek-dengan-tarif-rp-50000 |title=Blue Bird Luncurkan Bus Bandara Soetta-Jabodetabek dengan Tarif Rp 50000 |date=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nTravel time to and from the center of Jakarta (at the [[Gambir Station|Gambir railway station]]) takes around 70 minutes, depending on traffic. Buses to the airport leave from the various terminals in central Jakarta ([[Gambir, Gambir|Gambir]]) and surrounding areas.\n\n==== BUS - Shuttle service====\n{| style=\"text-align:left; font-size:95%; border:1px solid black\"\n|-\n! Service !! !!Destination (Soetta Airport,Terminal 1, 2 and 3)\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#09f; color:black; height:35px;\"| Shuttle Airport Bus\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:red;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Agramas || Pusat Grosir Cililitan ||[[East Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:green;color:white;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Citilink Shuttle || Scientia Square Park ||[[South Tangerang]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:green;color:white;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Citilink Shuttle || SCBD ||[[Central Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Bandung ||[[Bandung]]<ref>http://bumn.go.id/damri/berita/1-Trayek-Baru-DAMRI-Basoetta---Bandung-dan-Jakarta---Surabaya</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Bekasi Kayuringin Bus Terminal ||[[Bekasi]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Bekasi Trade Center||[[Bekasi]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Blok M Bus Terminal ||[[South Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Botani Square Mall ||[[Bogor]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Cikarang ||[[Cikarang]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Citra Raya ||[[Tangerang Regency]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || City Mall Cibinong ||[[Cibinong]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Depok ||[[Depok]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Epicentrum ||[[South Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Gambir Railway Station ||[[Central Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Kampung Rambutan Bus Terminal ||[[East Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Karawang ||[[Karawang]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Kemang Pratama ||[[Bekasi]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Kemayoran ||[[Central Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Kota Harapan Indah ||[[Bekasi]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Lebak Bulus ||[[South Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Lippo Karawaci Mall ||[[Tangerang]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Mangga Dua Square Mall ||[[North Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Pandeglang ||[[Pandeglang Regency]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Pasar Minggu Bus Terminal ||[[South Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Pondok Cabe ||[[South Tangerang]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Pramuka City ||[[Central Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Pulo Gebang ||[[East Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Purwakarta ||[[Purwakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Rawamangun Bus Terminal ||[[East Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Sentul City ||[[Bogor]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Serang\u2013Cilegon-Merak ||[[Banten]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Sukabumi ||[[Sukabumi]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Tanjung Priok Bus Terminal ||[[North Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || WTC Serpong ||[[South Tangerang]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:red;color:white;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Primajasa || Bandung Batununggal || [[Bandung]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:red;color:white;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Primajasa || Bandung Caringin || [[Bandung]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:yellow;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Hiba Utama || Depok Bus Terminal ||[[Depok]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:white;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Sinar Jaya || Cileungsi Bus Terminal ||[[Bogor Regency]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:red;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Redwhitestar || Bandung Gedungsate ||[[Bandung]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:red;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Primajasa  RWS|| Bandung Diponegoro32  || [[Bandung]]\n|}\n\n====JA Connexion Bus====\nGreater Jakarta Transportation Agency (BPTJ) operates this service, which uses air conditioned buses with comfortable seats and Wi-Fi.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2017/12/28/airport-bus-service-available-at-pondok-indah-mall.html|title=Airport bus service available at Pondok Indah Mall|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref> The routes are:\n* [[Hotel Borobudur]]-Hotel Alia-Hotel Luminor-Airport. \n* Hotel Aryaduta-Hotel Sari Pan Pacific-Airport.\n* Hotel Grand Cemara-Hotel Ibis Thamrin-Hotel Milenium-Airport.\n* Hotel Sahid Jaya-Mall Grand Indonesia-Hotel Ascot-Airport. \n* Hotel Amaris Thamrin City-Airport. \n* Hotel Sahid Jaya Lippo Cikarang-Airport. \n* Bogor Trade Mall-Airport. \n* Mall Taman Anggrek-Airport. \n* Mall Plaza Senayan-Airport. \n* Mall ITC Cempaka Mas-Airport. \n* Mall Kelapa Gading-Airport. \n* Pondok Indah Mall-Airport\n* Summarecon Serpong-Airport.\n* ITC Tanah Abang-Airport.\n* Bubulak-Bukit Cimanggu City(Bogor Icon)-Sentul-Airport\n* Pondok Gede (Transmart Atrium) - Airport.\n* Taman mini (Tamini Square) - Airport.\n\n====Inter-terminal shuttle service====\nSoekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport provides a free shuttle bus that connects Terminals 1, 2 and 3. The shuttle bus can be found at the arrival hall of Terminal 1A\u20131B\u20131C, on the eastern wing of the arrival hall of Terminal 2F and in front of the departure hall of Terminal 3.\n\n===Taxicab===\nThe airport is connected to Jakarta's city center via the [[Prof. Dr. Ir. Soedijatmo Toll Road]]. There is extensive car parking, including long-stay facilities, at the airport.\nVarious taxi and shuttle services are provided by several operators.\n\n===Rail===\n====Skytrain (inter-terminal shuttle service)====\n{{See also|Soekarno-Hatta Airport Skytrain}}\n{{Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport Skytrain}}\n[[File:Soetta Skytrain 8.jpg|thumb|left|Skytrain Automated People Mover for inter-terminal airport shuttle service]]\nThe plan to build an airport automated [[people mover]] system to connect Terminals 1, 2, and 3, and the Airport Rail Link Station, was announced in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://economy.okezone.com/read/2016/01/27/320/1298382/kereta-tanpa-masinis-di-bandara-soekarno-hatta-butuh-rp1-triliun |title=Kereta Tanpa Masinis di Bandara Soekarno\u2013Hatta Butuh Rp1 Triliun |author= Kurniasih Miftakhul Jannah |date=27 January 2016}}</ref> Starting on 17 September 2017, the people mover, named '''Skytrain''', is officially opened to connect Terminal 3 and Terminal 2 vice versa, with a [[headway]] of 5 minutes. One set of Skytrain can serve 2x88 passengers. It temporarily operates between 07.00\u201310.00, 13.00\u201314.00 and 17.00\u201319.00.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wartakota.tribunnews.com/2017/09/17/skytrain-bandara-soekarno-hatta-gratis |title=Skytrain Bandara Soekarno-Hatta Gratis |author=Yaspen Martinus |date=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Airport rail link====\n{{Soekarno-Hatta Airport Rail Link}}\n{{See also|Soekarno-Hatta Airport Rail Link}}\n[[Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport Rail Link]] connects [[Jakarta]] city center with the airport. The train takes 45\u201355 minutes from [[Manggarai railway station|Manggarai]] station at [[South Jakarta]] to SHIA station. Each train accommodates up to 272 passengers and will serve about 35,000 passengers with 122 trips a day, when fully operational.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://en.tempo.co/read/news/2017/02/26/056850395/Construction-of-Airport-Rail-Link-to-be-Completed-in-March-2017 |title=Construction of Airport Rail Link to be Completed in March 2017 |newspaper=Tempo|date=26 December 2017}}</ref> There is a 30 minutes interval between the train departures. As Manggarai station is under renovation, [[BNI City railway station|Sudirman Baru]] station is being temporary as the terminus for the city center.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.tempo.co/read/news/2016/12/06/056825670/Soekarno-Hatta-Airport-Train-to-Complete-by-June-2017 |title=Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport Train to Complete by June 2017 |date=26 December 2017}}</ref> The airport train currently makes 42 trips daily between 3.51 a.m. and 9.51 p.m., departing from [[BNI City railway station|Sudirman Baru]] station in to [[SHIA railway station|SHIA]], with a stop at [[Batuceper railway station|Batuceper]] station. Trips from Soekarno-Hatta to Sudirman Baru runs from 6.10 a.m. to 11.10 p.m., departing every hour.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2017/12/26/airport-train-kicks-off-services-with-promotional-fare.html|title=Airport train kicks off services with promotional fare|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref> The ticket price for the journey is IDR70 thousand (US$5). Passengers can only book train tickets using credit and debit cards, as well as electronic money via Railink app available for smartphones or vending machines at stations.\n\nAn express line between [[Halim Perdanakusuma Airport]] and the airport is under planning stage, to be built by an investor as a [[public\u2013private partnership]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/07/16/government-pegs-pt-kai-airport-railway-development.html|title=Government pegs PT KAI for airport railway development|publisher=|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/12/09/kai-airport-train-ready-2013.html |title=KAI: Airport train ready in 2013 |date=9 December 2011}}</ref> The express train will take 30 minutes to connect the airports.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bisnis.liputan6.com/read/799301/ada-kereta-ekspress-dari-bandara-halim-ke-soetta-hanya-30-menit?wp.bsns |title=Ada Kereta Ekspress, Dari Bandara Halim ke Soetta Hanya 30 Menit |date=13 January 2014}}</ref> In early 2015, the government changed the fund from participation to not funding at all, so the contract for Rp 28 billion will be revised, including new rail express tariff. The construction of this line has been delayed and completion is now projected to be in 2019 at the earliest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.beritasatu.com/aktualitas/241986-pemerintah-kaji-ulang-kontrak-ka-ekspres-halimsoetta.html |title=Pemerintah Kaji Ulang Kontrak KA Ekspres Halim-Soetta |date=19 January 2015}}</ref>\n<!-- don't put plans here, there's another article about airport plans in the history section. All article here has been moved to there -->\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n* On 28 October 1997, a [[Trigana Air Service]] [[Fokker F-28 Fellowship|Fokker F-28 Fellowship 3000]] passenger plane returned to land at Jakarta\u2013Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport after the aircraft experienced technical problems two minutes after takeoff. Smoke and severe heat had entered the cockpit and the passenger cabin. The airplane sustained damage due to the heat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19971028-1|title=ASN Aircraft accident Fokker F-28 Fellowship 3000 PK-YPT Jakarta\u2013Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport (CGK)|author=Harro Ranter|date=28 October 1997|publisher=|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n* On 23 January 2003, a [[Star Air (Indonesia)|Star Air]] [[Boeing 737]] touched down {{convert|500|m|ft|sp=us}} past the threshold of runway 25L, a little left of the centerline, at a time of heavy rainfall with associated heavy winds. It went off the side of the runway, causing substantial damage to the aircraft's undercarriage and belly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20030123-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Boeing 737-2B7 PK-ALV Jakarta\u2013Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport (CGK)|author=Harro Ranter|date=23 January 2003|publisher=|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n* 2003 Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport bombing \u2013 On 27 April 2003, a bomb exploded in terminal 2, departure hall of the domestic terminal. The bomb was hidden under a table of a [[KFC]] stall and exploded during lunch hours. 10 people were injured in the blast, one 17-year-old teenager identified as Yuli was seriously injured. Her legs had to be amputated. Emergency services were rushed to the scene and suspected that the motive of the bombing was due to the [[Free Aceh Movement]], a separatist movement in Aceh. This was proved by the location of the blast, which was located on the domestic passenger hall rather than on the international passenger hall.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sebuah Ledakan Mengguncang Bandara Soekarno\u2013Hatta|url=http://news.liputan6.com/read/53646/sebuah-ledakan-mengguncang-bandara-soekarno-hatta}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bom Bandara Soekarno\u2013Hatta Memutuskan Kaki Yuli|url=http://news.liputan6.com/read/53647/bom-bandara-soekarno-hatta-memutuskan-kaki-yuli}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\tApa Pesan Peledakan Bom di Bandara Soekarno\u2013Hatta|work=Unisosdem.org|url=http://www.unisosdem.org/article_detail.php?aid=1737&coid=3&caid=22&gid=1|accessdate=20 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920092814/http://www.unisosdem.org/article_detail.php?aid=1737&coid=3&caid=22&gid=1|archivedate=20 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.liputan6.com/read/53650/bom-di-bandara-diduga-terkait-kasus-aceh|title=Bom di Bandara Diduga Terkait Kasus Aceh|work=Liputan6.com|date=27 April 2003|accessdate=20 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918162500/http://news.liputan6.com/read/53650/bom-di-bandara-diduga-terkait-kasus-aceh|archivedate=18 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* On 11 August 2003, a [[Garuda Indonesia]] Fokker F-28 Fellowship 3000R suffered a left main gear collapse after a flight from [[Surabaya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20030811-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Fokker F-28 Fellowship 3000R PK-GFT Jakarta\u2013Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport (CGK)|author=Harro Ranter|date=11 August 2003|publisher=|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n* On 9 March 2009, a [[Lion Air]] [[MD-90]] overran runway 25L, due to an unstable approach {{convert|100|m|ft|sp=us}} before the runway in rainfall and strong winds, in which the aircraft touched down to the left of the centerline. Although its thrust reversers were functioning, it veered to the right, resulting in the aircraft resting 90 degrees off the runway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20090309-1|title=ASN Aircraft accident McDonnell Douglas MD-90-30 PK-LIL Jakarta Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport (CGK)|author=Harro Ranter|date=9 March 2009|publisher=|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1995, the landscaping of Soekarno\u2013Hatta airport was awarded by [[Aga Khan Award for Architecture]] as one of the best examples of integrating the terminal building pavilions, with lush tropical garden harmoniously.<ref>{{cite web | title = Landscaping of Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport | work = Aga Khan Award for Architecture | year = 1993\u20131995 | url = http://www.akdn.org/architecture/project/landscaping-soekarno-hatta-airport |accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nSoekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport was ranked fourth on the [[Skytrax]] World's Most Improved Airport 2014 list based on surveys of 12.85 million passengers from 110 countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jabar.tribunnews.com/2014/04/01/soekarno-hatta-peringkat-empat-the-worlds-most-improved-airport |title=Soekarno\u2013Hatta Peringkat Empat The World's Most Improved Airport |author=Sakina Rakhma Diah Setiawan |work=Tribun Jabar |date=1 April 2014 |accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref> [[Skytrax]] also ranked Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport as a 3-Star Airport.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jakarta Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport Quality Rating|url=http://www.airlinequality.com/ratings/jakarta-soekarno-hatta-airport-quality-rating/|publisher=Skytrax|accessdate=4 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport was ranked first on the [[Skytrax]] World's Most Improved Airport 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.airlinequality.com/news/best-airports-of-2017-unveiled-at-world-airport-awards/|title=Best airports of 2017 unveiled at World Airport Awards |publisher=Airline & Airport Reviews and Ratings (Skytrax) |date=14 March 2017|access-date=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Soekarno\u2013Hatta declared World\u2019s Most Improved Airport|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2017/03/15/soekarno-hatta-declared-worlds-most-improved-airport.html|accessdate=16 March 2017|work=The Jakarta Post|date=15 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Sukarno hatta airport - Entrance - Jakarta - Indonesia.jpg|The former main entrance gate at [[Prof. Dr. Ir. Soedijatmo Toll Road]]\nFile:Soekarno-hatta statue.JPG|The former site of the statue of Soekarno and Mohammad Hatta\nFile:Sukarno hatta airport - Terminal - Jakarta - Indonesia.jpg|Terminal 2\nFile:Sukarno hatta airport - Tower - Jakarta - Indonesia.jpg |Tower\nFile:CGK T2 waiting pavillon.jpg|Terminal building with gardens\nFile:check in hall.JPG|Check in desks in terminal 2\nSoekarno-Hatta T2 Gate Lounge 2.JPG |Gate lounge in terminal 2\nFile:terminal2cgk2.jpg|Baggage claim at terminal 2\nFile:Soetta Arrival Hall 2F.jpg|Arrival Hall terminal 2F\nFile:Soekarno-Hatta International Airport Terminal 3 front.JPG|The old Terminal 3\nFile:CGK Terminal 3 7.jpg|Dropoff bays at the departure area of Terminal 3.\nFile:CGK Terminal 3 9.jpg|Welcome signage at the arrival area of Terminal 3.\nFile:CGK Terminal 3 11.jpg|Directional signage at the departure area of Terminal 3.\nFile:CGK Terminal 3 14.jpg|A view of the Terminal 3 building.\nFile:CGK Terminal 2.jpg|The airport welcome sign along the tarmac in front of Terminal 2\nFile:CGK_Terminal_3_8.jpg|The luggage carousels at the arrival area of Terminal 3.\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Indonesia}}\n*{{Portal-inline|Jakarta}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Aviation}}\n{{Portal|Jakarta|Indonesia|Aviation}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Soekarno-Hatta International Airport}}\n{{wikivoyage|Soekarno-Hatta International Airport}}\n* [http://www.soekarnohatta-airport.co.id Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport]\n* {{WAD|WIII|source=[[DAFIF]]}}\n* {{GCM|CGK|source=[[DAFIF]]}}\n* {{NWS-current|WIII}}\n* {{ASN|CGK}}\n* [https://soundcloud.com/suarakecil/soekarno-hatta-airport Sound recording from inside Soekarno\u2013Hatta airport]\n\n{{Airports in Indonesia}}\n{{Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soekarno-Hatta International Airport}}\n[[Category:Airports established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Airports in Jakarta]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Banten]]\n[[Category:Infrastructure in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Transport in Banten]]\n[[Category:1985 establishments in Indonesia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name = Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport\n| nativename = {{lang|id|<small>Bandar Udara Internasional Soekarno\u2013Hatta</small>}}\n| image = Soekarno-Hatta International Airport.png\n| image2 = Soekarno-Hatta Airport aerial view.jpg|\n| image-width = 250\n| image2-width = 250\n| caption2 = \n| location = [[Tangerang]], [[Banten]]\n| hub = * [[Batik Air]]\n* [[Cardig Air]]\n* [[Citilink]]\n* [[Garuda Indonesia]]\n* [[Indonesia AirAsia]]\n* [[Lion Air]]\n* [[Nam Air]]\n* [[Sriwijaya Air]]\n* [[AirAsia]]\n| focus_city = \n| elevation-m = 10\n| metric-elev = \n| pushpin_label = '''CGK'''/WIII\n| r1-length-f = 12,008\n| r1-surface = Concrete\n| metric-rwy = \n| IATA = CGK\n| ICAO = WIII\n| WMO = 96749\n| type = Public\n| owner = [[Government of Indonesia]]\n| operator = [[Angkasa Pura|PT Angkasa Pura II]]\n| city-served = [[Jakarta metropolitan area]]\n| opened = {{start date|df=yes|1985|05|01}}\n| elevation-f = 32\n| coordinates = {{coord|6|07|32|S|106|39|21|E|region:ID-BT|display=it}}\n| website = http://www.soekarnohatta-airport.co.id/\n| image_map = Java Locator.svg\n| image_map_caption = [[Java]] region in Indonesia\n| pushpin_map = Jakarta Metropolitan Area#Indonesia Java#Indonesia#Southeast Asia#Asia\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location of airport in [[Banten]] , [[Indonesia]]\n| r1-number = 07R/25L \n| r1-length-m = 3,660\n| r2-number = 07L/25R \n| r2-length-f = 11,811\n| r2-length-m = 3,600\n| r2-surface = Asphalt Concrete\n| r3-number = 06/24\n| r3-length-f = 9,843\n| r3-length-m = 3,000\n| r3-surface = Asphalt Concrete\n| stat-year = 2018\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data = 66,908,159 {{increase}} 6.2% <ref>{{cite web|url=https://aci.aero/news/2019/03/13/preliminary-world-airport-traffic-rankings-released/|title=Preliminary world airport traffic rankings released}}</ref>\n| stat2-header = Aircraft Movements\n| stat2-data = 447,390 {{increase}} 8%\n| stat3-header = Cargo (metric tonnes)\n| stat3-data = 953,606 {{increase}} 16.73% <ref>{{cite web|url=https://cms.angkasapura2.co.id/NUWEB_PUBLIC_FILES/angkasapura2/Annual_01_05_2019__10_15_07.pdf|title=Annual Report 2018}}</ref>\n| stat4-header = Economic & Social impact\n| stat4-data = {{nowrap|$5.1 billion & 705 thousand<ref name=CGK_ESI>{{cite web |url=http://www.ecquants.com/2012_CGK.aspx |title=Soekarno\u2013Hatta International airport \u2013 Economic and social impacts |publisher=Ecquants |accessdate=14 September 2013}}</ref><!--end nowrap:-->}}\n| footnotes = Source: [[List of the busiest airports in Indonesia]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.angkasapura2.co.id/en/informasi/berita-detail/bandara-changi-terbaik-soetta-berkembang-pesat-1240|title=Bandara Changi Terbaik, Soetta Berkembang Pesat - PT Angkasa Pura II|last=(Persero)|first=PT Angkasa Pura II|website=www.angkasapura2.co.id|access-date=18 March 2017}}</ref> Passenger and Aircraft Movements from [[Airports Council International|ACI]]<ref name=\"stats\">{{cite web|url=http://www.aci.aero/media/afc782a2-a258-4c49-a700-fea9047d15fb/News/Releases/2013/PR_260313_Prelim_2012_World_Traffic_Rankings-final_pdf|title=Preliminary 2012 World Airport Traffic and Rankings|publisher=Airports Council International|date=26 March 2013}}</ref> <br>Cargo from Angkasa Pura II Airports Company<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.angkasapura2.co.id/commercial/?CdAirport=CGK|title=Halaman Tidak Ditemukan \u2013 PT Angkasa Pura II|author=PT Angkasa Pura II (Persero)|work=PT Angkasa Pura II (Persero)|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport''' ({{lang-id|Bandar Udara Internasional Soekarno\u2013Hatta}}) {{Airport codes|CGK|WIII}}, abbreviated '''SHIA'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mediaindonesia.com/read/2011/05/17/226706/4/2/Bandara-Soekarno-Hatta-Raih-Dua-Penghargaan|title=Bandara Soekarno Hatta Raih Dua Penghargaan|publisher=Media Indonesia|date=17 May 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110522081641/http://www.mediaindonesia.com/read/2011/05/17/226706/4/2/Bandara-Soekarno-Hatta-Raih-Dua-Penghargaan|archivedate=22 May 2011}}</ref> or '''Soetta''' or [[Cengkareng]] airport ({{lang-id|Bandara Cengkareng}}) (hence the [[IATA]] designator \"CGK\"),<!--<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.okezone.com/read/2011/01/05/337/410506/singkatan-bandara-soetta-lecehkan-proklamator|title=Singkatan Bandara Soetta Lecehkan Proklamator|publisher=Okezone.com|date=5 January 2011|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>--> is the primary airport serving the [[Jakarta metropolitan area]] on the island of [[Java]] in [[Indonesia]]. Named after the first president and vice-president of Indonesia, [[Soekarno]] and [[Mohammad Hatta]], the airport is located at [[Benda, Tangerang]], which is about 20&nbsp;km northwest of [[Central Jakarta]]. Together with [[Halim Perdanakusuma International Airport]], they served over 80 million passengers in 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2018/01/07/soekarno-hatta-airport-serves-63m-passengers-in-2017.html|title=Soekarno-Hatta airport serves 63m passengers in 2017|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=7 January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe airport commenced domestic operations on 1 May 1985 replacing the old over-capacity [[Kemayoran Airport]]. The airport was expanded in 1991 to replace [[Halim Perdanakusuma International Airport]] for international flights, which still serves domestic charter, VIP, private flights, and re-opened as a second commercial airport for domestic flights to relieve pressure over Soekarno-Hatta airport that is currently running overcapacity. The airport served 66.9 million passengers in 2018, ranked as [[List of busiest airports by passenger traffic|18th busiest airport]] in the world by [[Airports Council International]], and the busiest in Southeast Asia.<ref>{{cite news|URL=https://edition.cnn.com/travel/article/worlds-busiest-airports-2018-preliminary/index.html|title=This is the world's busiest airport|newspaper=CNN|accessdate=18 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indonesia-investments.com/business/business-columns/jakarta-s-soekarno-hatta-international-airport-world-s-8th-busiest-airport/item1674?|title= Jakarta\u2019s Soekarno-Hatta International Airport World\u2019s 8th Busiest Airport|accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref> According to air travel intelligence company [[OAG (company)|OAG]], the airport ranked as the 7th most connected airport in the world, and ranked first as '[[Airline hub|megahub]]' airport in Asia-Pacific region as per connectivity index, ahead of Japan's [[Tokyo Haneda Airport]] and Australia's [[Sydney Airport]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2016/12/03/soekarno-hatta-named-asia-pacifics-most-connected-airport.html |title=Soekarno-Hatta named Asia-Pacific's most connected airport |date=3 December 2016}}</ref> The airport ranked as the 7th most connected airport as '[[Airline hub|megahub]]' in the world in 2017 again by air travel intelligence company [[OAG (Air Travel Intelligence)|OAG]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2017/10/07/soekarno-hatta-among-worlds-largest-megahub-airports-in-2017.html|title=Soekarno-Hatta among world's largest megahub airports in 2017|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=7 October 2017}}</ref> The airport ranked as the 2nd most connected Low-Cost Megahub airport as '[[Airline hub|megahub]]'  in the world in 2018 by air travel intelligence company [[OAG (Air Travel Intelligence)|OAG]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com.my/business/business-news/2018/09/19/asia-pacific-leading-airports-perform-strongly-on-the-oag-megahub-international-index-2018/|title=Asia Pacific's leading airports perform strongly on the OAG Megahub International Index 2018|newspaper=The Star|accessdate=24 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe airport often struggles to accommodate all flights at its current limit of 81 aircraft movements per hour.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2017/07/27/flight-frequency-increased-to-meet-increasing-demand-minister.html|title=Flight frequency increased to meet increasing demand: Minister|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=28 July 2017}}</ref> Although overcapacity, after a survey [[Airport Council International|ACI]] in 2012 declared that Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport is being operated safely.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://megapolitan.kompas.com/read/2012/05/04/2122363/ACI|title=ACI: Soekarno-Hatta Aman dan Laik Operasi}}</ref> The two existing runways suffer from pavement and strength issues, which limits the airport's capacity to serve large aircraft. To reduce congestion and to achieve a target to handle 100 flights/hour, the third runway opened in August 2019. Upgrades of the existing two runways for safety and to accommodate wide-bodied aircraft are almost complete .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2016/06/13/soekarno-hattas-3rd-runway-to-be-constructed-in-2017.html|title=Soekarno-Hatta's 3rd runway to be constructed in 2017}}</ref> The airport will be able to serve 100 million passengers annually by 2025 after completion of ongoing development work.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2018/04/16/soekarno-hatta-airport-to-serve-100m-passengers-in-2025.html|title=Soekarno-Hatta airport to serve 100m passengers in 2025|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=16 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nUsed between 1928 and 1985, [[Kemayoran Airfield]] was considered unsatisfactory{{when|date=May 2014}} because it was too close to the major [[Halim Perdanakusuma International Airport|Halim Perdanakusuma]] Indonesian military airport. The civil airspace in the area became increasingly restricted, while air traffic increased rapidly, posing problems for international air traffic. In 1969, a senior communication officers meeting in [[Bangkok]] expressed these concerns.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}} [[File:Jakarta Airport Dept area.jpg|thumb|Departure area at Terminal 2]]\n\nIn the early 1970s, with the help of [[USAID]], eight potential locations were analyzed for a new international airport, namely [[Kemayoran]], Malaka, [[Babakan]], [[Jonggol]], [[Halim Perdanakusuma Airport|Halim]], [[Curug, Tangerang|Curug]], [[South Tangerang]] and North Tangerang.{{Citation needed|date=July 2013}} Finally, the North Tangerang site was chosen; it was also noted that Jonggol could be used as an alternative airfield. Meanwhile, as an interim step, the Indonesian government upgraded the Halim Perdanakusuma airfield for use for passenger services. The old Kemayoran site was closed in 1985, and the land was later used for commercial and housing purposes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jakarta.go.id/eng/news/2012/08/kemayoran-tower|title=Kemayoran Tower \u2013 News|publisher=Department of Communication, Informatics and Public Relations of Jakarta Capital City|date=28 August 2012|accessdate=4 June 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150220043406/http://www.jakarta.go.id/eng/news/2012/08/kemayoran-tower|archivedate=20 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1974 and 1975, a [[Canada|Canadian]] consortium, consisting of Aviation Planning Services Ltd., ACRESS International Ltd., and Searle Wilbee Rowland (SWR), won a bid for the new airport feasibility project. The feasibility study started on 20 February 1974, with a total cost of 1 million [[Canadian dollars]]. The one-year project proceeded with an Indonesian partner represented by PT Konavi. By the end of March 1975, the study revealed a plan to build three inline runways, three international terminal buildings, three domestic buildings, and one building for [[Hajj]] flights. Three stores for the domestic terminals would be built between 1975 and 1981 at a cost of [[US$]]465 million and one domestic terminal including an apron from 1982\u20131985 at a cost of US$126 million. A new terminal project, named the Jakarta International Airport Cengkareng, began.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.angkasa-online.com/12/04/lain/lain12.htm|title=Riwayat Pembangunan Cengkareng|magazine=Angkasa|issue=4|date=January 2002|accessdate=18 August 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020122074831/http://www.angkasa-online.com/12/04/lain/lain12.htm|archivedate=22 January 2002|language=id}}</ref>\n\n===Design===\n[[File:Soekarno-Hatta T2 Garden.JPG|thumb|Tropical gardens fill the spaces between Javanese-styled [[pendopo]] waiting and boarding pavilions.]]\nThe airport's terminal 1 and 2 were designed by [[Paul Andreu]], a French architect who also designed [[Paris\u2013Charles de Gaulle Airport]]. One of the characteristics of the airport is the incorporation of the local architecture into the design and the presence of tropical gardens between the waiting lounges. These unique characteristics earned the airport the 1995 [[Aga Khan Award for Architecture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.akdn.org/agency/akaa/sixthcycle/indonesia.html|title=Aga Khan Award for Architecture \u2013 The Sixth Award Cycle, 1993\u20131995|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020615033619/http://www.akdn.org/agency/akaa/sixthcycle/indonesia.html|archivedate=15 June 2002}}</ref> The runways run northeast-southwest. There are two parallel runways, on the north and south side. The airport terminal took the plan of spanning fan, with the main entrances of terminals connected to a series of waiting and boarding pavilions via corridors. These waiting and boarding pavilions are connected to the airplanes through [[jet bridge|boarding bridges]]. Terminal 1 is on the southern side of the airport, while Terminal 2 and 3 are on the north side.\n\nThe airport concept is described as \"garden within the airport\" or \"airport in the garden\", as tropical decorative and flower plants fill the spaces between corridors, waiting and boarding pavilions. The boarding pavilions demonstrate local [[Indonesian architecture|Indonesian vernacular architecture]], particularly the roof, in the [[Java]]nese stepped-roof ''[[pendopo]]'' and ''[[joglo]]'' style. The interior design displays the diversity of Indonesian art and culture, with ethnic decorative elements taken from wooden carvings of Java, Bali, Sumatra, Dayak, [[Toraja]] to Papua. Another example is the railings of stairs, doors, and gates, which show the [[kala (time)|kala]]-[[Makara (Hindu mythology)|makara]] (giant head and mythical fish-elephant creature) theme typical in [[Candi of Indonesia#Kala-Makara|ancient Indonesian temples]] such as [[Borobudur]]. Terminal 3, however, has a different architectural style\u2014unlike the ethnic-inspired Indonesian vernacular architecture of terminals 1 and 2, terminal 3 uses the contemporary modern style of large glass windows with metal frames and columns.\n\n===Project phases===\n[[File:Soekarno-Hatta Garuda Ticket Box.JPG|thumb|Soekarno\u2013Hatta ticket office ( Not available from 1 March 2015 )]]\n\nTime was needed to allocate land and also determine the provincial border.{{clarify|date=May 2014}} Authorities at [[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol]] were consulted about the airport plans, and concluded that the proposal was rather expensive and over-designed. The cost rose because of using a decentralized system. The centralized system was seen as a more suitable option. The team, however, chose the latter, similar to [[Orly Airport]], [[Lyon Satolas Airport|Lyon Satolas]], [[Hannover Airport]] and [[Kansas City International Airport|Kansas City Airport]] due to its simplicity and effectiveness.\n\nOn 12 November 1976, the building project tender was won by the French Aeroport de Paris. 6 months later, the final design was agreed on by the Indonesian government and Aeroport de Paris with a fixed cost of about 22,323,203 French francs and Rp. 177,156,000 equivalent to 2,100,000 francs. The work was scheduled to take 18 months. The government-appointed PT. Konavi as the local partner. The plan included 2 runways with taxiways, one access road in the east and one in the west (closed to public use) for airport services, 3 terminals capable of accommodating 3 million passengers per year, and 1 module for international flights and 2 for domestic. \"An airport inside a garden\" was chosen as the design idea.\n\nOn 20 May 1980, a four-year contract was signed. Sainraptet Brice, SAE, Colas together with PT. Waskita Karya were chosen to be the developers. Ir. [[Karno Barkah]] was appointed the project director, responsible for the airport's construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ahmad.web.id/sites/apa_dan_siapa_tempo/profil/K/20030623-38-K_2.html|title=Apa dan Siapa \u2013 KARNO BARKAH|publisher=Tempo|via=Ahmad.web.id}}</ref> On 1 December 1980, the Indonesian government signed a contract for Rp. 384.8 billion with developers. The cost structure was: Rp140,450,513,000 from the state budget, 1,223,457 francs donated by France and US$15,898,251 from the United States. The airport structure was completed exactly four years later. It was finally opened on 1 May 1985 for domestic flights, and the second circular terminal was opened exactly six years later for international operations.{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border: #999 solid 1px; text-align: lcenter; margin-bottom: 0; margin: 1em auto 1em auto\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"5\" style=\"background: #8B8589;\" | '''Phases of Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport Project'''\n|- style=\"font-weight:bold; background:#d3d3d3;\"\n|-\n!Phase!!Year!!Description!!Status\n|-\n|Phase 1||1 May 1985|| Opening of Terminal 1 with a capacity of 9 million passengers per annum||Completed\n|-\n|Phase 2||11 May 1991||Opening of Terminal 2 with a capacity of 18 million passengers per annum||Completed\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Phase 3|| rowspan=\"2\" |15 Apr 2009||Construction of Terminal 3 phase 1 with a capacity of 22 million passengers per annum||Completed\n|-\n|Fully built new Freight Terminal (on northwest section)||In progress\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |Phase 4|| rowspan=\"6\" |9 Aug 2016||Completion of Terminal 3 with a capacity of 43 million passengers per annum||Completed\n|-\n|Construction of Airport Railway ||Completed\n|-\n|Construction of third runway ||Completed\n|-\n|Fully built integrated building{{clarify|date=May 2014}}||In Progress\n|-\n|Additional 500m to the third runway ||Completed\n|-\n|Construction of Terminal 4<ref>{{cite web|url=https://seasia.co/2018/01/31/runway-3-terminal-4-to-add-capacity-of-jakarta-airport|title=Runway 3, Terminal 4 to Add Capacity of Jakarta Airport|publisher=seasia.co|author=Akhyari Hananto}}</ref> ||Designing<ref>{{cite web|url=https://money.kompas.com/read/2019/12/28/152800426/desain-terminal-4-bandara-soekarno-hatta-mulai-dirancang|title=Desain Terminal 4 Bandara Soekarno-Hatta Mulai Dirancang}}</ref>\n|-\n|Phase 5||2022||Refurbishment of Terminal 1 & Terminal 2 to increase capacity to 61 million passengers per annum||In progress\n|}\n\n===Plans===\nThe capacity of the airport has increased from 22 million in 2014 to 62 million in 2017, but the airport handled more than 63 million passengers in 2017. Therefore, plans to build the fourth passenger terminal is already underway. [[Angkasa Pura|Angkasa Pura II]], as the operator, designed Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport to have 3 passenger terminals, 1 new freight terminal (cargo village) and an 'Integrated Building', that will be built in between Terminal 1 and 2. Also, there will be an increase in apron capacity from 125 airplanes to 174 airplanes.\n\nAn airport train to [[Manggarai Station]] and a [[people mover]] for ground transportation to, from and inside the airport were also planned. The free Skytrain began operations in September 2017 while the airport train started commercial service in December 2017.\n\nIn the first stage, Terminal 3 will be expanded. Terminal 1 and Terminal 2 will be integrated with green walls{{clarify|date=May 2014}} and the airport will have a convention hall, shopping center, hotel, playground, recreational facilities and parking area for 20,000 vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/07/25/jakarta\u2019s-airport-be-world-class-\u2018aerotropolis\u2019.html |title=Jakarta\u2019s airport to be world-class \u2018aerotropolis\u2019 |date=25 July 2011 |work=The Jakarta Post |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304093018/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/07/25/jakarta%E2%80%99s-airport-be-world-class-%E2%80%98aerotropolis%E2%80%99.html |archivedate=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nTo anticipate a surge in passenger numbers, at least a ten percent increase each year, the government made plans to build a third runway. By May 2019 the construction progress reached 70 percent. 2500 meters of the runway began operational on 15 August 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/news/articles/soekarno-hatta-third-runway-enters-service-460310/|title=Soekarno-Hatta third runway enters service|author=Ellis Taylor|date=August 16, 2019}}</ref> The third runway will be expanded to 3000 metres by the end of 2019. With the opening of the third runway, capacity was increased to 114 flights per hour, up from 81 flights per hour.\n\nInitially, Angkasa Pura II planned for an expansion that will use about {{convert|1000|ha|acres}} from 10 villages in the Teluk Naga and [[Kosambi]] subdistricts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/04/07/govt-prepares-soekarno-hatta-airport-expansion.html|title=Govt prepares Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport expansion|work=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://koran-jakarta.com/index.php/detail/view01/83180 |title=Bandara Soeta Butuh Investasi Rp11,7 Triliun |date=10 February 2012}}</ref> The expansion plan was rejected by the Tangerang Municipal Government because the residents living around the airport would lose their jobs. The local government offered another location such as in [[Balaraja]], but Angkasa Pura II corporate secretary said that building a new airport would not be an easy task, as it requires a thorough study.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/08/04/tangerang-rejects-soekarno-hatta-airport-expansion-plan.html|title=Tangerang rejects Soekarno\u2013Hatta airport expansion plan|work=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref> Finally, Angkasa Pura II only used 134 hectares of land and appraisal will be used to buy the land.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wartakota.tribunnews.com/2016/10/14/sebanyak-2459-bidang-di-tangerang-tegusur-terkait-pembangunan-runway-3-bandara |title=Sebanyak 2.459 Bidang di Tangerang Tegusur, Terkait Pembangunan Runway 3 Bandara |date=14 October 2016}}</ref> It can be done due to a new design for the third runway.\n\nTo accommodate 86 aircraft movements per hour from the current 72 movements per hour, since 2016 the airport authority has been developing an east cross taxiway costing Rp 1,150 billion ($86.1 million) to connect the existing Runway 1 and Runway 2.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://news.detik.com/berita/d-3418450/2-runway-bandara-cengkareng-akan-dihubungkan-lewat-timur |title=2 Runway Bandara Cengkareng Akan Dihubungkan Lewat Timur |author=Rina Atriana |date=9 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Terminals==\nThere are three main terminal buildings; Terminal 1, Terminal 2 and Terminal 3. The airport also has a dedicated freight terminal for domestic and international cargo.\n\nAfter renovations and expansions of Terminal 3, the current capacity of Soekarno\u2013Hatta is 51 million,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://interaktif.print.kompas.com/terminal_3|title=Selamat Datang di Gerbang Indonesia|work=[[Kompas.com]]|accessdate=2 October 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160921202532/http://interaktif.print.kompas.com/terminal_3|archivedate=21 September 2016}}</ref> but the airport served 54 million passengers in 2015, making it the 18th busiest airport in the world, and the busiest airport in the [[Southern Hemisphere]]. There are non-stop flights to a large number of destinations in Asia and Australia, and several flights to Europe daily, ranking as the 17th most connected airport in the world, and the largest megahub in Asia according to OAG.<ref>{{cite news|title= Soekarno\u2013Hatta airport named Asia's largest megahub |newspaper=The Jakarta Post |location=Jakarta |date=6 October 2015 |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2015/10/06/soekarno-hatta-airport-named-asias-largest-megahub.html }}</ref>\n\nTerminal 1 and Terminal 2 are currently under renovation, which will cost Rp 3.2 trillion ($235.2 million). The renovation works is targeted to be completed by 2021. The revitalization project is expected to double the number of passengers of the two terminals up to 36 million a year.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://jakartaglobe.id/business/ap-ii-spend-rp-3-2t-soekarno-hatta-airport-revitalization/|title=AP II to Spend Rp 3.2t on Soekarno-Hatta Airport Revitalization|newspaper=Jakarta Globe|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref> Terminal 1 caters to domestic [[Low cost carrier]], while Terminal 2 caters to international [[Low cost carriers]]. Terminal 3 will become a full-service terminal for both domestic and international flights.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2018/08/10/soekarno-hatta-airports-terminal-1-2-converted-into-lcc-terminals.html|title= Soekarno-Hatta Airport\u2019s Terminal 1, 2 converted into LCC terminals|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=10 August 2018}}</ref> The airport operator AP II has undertaken plan to build a fourth terminal at Soekarno-Hatta, which is expected to be completed by 2024.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/land-acquisition-for-new-soetta-runway-in-inodnesia-stays-on-track |title=Land acquisition for new Soetta runway in Indonesia stays on track|newspaper=The Straits Time|accessdate=11 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Terminal 1===\nTerminal 1 is the first terminal built and was opened in 1985. It is located on the southern side of the airport, opposite Terminal 2. Terminal 1 has 3 sub-terminals, each equipped with 25 check-in counters, 5 baggage carousels, and 7 gates. It has the capacity to handle 9 million passengers per annum.\n\nThe gates in Terminal 1 have a prefix of A, B or C. The gates are A1\u2013A7, B1\u2013B7 and C1\u2013C7. In the latest masterplan, Terminal 1 will have its capacity increased to 18 million passengers per annum. Terminal 1 is used for domestic flights except for those operated by [[Garuda Indonesia]], [[Sriwijaya Air]], [[NAM Air]], [[Indonesia AirAsia]]. Terminal 1A is home to [[Lion Air]] domestic flights (except to [[Sumatra]] & [[Bali]]). Terminal 1B is home to [[Lion Air]] domestic flights (only to [[Sumatra]] and [[Bali]]). Terminal 1C is home to [[Citilink]] (domestic flights) and [[Trigana Air Service]]. The terminal was converted into a domestic [[Low-cost carrier terminal|low-cost carrier terminal (LCCT)]] in 2019.\n\n===Terminal 2===\n[[File:CGK T2 check in.jpg|thumb|Check In Area Terminal 2]]\nTerminal 2 is the second terminal built, and was opened in 1991. It is located on the north-western side of the airport, opposite Terminal 1. Like Terminal 1, it has three sub-terminals, labeled as D, E and F, each of which has seven gates and 25 check-in counters. Terminal 2 caters to umrah (minor haj) flights and was converted into an international [[Low cost carrier terminal|low-cost carrier terminal (LCCT)]] in 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2018/07/23/soekarno-hattas-terminal-2-to-be-used-for-low-cost-carriers.html|title=Soekarno-Hatta's Terminal 2 to be used for low-cost carriers|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=23 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2018/02/07/international-flights-to-move-to-soekarno-hatta-terminal-3-by-may.html|title=International flights to move to Soekarno-Hatta Terminal 3 by May|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=20 June 2018}}</ref> Currently, Terminal 2 Domestic (2D & 2E) is home to [[Sriwijaya Air]], [[Nam Air]], [[Indonesia AirAsia]], and [[Batik Air]]'s domestic flights, while Terminal 2 International (2F) is an international LCCT for [[AirAsia]], [[Indonesia AirAsia]], [[Thai AirAsia]], [[Sriwijaya Air]], [[Lion Air]], [[Malindo Air|Malindo]], [[Thai Lion Air]], [[Citilink]], [[Jetstar Asia Airways]], [[Cebu Pacific]] and [[Scoot]] international flights.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2019/08/13/2019-list-of-all-airlines-operating-at-soekarno-hatta-airport.html|title=2019 list of all airlines operating at Soekarno-Hatta airport|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.tribunnews.com/amp/bisnis/2019/04/26/mulai-1-mei-terminal-2f-bandara-soekarno-hatta-hanya-untuk-penerbangan-lcc|title=Mulai 1 Mei, Terminal 2F Bandara Soekarno-Hatta Hanya untuk Penerbangan LCC|newspaper=Tribun News|accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Terminal 3===\n{{Main|Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport Terminal 3}}\n[[File:CGK Terminal 3 13.jpg|thumb|right|The departure lounge at Terminal 3.]]\n\nTerminal 3 is the airport's newest and largest terminal. It is used as a base for Garuda Indonesia and serves as a full-service terminal for both international and domestic flights.\n\nThe original Terminal 3 was officially opened for international flights on 15 November 2011, when all [[Indonesia AirAsia]] flights started using Terminal 3 as its new base for international, as well as domestic flights. It was built to cater to low-cost carriers. The terminal was located on the north-eastern side of the airport.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.destinasian.com/airline-news/airasia/airasia-jakarta-terminal-3/ |title=In Jakarta AirAsia Routes All Flights to Terminal 3 |date=16 November 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 August 2016, a new passenger terminal named 'Terminal 3 Ultimate', was officially opened. The original Terminal 3 was revamped and integrated into the new Terminal 3 Ultimate. The terminal was built at a cost of 4.7 trillion rupiah. It has a floor area of {{convert|422804|m2|abbr=on|sp=us}} and was built to handle 25 million passengers per annum. Unlike Terminal 1 and 2, the Terminal 3 Ultimate architectural style is vastly different, using an eco-friendly contemporary modern design.<ref>[http://finance.detik.com/read/2016/06/04/094523/3225351/4/jadi-hadiah-lebaran-bagaimana-persiapan-terminal-3-ultimate-bandara-soetta Jadi Hadiah Lebaran, Bagaimana Persiapan Terminal 3 Ultimate Bandara Soetta?] www.detik.com</ref> It is equipped with 10 international gates, 18 domestic gates, 112 check-in counters, 41 aerobridges and 10 bus gates.<ref>[http://finance.detik.com/read/2016/04/21/170247/3193572/4/penumpang-tiba-di-terminal-3-ultimate-tak-akan-kehujanan-dan-kepanasan-kenapa Penumpang Tiba di Terminal 3 Ultimate Tak Akan Kehujanan dan Kepanasan, Kenapa?] www.detik.com</ref><ref>[http://www.pikiran-rakyat.com/ekonomi/2016/01/27/358754/terminal-3-bandara-soekarno-hatta-nyaris-rampung-mei-digunakan Terminal 3 Bandara Soekarno\u2013Hatta Nyaris Rampung, Mei Digunakan] www.pikiran-rakyat.com</ref>\n\nIn 2018, the terminal's west pier (Pier 1) was extended. 8 new aerobridges were added, with 7 catering to wide-body aircraft and 1 catering to narrow-body aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tangerangonline.id/2018/10/28/terminal-3-pier-1-extension-bandara-soetta-mulai-diuji-coba/ |title=Terminal 3 Pier 1 Extension Bandara Soetta Mulai Diuji Coba |work=tangerangonline.id |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tangerangonline.id/2018/05/21/tambah-garbarata-ap-ii-kembangkan-pier-1-terminal-3-bandara-soetta |title=Tambah Garbarata, AP II Kembangkan Pier 1 Terminal 3 Bandara Soetta |work=tangerangonline.id |accessdate=8 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nTerminal 3 is equipped with BHS level 5 to detect bombs, an Airport Security System (ASS) which can control up to 600 CCTVs to detect faces who are available in the security register, an Intelligence Building Management System (IBMS) which can control uses of water and electricity (eco-green), rainwater system to produce clean water from rain, a recycled water system to produce toilet water from used toilet water, and illumination technology control to illuminate the terminal depending on the weather surrounding the terminal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.detik.com/berita/3229721/ini-fasilitas-canggih-yang-ada-di-terminal-3-ultimate-bandara-soekarno-hatta |title=Ini Fasilitas Canggih yang Ada di Terminal 3 Ultimate Bandara Soekarno-Hatta |author=Jabbar Ramdhani |date=10 June 2016}}</ref> Terminal 3 will be able to serve 60 airplanes from the current 40 airplanes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://megapolitan.kompas.com/read/2014/11/17/15163911/Agar.Penumpang.Lebih.Aman.dan.Nyaman.di.Bandara.Soekarno-Hatta |title=Agar Penumpang Lebih Aman dan Nyaman di Bandara Soekarno-HattaYYY |author=Pingkan Elita Dundu |date=17 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Terminal 4===\nAngkasa Pura II has undertaken a plan to build Terminal 4, which will be located on the north side of runway 1,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nasional.kompas.com/read/2016/08/03/18184311/angkasa.pura.ii.persiapkan.pembangunan.terminal.4.bandara.soekarno-hatta|title=Angkasa Pura II Persiapkan Pembangunan Terminal 4 Bandara Soekarno-Hatta}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnnindonesia.com/ekonomi/20160804115050-92-149157/ap-ii-ancang-ancang-bangun-terminal-4/|title=AP II Ancang-ancang Bangun Terminal 4}}</ref> south of Terminal 3, and east of Terminal 1. Terminal 4 will be built at the 4th stage as part of the development of the airport. The terminal will be built on 130 hectares of land, which will be able to serve 45 million passengers annually.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2019/10/10/angkasa-pura-ii-to-begin-construction-on-soekarno-hatta-airports-terminal-4-in-2021.html|title=Angkasa Pura II to begin construction on Soekarno-Hatta airport\u2019s Terminal 4 in 2021|accessdate=10 October 2019}}</ref> The terminal will be designed in the form of an 'H' and use eco-friendly and modern design, similar to the design of Terminal 3. The terminal is expected to be operational by 2024.\n\n===Freight Terminal===\nThe freight terminal is located on the east side of terminal 1. This terminal was used to handle cargo at the Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport, both domestic and international cargo. In the latest master plan, the freight terminal will move to the west side of terminal 2 and have a larger capacity.\n\n'''Navigation Aids'''\n\nRunway 07L/25R and 07R/25L are equipped with [[Instrument landing system|Instrument Landing System (ILS)]]. The runways are also equipped with [[VOR/DME]].\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport-dest-list\n|[[AirAsia]] |[[Senai International Airport|Johor Bahru]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[Penang International Airport|Penang]]\n|[[Air China]] |[[Beijing Capital International Airport|Beijing\u2013Capital]]\n|[[All Nippon Airways]] |[[Haneda Airport|Tokyo\u2013Haneda]], [[Narita International Airport|Tokyo\u2013Narita]]\n|[[Asiana Airlines]] |[[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]]\n|[[Batik Air]] |[[Pattimura Airport|Ambon]], [[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Sultan Iskandar Muda International Airport|Banda Aceh]], [[Radin Inten II International Airport|Bandar Lampung]], [[Don Mueang International Airport|Bangkok\u2013Don Mueang]],<ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/287602/batik-air-plans-bangkok-launch-from-late-dec-2019/</ref> [[Banyuwangi Airport|Banyuwangi]], [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Kalimarau Airport|Berau]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Jalaluddin Airport|Gorontalo]], [[Guilin Liangjiang International Airport|Guilin]], [[Sultan Thaha Airport|Jambi]], [[Sentani International Airport|Jayapura]], [[Haluoleo Airport|Kendari]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]],<ref>http://m.harnas.co/2019/10/22/batik-air-buka-rute-cengkareng-kuala-lumpur</ref>  [[Kunming Changshui International Airport|Kunming]], [[El Tari International Airport|Kupang]], [[Komodo Airport|Labuan Bajo]], [[Silampari Airport|Lubuklinggau]], [[Syukuran Aminuddin Amir Airport|Luwuk]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]], [[Rendani Airport|Manokwari]], [[Zainuddin Abdul Madjid International Airport|Mataram\u2013Lombok]], [[Kualanamu International Airport|Medan]], [[Nanning Wuxu International Airport|Nanning]], [[Minangkabau International Airport|Padang]], [[Tjilik Riwut Airport|Palangkaraya]], [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport|Palembang]], [[Mutiara SIS Al-Jufrie Airport|Palu]], [[Sultan Syarif Kasim II International Airport|Pekanbaru]], [[Penang International Airport|Penang]], [[Aji Pangeran Tumenggung Pranoto Airport|Samarinda]], [[Achmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]], [[Domine Eduard Osok Airport|Sorong]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[Taoyuan International Airport|Taipei\u2013Taoyuan]],<ref>https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/286633/batik-air-plans-taipei-service-in-dec-2019/</ref> [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]], [[Juwata International Airport|Tarakan]], [[Sultan Babullah Airport|Ternate]], [[Yogyakarta International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013International]]<br>'''Charter:''' [[Haikou Meilan International Airport|Haikou]]\n|[[Cathay Pacific]] |[[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]]\n|[[Cebu Pacific]] |[[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|Manila]]\n|[[China Airlines]] |[[Taiwan Taoyuan International Airport|Taipei\u2013Taoyuan]]\n|[[China Eastern Airlines]] |[[Shanghai Pudong International Airport|Shanghai\u2013Pudong]]\n|{{nowrap|[[China Southern Airlines]]}} |[[Guangzhou Baiyun International Airport|Guangzhou]], [[Shenzhen Bao'an International Airport|Shenzhen]]\n|[[Citilink]] |[[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Radin Inten II International Airport|Bandar Lampung]], [[Banyuwangi Airport|Banyuwangi]], [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Fatmawati Soekarno Airport|Bengkulu]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Sultan Thaha Airport|Jambi]], [[Sentani International Airport|Jayapura]], [[Kertajati International Airport|Kertajati]],<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Citilink adds new domestic sectors in Dec 2019/Jan 2020 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/288664/citilink-adds-new-domestic-sectors-in-dec-2019jan-2020/ |website=Routesonline |accessdate=10 January 2020}}</ref> [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[Komodo Airport|Labuan Bajo]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Abdul Rachman Saleh Airport|Malang]], [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]], [[Kualanamu International Airport|Medan]], [[Minangkabau International Airport|Padang]], [[Tjilik Riwut Airport|Palangkaraya]], [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport|Palembang]], [[Depati Amir Airport|Pangkal Pinang]], [[Sultan Syarif Kasim II International Airport|Pekanbaru]], [[Penang International Airport|Penang]], [[Phnom Penh International Airport|Phnom Penh]], [[Supadio International Airport|Pontianak]],<ref>https://www.citilink.co.id/best-fare/terbang-ke-pontianak</ref> [[Aji Pangeran Tumenggung Pranoto Airport|Samarinda]], [[Achmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Sisingamangaraja XII International Airport|Silangit]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[Adisumarmo International Airport|Surakarta/Solo]], [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]], [[Yogyakarta International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013International]]<ref name=\"Garuda_YIA\">{{cite web |title=Starting on March 29th 2020, Garuda Indonesia Group Serves All Flights From and Toward Yogyakarta Through Yogyakarta International Airport |url=https://www.garuda-indonesia.com/id/en/news-and-events/ga-group-layani-penerbangan-dari-dan-ke-yia.page? |website=Garuda Indonesia |accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]] |[[Dubai International Airport|Dubai\u2013International]]\n|[[Ethiopian Airlines]] |[[Addis Ababa Bole International Airport|Addis Ababa]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|[[Etihad Airways]] |[[Abu Dhabi International Airport|Abu Dhabi]]\n|[[EVA Air]] |[[Taiwan Taoyuan International Airport|Taipei\u2013Taoyuan]]\n|[[Flynas]] |'''Charter:''' [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|Jeddah]]\n|[[Garuda Indonesia]] |[[Pattimura Airport|Ambon]], [[Amsterdam Schiphol Airport|Amsterdam]], [[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Sultan Iskandar Muda International Airport|Banda Aceh]], [[Radin Inten II International Airport|Bandar Lampung]], [[Suvarnabhumi Airport|Bangkok\u2013Suvarnabhumi]], [[Syamsudin Noor International Airport|Banjarmasin]], [[Banyuwangi Airport|Banyuwangi]], [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Fatmawati Soekarno Airport|Bengkulu]], [[Frans Kaisiepo Airport|Biak]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Guangzhou Baiyun International Airport|Guangzhou]], [[Binaka Airport|Gunungsitoli]], [[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]], [[Sultan Thaha Airport|Jambi]], [[Sentani International Airport|Jayapura]], [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|Jeddah]], [[Haluoleo Airport|Kendari]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[El Tari International Airport|Kupang]], [[Komodo Airport|Labuan Bajo]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Abdul Rachman Saleh Airport|Malang]], [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]], [[Zainuddin Abdul Madjid International Airport|Mataram\u2013Lombok]], [[Kualanamu International Airport|Medan]], [[Prince Mohammad bin Abdulaziz Airport|Medina]], [[Melbourne Airport|Melbourne]], [[Mopah Airport|Merauke]], [[Kansai International Airport|Osaka\u2013Kansai]], [[Minangkabau International Airport|Padang]], [[Tjilik Riwut Airport|Palangkaraya]], [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport|Palembang]], [[Mutiara SIS Al-Jufrie Airport|Palu]], [[Pangkal Pinang Airport|Pangkal Pinang]], [[Sultan Syarif Kasim II International Airport|Pekanbaru]], [[Perth Airport|Perth]], [[Supadio International Airport|Pontianak]]<ref>http://beritatrans.com/2013/08/20/penerbangan-garuda-pontianak-jakarta-jadi-8-kali-sehari/</ref>, [[Aji Pangeran Tumenggung Pranoto Airport|Samarinda]], [[Achmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]], [[Shanghai Pudong International Airport|Shanghai\u2013Pudong]], [[Ferdinand Lumban Tobing Airport|Sibolga]], [[Sisingamangaraja XII International Airport|Silangit]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]], [[Domine Eduard Osok Airport|Sorong]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[Adisumarmo International Airport|Surakarta/Solo]], [[Sydney Airport|Sydney]], [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]], [[Raja Haji Fisabilillah International Airport|Tanjung Pinang]], [[Sultan Babullah Airport|Ternate]], [[Haneda Airport|Tokyo\u2013Haneda]], [[Yogyakarta International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013International]]<ref name=\"Garuda_YIA\"/> <br>'''Charter:''' [[Christmas Island Airport|Christmas Island]]\n|[[Indonesia AirAsia]]| [[Don Mueang International Airport|Bangkok\u2013Don Mueang]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Senai International Airport|Johor Bahru]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[Lombok International Airport|Mataram\u2013Lombok]], [[Kualanamu International Airport|Medan]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Liu |first1=Jim |title=Indonesia AirAsia resumes Jakarta \u2013 Medan Kualanamu in March 2020 |url=https://www.routesonline.com/news/38/airlineroute/289265/indonesia-airasia-resumes-jakarta-medan-kualanamu-in-march-2020/ |website=Routesonline |accessdate=3 February 2020}}</ref>, [[Penang International Airport|Penang]], [[Ahmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]], [[Domine Eduard Osok Airport|Sorong]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]], [[Yogyakarta International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013International]]<ref>{{cite web |title=AirAsia to move its operations in Yogyakarta to Yogyakarta International Airport, Kulon Progo starting 29 March 2020 |url=https://newsroom.airasia.com/news/2020/3/19/airasia-to-move-its-operations-in-yogyakarta-to-yogyakarta-international-airport-kulon-progo-starting-29-march-2020 |website=AirAsia |accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Japan Airlines]] |[[Narita International Airport|Tokyo\u2013Narita]]\n|[[Jet Asia Airways]] |[[Suvarnabhumi Airport|Bangkok\u2013Suvarnabhumi]]\n|[[Jetstar Asia Airways]] |[[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]] \n|[[KLM]] |[[Amsterdam Airport Schiphol|Amsterdam]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]]\n|[[Korean Air]] |[[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]]\n|[[Lion Air]] |[[Pattimura Airport|Ambon]], [[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Sultan Iskandar Muda International Airport|Banda Aceh]], [[Radin Inten II International Airport|Bandar Lampung]], [[Syamsudin Noor International Airport|Banjarmasin]], [[Banyuwangi Airport|Banyuwangi]], [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Fatmawati Soekarno Airport|Bengkulu]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Sultan Thaha Airport|Jambi]], [[Sentani International Airport|Jayapura]], [[Haluoleo Airport|Kendari]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[El Tari International Airport|Kupang]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Abdul Rachman Saleh Airport|Malang]], [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]], [[Zainuddin Abdul Madjid International Airport|Mataram\u2013Lombok]], [[Kualanamu International Airport|Medan]], [[Minangkabau International Airport|Padang]], [[Tjilik Riwut Airport|Palangkaraya]], [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport|Palembang]], [[Depati Amir Airport|Pangkal Pinang]], [[Mutiara SIS Al-Jufrie Airport|Palu]], [[Sultan Syarif Kasim II International Airport|Pekanbaru]], [[Supadio International Airport|Pontianak]],<ref>https://www.amp.kontan.co.id/news/lion-air-tambang-jadwal-terbang-pontianak-jakarta</ref> [[Achmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[Adisumarmo International Airport|Surakarta/Solo]], [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]], [[Raja Haji Fisabilillah International Airport|Tanjung Pinang]], [[Juwata International Airport|Tarakan]], [[Sultan Babullah Airport|Ternate]],<ref>https://agent.lionair.co.id/LionAirAgentsPortal/Default.aspx/</ref> [[Yogyakarta International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013International]]<ref>https://agent.lionair.co.id/LionAirAgentsPortal/Default.aspx</ref>  <br>'''Charter:''' [[Sanya Phoenix International Airport|Sanya]]\n|[[Malaysia Airlines]]| [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]]\n|[[Malindo Air]]| [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]]\n|[[NAM Air]]| [[Silampari Airport|Lubuklinggau]], [[Muara Bungo Airport|Muara Bungo]], [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport|Palembang]], [[Pangkal Pinang Airport|Pangkal Pinang]], [[Supadio International Airport|Pontianak]]<ref>https://www.flynamair.com/about</ref><ref>https://jambi.antaranews.com/berita/308789/seputar-nam-air-yang-patut-anda-ketahui</ref>, [[H. Asan Airport|Sampit]], [[Achmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]]\n|[[Oman Air]]| [[Muscat International Airport|Muscat]]\n|[[Philippine Airlines]]| [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport|Manila]] \n|[[Qantas]]| [[Sydney Airport|Sydney]]\n|[[Qatar Airways]]| [[Hamad International Airport|Doha]]\n|[[Royal Brunei Airlines]]| [[Brunei International Airport|Bandar Seri Begawan]]\n|[[Saudia]]| [[King Abdulaziz International Airport|Jeddah]], [[Prince Mohammad bin Abdulaziz Airport|Medina]], [[King Khalid International Airport|Riyadh]]\n|[[Scoot]]| [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|[[Shenzhen Airlines]]| [[Shenzhen Bao'an International Airport|Shenzhen]] \n|[[Singapore Airlines]]| [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|[[SriLankan Airlines]]| [[Bandaranaike International Airport|Colombo\u2013Bandaranaike]]\n|[[Sriwijaya Air]]| [[Radin Inten II International Airport|Bandar Lampung]], [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Ngurah Rai International Airport|Denpasar/Bali]], [[Sultan Thaha Airport|Jambi]], [[Sentani International Airport|Jayapura]], [[Sultan Hasanuddin International Airport|Makassar]], [[Abdul Rachman Saleh Airport|Malang]], [[Sam Ratulangi International Airport|Manado]], [[Kualanamu International Airport|Medan]], [[Minangkabau International Airport|Padang]], [[Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport|Palembang]], [[Depati Amir Airport|Pangkal Pinang]]<ref>https://www.airmagz.com/54069/jelang-imlek-2020-sriwijaya-air-tambah-rute-penerbangan.html</ref>, [[Supadio International Airport|Pontianak]]<ref>https://www.airmagz.com/54069/jelang-imlek-2020-sriwijaya-air-tambah-rute-penerbangan.html</ref>, [[Achmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]], [[Sisingamangaraja XII International Airport|Silangit]], [[Juanda International Airport|Surabaya]], [[Adisumarmo International Airport|Surakarta/Solo]], [[H.A.S. Hanandjoeddin International Airport|Tanjung Pandan]], [[Raja Haji Fisabilillah International Airport|Tanjung Pinang]], [[Yogyakarta International Airport|Yogyakarta\u2013International]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Mulai Tanggal 29 Maret 2020 Penerbangan Sriwijaya Air dari/ke Yogyakarta Pindah ke Yogyakarta International Airport (YIA) |url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B9RD5mxJcB9/ |website=Sriwijaya Air Official Instagram |accessdate=3 March 2020}}</ref>  <br>'''Charter:''' [[Haikou Meilan International Airport|Haikou]], [[Nanning Wuxu International Airport|Nanning]], [[Zhangjiajie Hehua International Airport|Zhangjiajie]]\n|[[Thai Airways]]| [[Suvarnabhumi Airport|Bangkok\u2013Suvarnabhumi]]\n|[[Thai Lion Air]]| [[Don Mueang International Airport|Bangkok\u2013Don Mueang]] \n|[[Trigana Air Service]]| [[Iskandar Airport|Pangkalan Bun]]\n|[[Turkish Airlines]]| [[Istanbul New Airport|Istanbul]]\n|[[Uzbekistan Airways]]| [[Tashkent International Airport|Tashkent]] \n|[[Vietnam Airlines]]| [[Tan Son Nhat International Airport|Ho Chi Minh City]]\n|[[XiamenAir]]| [[Fuzhou Changle International Airport|Fuzhou]], [[Xiamen Gaoqi International Airport|Xiamen]]\n}}\n\n===Cargo===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%;width:78%\"\n|- style=\"background:lightgrey;\"\n! style=\"width:22%;\"|Airlines|| class=\"unsortable\"|Destinations\n|- \n|[[ANA Cargo]] || [[Narita International Airport|Tokyo\u2013Narita]]<ref name=\"NH\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anacargo.jp/en/int/news/schedule/2014/140430.html|title=Expand Freighter Network from May 14th, 2014|publisher=ANA Cargo|date=30 April 2014| accessdate=20 May 2014}}</ref>\n|- \n|[[Asialink Cargo Airlines]] || [[Depati Amir Airport|Pangkal Pinang]]<ref>http://www.asialinkcargo.co.id</ref>\n|-\n|[[Cardig Air]] || [[Tan Son Nhat International Airport|Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Shenzhen Bao'an International Airport|Shenzhen]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardigair.com/site/schedule.php |title=Cardig Air Scheduled Timetable |publisher=Cardigair.com |date= |accessdate=1 January 2014}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Cargolux]] || [[Luxembourg Airport|Luxembourg]], [[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]]\n|-\n|[[Cathay Pacific Cargo]] || [[Noi Bai International Airport|Hanoi]], [[Hong Kong International Airport|Hong Kong]], [[Penang International Airport|Penang]]\n|-\n|[[China Airlines Cargo]] || [[Taiwan Taoyuan International Airport|Taipei\u2013Taoyuan]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]]\n|-\n|[[FedEx Express]] || [[Guangzhou Baiyun International Airport|Guangzhou]], [[Tan Son Nhat International Airport|Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]], [[Bangkok-Suvarnabhumi]]\n|-\n|[[K-Mile Air]] || [[Bangkok-Suvarnabhumi]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|-\n|[[Korean Air Cargo]] || [[Tan Son Nhat International Airport|Ho Chi Minh City]], [[Penang International Airport|Penang]], [[Incheon International Airport|Seoul\u2013Incheon]]\n|- \n|[[MASkargo]] || [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]] \n|- \n|[[My Indo Airlines]] || [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]], [[Sultan Aji Muhammad Sulaiman Airport|Balikpapan]], [[Ahmad Yani International Airport|Semarang]]\n|-\n|[[Qantas Freight]] || [[Sydney Airport|Sydney]] \n|-\n|[[Singapore Airlines Cargo]] || [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|-\n|[[Raya Airways]] || [[Sultan Abdul Aziz Shah Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013Subang]]\n|-\n|[[Tri-MG Intra Asia Airlines]] || [[Hang Nadim Airport|Batam]], [[Kuala Lumpur International Airport|Kuala Lumpur\u2013International]], [[Singapore Changi Airport|Singapore]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===Busiest routes===\nJakarta\u2013Singapore is one of the world's busiest international air routes; passenger numbers of this route is growing fast. It was the second busiest international route in Asia after Hong Kong\u2013Taipei in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/changis-busiest-routes-set-to-grow-further|title=Changis busiest routes set to growfurther}}</ref> [[Singapore Airlines]] alone operates more than 70 weekly flights between Jakarta & Singapore. Jakarta Soekarno-Hatta\u2013Surabaya route is ranked ninth busiest in the world by [[IATA]] in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.traveller.com.au/worlds-busiest-air-routes-the-busiest-route-in-the-world-will-surprise-you-gtemeg|title=The busiest-route in the world will surprise you}}</ref> Jakarta\u2013Singapore, and Jakarta\u2013Kuala Lumpur routes are ranked within the top ten of world's busiest international air routes in 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/spore-kl-route-is-worlds-busiest-global-air-link|title=Singapore-KL route is world's busiest global air link|newspaper=The Straits Times|accessdate=29 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===New traffic procedure===\nTo ease congestion, the airport authority implemented a new traffic procedure, the 72 Improved Runway Capacity (IRC 72), to handle 72 planes per hour. This limited a plane to 30\u201345 minutes only for arrival and unloading of passengers, to allow other planes to use the parking space. Gradually it has been implemented and on 26 June 2014 IRC 72 has been implemented fully for the period of 00:00 am to 01:30 am, 02:00 am to 10:00 am and 11:30 pm to 00:00 am with occupancy periods for aircraft are reduced from 110 seconds to 90 seconds of takeoff and from 65 seconds to 50 seconds for landing. The low time is from 04:00pm to 10:00pm with only maximum 32 flights/hour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.tempo.co/read/news/2014/06/26/056588302/Soekarno-Hatta-Airport-Increases-Runway-Capacity |title=Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport Increases Runway Capacity |date=26 June 2014 |publisher=Tempo.co}}</ref> By 2015, IRC 72 will become IRC 86 with the opening of the new terminal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.tempo.co/read/news/2014/02/21/056556275/Air-Traffic-Procedures-Restructured |title=Air Traffic Procedures Restructured |author=Maria Yuniar |date=21 February 2014 |publisher=Tempo.co}}</ref> As a comparison, [[London Heathrow Airport]], which has 2 runways like SHIA, can handle 100 flights per hour, so the target for SHIA has been revised to 92 flights per hour by 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.tempo.co/read/news/2014/04/25/056573110/Soekarno-Hatta-Airport-Ready-to-Serve-72-Flights-per-Hour |title=Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport Ready to Serve 72 Flights per Hour |author=Ananda Putri |date=25 April 2014 |publisher=Tempo.co}}</ref> As of July 2017, maximum flight frequency at Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport had been increased to 81 take-offs and landings per hour to accommodate increasing demand from aviation companies.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2017/07/27/flight-frequency-increased-to-meet-increasing-demand-minister.html|title=Flight frequency increased to meet increasing demand: Minister|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=28 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Airport facilities==\nTerminals 1 and 2 were designed to resemble a traditional ''joglo'' Javanese construction. The approach has been emphasized by the inclusion of well-maintained gardens located near all boarding areas. Terminal 3 and other new airport buildings use an eco-friendly and modern design.\n\n===Aircraft maintenance===\nMaintenance facilities for aircraft in Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport are supported by [[GMF AeroAsia]] (Garuda Maintenance Facility).\nThey include {{convert|480000|m2|sqft|sp=us}} of built-up structures, including four hangars, a spares warehouse, workshops, utility buildings, a ground support equipment building, chemical stores, an engine test cell, and management offices. In addition, [[GMF AeroAsia]] has an apron capable of handling up to 50 aircraft, taxiways, a run-up bay, and a waste treatment area, taking up {{convert|1150000|m2|sqft|sp=us}}.\n\nHangar 1 was built in 1991 and was designed for [[Boeing 747]]s. It has two full docks and is {{convert|22000|m2|sqft|sp=us}}. Hangar 2 is {{convert|23000|m2|sqft|sp=us}} and has 3 aircraft bays. It can perform minor A and B checks. It can hold up to one narrow body and one wide-body jet. Hangar 3 is also {{convert|23000|m2|sqft|sp=us}}. It normally holds up to 3 narrow-body aircraft but can be configured to hold up to one wide-body and one narrow body. It has 7 bays with 4 full docks, 6 roof-mounted cranes and one bay designed for [[McDonnell Douglas MD-11]]s, [[McDonnell Douglas DC-10]]s, and wide-body [[Airbus A330]]s aircraft. Hangar 4 is {{convert|67022|m2|sqft|sp=us}}. The Hangar 4 was opened in 2015 and was designed for narrow-body aircraft like B737s and A320s. It can handle 16 narrow-body aircraft at one time.\n\n===Golf course===\nThere is a golf course at the Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport supported by the Cengkareng Golf Club. The golf course has been open since 1999. It is located on the left side of the airport main gate by the Sheraton Bandara Hotel. The Cengkareng Golf Club is in the {{convert|102|ha|acres|adj = on}} Soewarna Business Park at Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport. In 2005 and 2008, this golf course was used for [[Indonesia Open (golf)|Indonesia Open]], a part of the [[PGA European Tour]]. There are 18 holes in the golf course.\n\n===Airport hotel===\nSoekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport has a hotel, the Bandara International Hotel, managed by [[AccorHotels]]. The Bandara International Hotel, which is located on the left side of the main exit road from the airport, has 4 floors with 220 guest rooms. The airport now has other hotels, including budget such as Ibis Styles, Pop! Hotels, Swiss-Belhotel, Orchard Hotel, Swiss-Belinn, Ibis Budget, and Amaris as an alternative. Terminal 3 of the airport has a Digital Airport Hotel or [[Capsule hotel]] with 120 rooms, which has Alpha-type and Beta-type rooms.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.tempo.co/read/news/2018/08/08/056920640/Soekarno-Hatta-Airports-Capsule-Hotel-Can-be-Booked-Online|title= Soekarno Hatta Airport`s Capsule Hotel Can be Booked Online|newspaper=Tempo|accessdate=18 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Lounges===\nThere are five airport lounges in the departure area. The Jasa Angkasa Semesta (JAS) Lounge is available for first and business class passengers of [[Cathay Pacific]], [[Qantas]], [[EVA Air]], [[Saudia]], and [[Singapore Airlines]]. The Pura Indah Lounge is available for first and business class passengers of [[Singapore Airlines]], [[KLM]], [[Malaysia Airlines]], [[Emirates (airline)|Emirates]], [[Cathay Pacific]], and [[China Airlines]]. The new Garuda Indonesia lounge is available for their business class and first-class passengers only, as well as GECC and GarudaMiles gold and above cardholders. The BNI Executive Lounge is located next to the Garuda Indonesia Lounge, the lounge serves passengers from all airlines. Other lounges are available outside of the departures area, operated by companies such as [[Indosat]], Sapphire, PT Mandara Jasindo Sena, [[Telkomsel]], and [[XL Axiata]]. Since 2013, the only lounge in Terminal 1 was opened named Batik Air Business Class Lounge inside the waiting room C7. The Garuda Indonesia lounge has been moved to Terminal 3 Ultimate.\n\n===Other facilities===\n[[File:Jakarta Airport 200507-1.jpg|thumb|Shopping area at Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport]]\nThe airport contains the head office of [[Garuda Indonesia]], Garuda Indonesia Management Building, located within the Garuda Indonesia City Center.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.garuda-indonesia.com/news/2009/07/23/president-susilo-bambang-yudhoyono-officially-opens-new-head-office-and-the-unveiling-of-new-garuda-indonesia-concept-of-service |title=President Susilo Bambang Yudhoyono Officially Opens New Head Office and the Unveiling of New Garuda Indonesia Concept of Service |publisher=Garuda Indonesia |date=23 July 2009 |accessdate=16 September 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231210258/http://www.garuda-indonesia.com/news/2009/07/23/president-susilo-bambang-yudhoyono-officially-opens-new-head-office-and-the-unveiling-of-new-garuda-indonesia-concept-of-service |archivedate=31 December 2010}}</ref> [[Angkasa Pura]] II's head office is on the airport property.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.angkasapura2.co.id/profile.php?isi=20&bhs=ina |title=Informasi Perusahaan |publisher=[[Angkasa Pura]] II |accessdate=16 September 2010 |quote=Kantor Pusat PT (Persero) Angkasa Pura II Bandara Internasional Jakarta Soekarno\u2013Hatta}}</ref>\n\nThere are 21 reading corners located in the waiting rooms of Terminal 2D, 2E and 2F.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://medan.tribunnews.com/2013/07/23/pojok-baca-kini-hadir-di-bandara-soekarno-hatta |title=Pojok Baca Kini Hadir di Bandara Soekarno Hatta |date=23 July 2013}}</ref> Shopping areas are also available in all terminals. Duty-free shops, souvenir shops, restaurants, and a cafeteria can be found there. There is a new \"Shopping Arcade\" located in terminal 1C. There are no shops in the arrival zones of the terminals, except for Terminal 3, where several cafes and fast-food restaurant chains are located.\n\nLintasarta, Internux (via YelloChat Free WiFi) and Telkom Indonesia have provided WiFi networks for the airport. The three networks allow users to connect to another network if a specific one is operational. Since November 2013, Terminal 2 has free WiFi covering the whole terminal and free WiFi for Terminal 1 is servicing as of July 2014. Terminal 3 now has free WiFi covering since November 2014.\n\nTo handle the overcrowding of smoking rooms being used, airport authorities have drawn up plans to build a smoking area in a garden near the rest area in Terminal 1A. It was opened in January 2015 and it will be developed to other terminals, if necessary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wartakota.tribunnews.com/2014/12/23/taman-khusus-merokok-dibangun-di-bandara|title=Taman Khusus Merokok Dibangun di Bandara|date=23 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Ground transportation==\nThere are several transportation options available for access to the airport: local airport terminal shuttles, trains, buses, taxi services of various kinds, and cars. There is a free shuttle bus service and people maneuver system ''Skytrain'' to connect the terminals of the airport.\n\n===Bus===\nSeveral bus companies, including the state-owned [[Perum DAMRI]] and private company Primajasa,<ref>{{cite news |last=Atriana |first=Rina |date=9 August 2016 |title=Transportasi di T3 Ultimate Bandara Soetta: Taksi, Damri hingga Shuttle Bus |url=https://news.detik.com/berita/3271710/transportasi-di-t3-ultimate-bandara-soetta-taksi-damri-hingga-shuttle-bus |work=detikNews |access-date=18 June 2017 |language=id}}</ref> provide services to various destinations from the airport. ''Jabodetabek Airport Connexion'' which consist of [[Perum DAMRI]],[[Perum PPD]], Big Bird dan Sinar Jaya Megah Langgeng serve routes from the airport to certain malls and hotels in [[Jabodetabek|Greater Jakarta]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wartakota.tribunnews.com/2017/05/30/dari-hotel-atau-mal-ke-bandara-soetta-bisa-naik-ini |title=Dari Hotel atau Mal ke Bandara Soetta Bisa Naik Ini |author=Max Agung Pribadi |date=30 May 2017}}</ref> The buses operate from 06.00 to 23.00 with routes:<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wartakota.tribunnews.com/2017/05/30/blue-bird-luncurkan-bus-bandara-soeta-jabodetabek-dengan-tarif-rp-50000 |title=Blue Bird Luncurkan Bus Bandara Soetta-Jabodetabek dengan Tarif Rp 50000 |date=30 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nTravel time to and from the center of Jakarta (at the [[Gambir Station|Gambir railway station]]) takes around 70 minutes, depending on traffic. Buses to the airport leave from the various terminals in central Jakarta ([[Gambir, Gambir|Gambir]]) and surrounding areas.\n\n==== BUS - Shuttle service====\n{| style=\"text-align:left; font-size:95%; border:1px solid black\"\n|-\n! Service !! !!Destination (Soetta Airport,Terminal 1, 2 and 3)\n|-\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background:#09f; color:black; height:35px;\"| Shuttle Airport Bus\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:red;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Agramas || Pusat Grosir Cililitan ||[[East Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:green;color:white;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Citilink Shuttle || Scientia Square Park ||[[South Tangerang]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:green;color:white;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Citilink Shuttle || SCBD ||[[Central Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Bandung ||[[Bandung]]<ref>http://bumn.go.id/damri/berita/1-Trayek-Baru-DAMRI-Basoetta---Bandung-dan-Jakarta---Surabaya</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Bekasi Kayuringin Bus Terminal ||[[Bekasi]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Bekasi Trade Center||[[Bekasi]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Blok M Bus Terminal ||[[South Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Botani Square Mall ||[[Bogor]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Cikarang ||[[Cikarang]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Citra Raya ||[[Tangerang Regency]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || City Mall Cibinong ||[[Cibinong]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Depok ||[[Depok]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Epicentrum ||[[South Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Gambir Railway Station ||[[Central Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Kampung Rambutan Bus Terminal ||[[East Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Karawang ||[[Karawang]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Kemang Pratama ||[[Bekasi]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Kemayoran ||[[Central Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Kota Harapan Indah ||[[Bekasi]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Lebak Bulus ||[[South Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Lippo Karawaci Mall ||[[Tangerang]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Mangga Dua Square Mall ||[[North Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Pandeglang ||[[Pandeglang Regency]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Pasar Minggu Bus Terminal ||[[South Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Pondok Cabe ||[[South Tangerang]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Pramuka City ||[[Central Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Pulo Gebang ||[[East Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Purwakarta ||[[Purwakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Rawamangun Bus Terminal ||[[East Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Sentul City ||[[Bogor]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Serang\u2013Cilegon-Merak ||[[Banten]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Sukabumi ||[[Sukabumi]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || Tanjung Priok Bus Terminal ||[[North Jakarta]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Damri || WTC Serpong ||[[South Tangerang]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:red;color:white;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Primajasa || Bandung Batununggal || [[Bandung]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:red;color:white;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Primajasa || Bandung Caringin || [[Bandung]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:yellow;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Hiba Utama || Depok Bus Terminal ||[[Depok]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:gray;color:white;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Sinar Jaya || Cileungsi Bus Terminal ||[[Bogor Regency]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:red;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Redwhitestar || Bandung Gedungsate ||[[Bandung]]\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:red;color:black;text-align:center;font-weight:bold\" | Primajasa  RWS|| Bandung Diponegoro32  || [[Bandung]]\n|}\n\n====JA Connexion Bus====\nGreater Jakarta Transportation Agency (BPTJ) operates this service, which uses air conditioned buses with comfortable seats and Wi-Fi.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/travel/2017/12/28/airport-bus-service-available-at-pondok-indah-mall.html|title=Airport bus service available at Pondok Indah Mall|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref> The routes are:\n* [[Hotel Borobudur]]-Hotel Alia-Hotel Luminor-Airport. \n* Hotel Aryaduta-Hotel Sari Pan Pacific-Airport.\n* Hotel Grand Cemara-Hotel Ibis Thamrin-Hotel Milenium-Airport.\n* Hotel Sahid Jaya-Mall Grand Indonesia-Hotel Ascot-Airport. \n* Hotel Amaris Thamrin City-Airport. \n* Hotel Sahid Jaya Lippo Cikarang-Airport. \n* Bogor Trade Mall-Airport. \n* Mall Taman Anggrek-Airport. \n* Mall Plaza Senayan-Airport. \n* Mall ITC Cempaka Mas-Airport. \n* Mall Kelapa Gading-Airport. \n* Pondok Indah Mall-Airport\n* Summarecon Serpong-Airport.\n* ITC Tanah Abang-Airport.\n* Bubulak-Bukit Cimanggu City(Bogor Icon)-Sentul-Airport\n* Pondok Gede (Transmart Atrium) - Airport.\n* Taman mini (Tamini Square) - Airport.\n\n====Inter-terminal shuttle service====\nSoekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport provides a free shuttle bus that connects Terminals 1, 2 and 3. The shuttle bus can be found at the arrival hall of Terminal 1A\u20131B\u20131C, on the eastern wing of the arrival hall of Terminal 2F and in front of the departure hall of Terminal 3.\n\n===Taxicab===\nThe airport is connected to Jakarta's city center via the [[Prof. Dr. Ir. Soedijatmo Toll Road]]. There is extensive car parking, including long-stay facilities, at the airport.\nVarious taxi and shuttle services are provided by several operators.\n\n===Rail===\n====Skytrain (inter-terminal shuttle service)====\n{{See also|Soekarno-Hatta Airport Skytrain}}\n{{Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport Skytrain}}\n[[File:Soetta Skytrain 8.jpg|thumb|left|Skytrain Automated People Mover for inter-terminal airport shuttle service]]\nThe plan to build an airport automated [[people mover]] system to connect Terminals 1, 2, and 3, and the Airport Rail Link Station, was announced in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://economy.okezone.com/read/2016/01/27/320/1298382/kereta-tanpa-masinis-di-bandara-soekarno-hatta-butuh-rp1-triliun |title=Kereta Tanpa Masinis di Bandara Soekarno\u2013Hatta Butuh Rp1 Triliun |author= Kurniasih Miftakhul Jannah |date=27 January 2016}}</ref> Starting on 17 September 2017, the people mover, named '''Skytrain''', is officially opened to connect Terminal 3 and Terminal 2 vice versa, with a [[headway]] of 5 minutes. One set of Skytrain can serve 2x88 passengers. It temporarily operates between 07.00\u201310.00, 13.00\u201314.00 and 17.00\u201319.00.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://wartakota.tribunnews.com/2017/09/17/skytrain-bandara-soekarno-hatta-gratis |title=Skytrain Bandara Soekarno-Hatta Gratis |author=Yaspen Martinus |date=17 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n====Airport rail link====\n{{Soekarno-Hatta Airport Rail Link}}\n{{See also|Soekarno-Hatta Airport Rail Link}}\n[[Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport Rail Link]] connects [[Jakarta]] city center with the airport. The train takes 45\u201355 minutes from [[Manggarai railway station|Manggarai]] station at [[South Jakarta]] to SHIA station. Each train accommodates up to 272 passengers and will serve about 35,000 passengers with 122 trips a day, when fully operational.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://en.tempo.co/read/news/2017/02/26/056850395/Construction-of-Airport-Rail-Link-to-be-Completed-in-March-2017 |title=Construction of Airport Rail Link to be Completed in March 2017 |newspaper=Tempo|date=26 December 2017}}</ref> There is a 30 minutes interval between the train departures. As Manggarai station is under renovation, [[BNI City railway station|Sudirman Baru]] station is being temporary as the terminus for the city center.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.tempo.co/read/news/2016/12/06/056825670/Soekarno-Hatta-Airport-Train-to-Complete-by-June-2017 |title=Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport Train to Complete by June 2017 |date=26 December 2017}}</ref> The airport train currently makes 42 trips daily between 3.51 a.m. and 9.51 p.m., departing from [[BNI City railway station|Sudirman Baru]] station in to [[SHIA railway station|SHIA]], with a stop at [[Batuceper railway station|Batuceper]] station. Trips from Soekarno-Hatta to Sudirman Baru runs from 6.10 a.m. to 11.10 p.m., departing every hour.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2017/12/26/airport-train-kicks-off-services-with-promotional-fare.html|title=Airport train kicks off services with promotional fare|newspaper=The Jakarta Post|accessdate=26 December 2017}}</ref> The ticket price for the journey is IDR70 thousand (US$5). Passengers can only book train tickets using credit and debit cards, as well as electronic money via Railink app available for smartphones or vending machines at stations.\n\nAn express line between [[Halim Perdanakusuma Airport]] and the airport is under planning stage, to be built by an investor as a [[public\u2013private partnership]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/07/16/government-pegs-pt-kai-airport-railway-development.html|title=Government pegs PT KAI for airport railway development|publisher=|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/12/09/kai-airport-train-ready-2013.html |title=KAI: Airport train ready in 2013 |date=9 December 2011}}</ref> The express train will take 30 minutes to connect the airports.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bisnis.liputan6.com/read/799301/ada-kereta-ekspress-dari-bandara-halim-ke-soetta-hanya-30-menit?wp.bsns |title=Ada Kereta Ekspress, Dari Bandara Halim ke Soetta Hanya 30 Menit |date=13 January 2014}}</ref> In early 2015, the government changed the fund from participation to not funding at all, so the contract for Rp 28 billion will be revised, including new rail express tariff. The construction of this line has been delayed and completion is now projected to be in 2019 at the earliest.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.beritasatu.com/aktualitas/241986-pemerintah-kaji-ulang-kontrak-ka-ekspres-halimsoetta.html |title=Pemerintah Kaji Ulang Kontrak KA Ekspres Halim-Soetta |date=19 January 2015}}</ref>\n<!-- don't put plans here, there's another article about airport plans in the history section. All article here has been moved to there -->\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n* On 28 October 1997, a [[Trigana Air Service]] [[Fokker F-28 Fellowship|Fokker F-28 Fellowship 3000]] passenger plane returned to land at Jakarta\u2013Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport after the aircraft experienced technical problems two minutes after takeoff. Smoke and severe heat had entered the cockpit and the passenger cabin. The airplane sustained damage due to the heat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19971028-1|title=ASN Aircraft accident Fokker F-28 Fellowship 3000 PK-YPT Jakarta\u2013Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport (CGK)|author=Harro Ranter|date=28 October 1997|publisher=|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n* On 23 January 2003, a [[Star Air (Indonesia)|Star Air]] [[Boeing 737]] touched down {{convert|500|m|ft|sp=us}} past the threshold of runway 25L, a little left of the centerline, at a time of heavy rainfall with associated heavy winds. It went off the side of the runway, causing substantial damage to the aircraft's undercarriage and belly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20030123-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Boeing 737-2B7 PK-ALV Jakarta\u2013Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport (CGK)|author=Harro Ranter|date=23 January 2003|publisher=|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n* 2003 Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport bombing \u2013 On 27 April 2003, a bomb exploded in terminal 2, departure hall of the domestic terminal. The bomb was hidden under a table of a [[KFC]] stall and exploded during lunch hours. 10 people were injured in the blast, one 17-year-old teenager identified as Yuli was seriously injured. Her legs had to be amputated. Emergency services were rushed to the scene and suspected that the motive of the bombing was due to the [[Free Aceh Movement]], a separatist movement in Aceh. This was proved by the location of the blast, which was located on the domestic passenger hall rather than on the international passenger hall.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sebuah Ledakan Mengguncang Bandara Soekarno\u2013Hatta|url=http://news.liputan6.com/read/53646/sebuah-ledakan-mengguncang-bandara-soekarno-hatta}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Bom Bandara Soekarno\u2013Hatta Memutuskan Kaki Yuli|url=http://news.liputan6.com/read/53647/bom-bandara-soekarno-hatta-memutuskan-kaki-yuli}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\tApa Pesan Peledakan Bom di Bandara Soekarno\u2013Hatta|work=Unisosdem.org|url=http://www.unisosdem.org/article_detail.php?aid=1737&coid=3&caid=22&gid=1|accessdate=20 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160920092814/http://www.unisosdem.org/article_detail.php?aid=1737&coid=3&caid=22&gid=1|archivedate=20 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.liputan6.com/read/53650/bom-di-bandara-diduga-terkait-kasus-aceh|title=Bom di Bandara Diduga Terkait Kasus Aceh|work=Liputan6.com|date=27 April 2003|accessdate=20 September 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160918162500/http://news.liputan6.com/read/53650/bom-di-bandara-diduga-terkait-kasus-aceh|archivedate=18 September 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* On 11 August 2003, a [[Garuda Indonesia]] Fokker F-28 Fellowship 3000R suffered a left main gear collapse after a flight from [[Surabaya]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20030811-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Fokker F-28 Fellowship 3000R PK-GFT Jakarta\u2013Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport (CGK)|author=Harro Ranter|date=11 August 2003|publisher=|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n* On 9 March 2009, a [[Lion Air]] [[MD-90]] overran runway 25L, due to an unstable approach {{convert|100|m|ft|sp=us}} before the runway in rainfall and strong winds, in which the aircraft touched down to the left of the centerline. Although its thrust reversers were functioning, it veered to the right, resulting in the aircraft resting 90 degrees off the runway.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=20090309-1|title=ASN Aircraft accident McDonnell Douglas MD-90-30 PK-LIL Jakarta Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport (CGK)|author=Harro Ranter|date=9 March 2009|publisher=|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\nIn 1995, the landscaping of Soekarno\u2013Hatta airport was awarded by [[Aga Khan Award for Architecture]] as one of the best examples of integrating the terminal building pavilions, with lush tropical garden harmoniously.<ref>{{cite web | title = Landscaping of Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport | work = Aga Khan Award for Architecture | year = 1993\u20131995 | url = http://www.akdn.org/architecture/project/landscaping-soekarno-hatta-airport |accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref>\n\nSoekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport was ranked fourth on the [[Skytrax]] World's Most Improved Airport 2014 list based on surveys of 12.85 million passengers from 110 countries.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jabar.tribunnews.com/2014/04/01/soekarno-hatta-peringkat-empat-the-worlds-most-improved-airport |title=Soekarno\u2013Hatta Peringkat Empat The World's Most Improved Airport |author=Sakina Rakhma Diah Setiawan |work=Tribun Jabar |date=1 April 2014 |accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref> [[Skytrax]] also ranked Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport as a 3-Star Airport.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jakarta Soekarno\u2013Hatta Airport Quality Rating|url=http://www.airlinequality.com/ratings/jakarta-soekarno-hatta-airport-quality-rating/|publisher=Skytrax|accessdate=4 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport was ranked first on the [[Skytrax]] World's Most Improved Airport 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.airlinequality.com/news/best-airports-of-2017-unveiled-at-world-airport-awards/|title=Best airports of 2017 unveiled at World Airport Awards |publisher=Airline & Airport Reviews and Ratings (Skytrax) |date=14 March 2017|access-date=15 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Soekarno\u2013Hatta declared World\u2019s Most Improved Airport|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2017/03/15/soekarno-hatta-declared-worlds-most-improved-airport.html|accessdate=16 March 2017|work=The Jakarta Post|date=15 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Sukarno hatta airport - Entrance - Jakarta - Indonesia.jpg|The former main entrance gate at [[Prof. Dr. Ir. Soedijatmo Toll Road]]\nFile:Soekarno-hatta statue.JPG|The former site of the statue of Soekarno and Mohammad Hatta\nFile:Sukarno hatta airport - Terminal - Jakarta - Indonesia.jpg|Terminal 2\nFile:Sukarno hatta airport - Tower - Jakarta - Indonesia.jpg |Tower\nFile:CGK T2 waiting pavillon.jpg|Terminal building with gardens\nFile:check in hall.JPG|Check in desks in terminal 2\nSoekarno-Hatta T2 Gate Lounge 2.JPG |Gate lounge in terminal 2\nFile:terminal2cgk2.jpg|Baggage claim at terminal 2\nFile:Soetta Arrival Hall 2F.jpg|Arrival Hall terminal 2F\nFile:Soekarno-Hatta International Airport Terminal 3 front.JPG|The old Terminal 3\nFile:CGK Terminal 3 7.jpg|Dropoff bays at the departure area of Terminal 3.\nFile:CGK Terminal 3 9.jpg|Welcome signage at the arrival area of Terminal 3.\nFile:CGK Terminal 3 11.jpg|Directional signage at the departure area of Terminal 3.\nFile:CGK Terminal 3 14.jpg|A view of the Terminal 3 building.\nFile:CGK Terminal 2.jpg|The airport welcome sign along the tarmac in front of Terminal 2\nFile:CGK_Terminal_3_8.jpg|The luggage carousels at the arrival area of Terminal 3.\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal-inline|Indonesia}}\n*{{Portal-inline|Jakarta}}\n* {{Portal-inline|Aviation}}\n{{Portal|Jakarta|Indonesia|Aviation}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Soekarno-Hatta International Airport}}\n{{wikivoyage|Soekarno-Hatta International Airport}}\n* [http://www.soekarnohatta-airport.co.id Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport]\n* {{WAD|WIII|source=[[DAFIF]]}}\n* {{GCM|CGK|source=[[DAFIF]]}}\n* {{NWS-current|WIII}}\n* {{ASN|CGK}}\n* [https://soundcloud.com/suarakecil/soekarno-hatta-airport Sound recording from inside Soekarno\u2013Hatta airport]\n\n{{Airports in Indonesia}}\n{{Soekarno\u2013Hatta International Airport}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Soekarno-Hatta International Airport}}\n[[Category:Airports established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Airports in Jakarta]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Banten]]\n[[Category:Infrastructure in Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Transport in Banten]]\n[[Category:1985 establishments in Indonesia]]\n", "name_user": "Meandkancil2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePassenger:add References For AirAsia (AK) and Indonesia AirAsia (QZ) Jakarta (Soekarno-Hatta) - Johor Bahru", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soekarno%E2%80%93Hatta_International_Airport"}
{"title_page": "Scott Benzel", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = #6495ED\n| name          = Scott Benzel\n| image         = Scott Benzel, Mathesis and Mathematikoi, Mt. Wilson Observatory, 2017.jpg\n|alt=Scott Benzel, Mathesis and Mathematikoi, Mt. Wilson Observatory, 2017\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = Scott Benzel, Mathesis and Mathematikoi, Mt. Wilson Observatory, 2017\n| birth_name     =\n| birth_date     = {{birth-date|1968}}\n| birth_place      = [[Scottsdale, Arizona]]\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| field         = [[contemporary art]], [[sculpture]], [[photography]],[[performance art]], and [[video art]].\n| training      =  University of Arizona, BA 1995, California Institute of the Arts, M.F.A, 2001\n| movement      =\n| works         = \n| patrons       =\n| influenced by = \n| influenced    =\n| awards        = \n}}\n'''Scott Benzel''' (born 1968 in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], lives and works in [[Los Angeles]]), is an American [[visual artist]], musician, [[performance artist]], and [[composer]]. Benzel is a member of the faculty of the School of Art at [[California Institute of the Arts]], Valencia, CA.<ref>{{cite web|title=Faculty and Staff Calarts School of Art|url=https://art.calarts.edu/faculty-and-staff/}}</ref> \n\n==Biography==\nBenzel was born in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]] and raised in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]. He graduated from the [[University of Arizona]] after undergraduate work at [[California Institute of the Arts]]. In 1998, Benzel returned to [[California Institute of the Arts]] and received his [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] in 2001. Benzel is a member of the faculty of the School of Art at [[California Institute of the Arts]].\n\n==Work==\nBenzel's work explores the processes and contradictions inherent in mass media systems of production, the development of collective cultural imaginations and identification, and mythologized cultural histories.\n\nBenzel's work has been shown or performed at The [[J. Paul Getty Museum]], Los Angeles, the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], [[The Hammer Museum]], Los Angeles, The Contemporary Art Museum of St. Louis,<ref>{{cite web|title=Contemporary Art Museum St. Louis, Front Room, Scott Benzel|url=http://camstl.org/exhibitions/front-room/scott-benzel/}}</ref> LAXART, Los Angeles, Maccarone, New York,<ref>{{cite web|title=Maccarone, New York|url=http://www.maccarone.net}}</ref> [[Various Small Fires]], Los Angeles,<ref>{{cite web|title=Various Small Fires, Los Angeles, Scott Benzel|url=http://www.vsf.la/scott-benzel/}}</ref> [[Blum & Poe]], Los Angeles, Human Resources, Los Angeles, the Bard Center for Curatorial Studies,<ref>{{cite web|title=Bard Center for Curatorial Studies, Scott Benzel|url=http://www.bard.edu/ccs/exhibitions/scott-benzel-ivory-neige-lorigine-du-monde-magic-eraser-2/}}</ref> The Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles (in collaboration with Sam Durant and Tom Recchion), Performa 09, New York (in collaboration with [[Mike Kelley (artist)|Mike Kelley]]),<ref>{{cite web|title=Roberta Smith, Performa 09: Mike Kelley\u2019s Extracurricular Activity\", The New York Times,2009|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/11/19/performa-09-mike-kelleys-extracurricular-activity/}}</ref> Mandrake, Los Angeles, Art Basel, Miami, and Art Basel: Statements (in collaboration with Andrea Bowers).\n\nBenzel collaborated with Mike Kelley on the scores and soundtracks to Kelley\u2019s installations ''Day is Done'' at Gagosian Gallery, New York, ''Profondeurs Vertes'' at the Musee Louvre, Paris, and Kelley and Michael Smith\u2019s ''A Voyage of Growth and Discovery'' at the Sculpture Center, New York and West of Rome, Los Angeles. With Kelley, he composed and produced ''Judson Church Dances'', a live performance of the music of ''Day is Done'' with Kelley at [[Judson Church]] for Performa 09, New York.\n\n===Mathesis and Mathematikoi, for string quartet, anvil, dancers, and telescope operator===\nPerformed on the rotating deck of the 100 inch telescope at Mt. Wilson Observatory, CA, part of Knowledges 2017 <ref>{{cite web|title=Kholti, Hedi El, Frieze, Bad and Good times in L.A., a year of protest and performance in Los Angeles, 2017|url=https://frieze.com/article/bad-and-good-times-la/}}</ref>\n\n===The Kouroi/The Society of Dilettanti, for string trio, experimental hardcore trio, voice, and live stream===\nMusical performance/lecture at the J. Paul Getty Museum, Los Angeles, 2017\n\n===Op. 21: Inner Experience Fellowship/Friends of Crime===\nFitzpatrick/Leland House, MAK Center for Art and Architecture, Los Angeles\n\n===Split Chorale for Viljo Revell===\nBenzel collaborated with Kathryn Andrews on the performance for 300 choristers and video in [[Toronto City Hall]], Toronto, ON, as part of Nuit Blanche, Toronto, 2014\n\n===(Threnody) A beginner\u2019s guide to Mao Tse-Tung===\nBenzel was selected for inclusion in the first Los Angeles biennial, Made in L.A. 2012 at the Hammer Museum,<ref>{{cite web|title=Made in L.A. 2012, Hammer Museum|url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2012/made-in-la-2012/}}</ref> 2012\n\n===Maldistribution===\nBenzel's solo show at Human Resources, Los Angeles, was selected by Artforum and Frieze magazines in their year-end Best of 2011 lists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Holte, Michael Ned, Artforum Best of 2011:Scott Benzel, December, 2011|url=http://scottbenzel.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/ArtforumBestof2011-Benzel.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Griffin, Jonathan, Frieze Best of 2011|url=http://blog.frieze.com/best-of-2011-part-6/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910013914/http://blog.frieze.com/best-of-2011-part-6/|archivedate=2014-09-10}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\n===Selected Solo Exhibitions and Performance===\n\n2020 ''Mindless Pleasures'' Bel Ami, Los Angeles\n\n2018 ''V.I.T.R.I.O.L.'' Los Angeles Contemporary Exhibitions, Los Angeles\n\n2018 ''Torcat Tiqaucrat Mytics Ahtrae'' Acid Free, Blum and Poe, Los Angeles\n\n2017 ''The Kouroi / The Society of Dilettanti'' J. Paul Getty Museum, Los Angeles\n\n2017 ''Mathesis and Mathematikoi'' Mt. Wilson Observatory, CA, Knowledges 2017, curated by Christina Ondrus\n\n2016 ''(Mayakovsky) for Instrumental Transcommunication, Voice, and Autotune'' Rainbow in Spanish, Los Angeles\n\n2015 ''Op. 21: Inner Experience Fellowship/Friends of Crime'' MAK Center for Art and Architecture, Los Angeles\n\n2015 ''Desert Center (Composition I10 Mvmt IV (Dusk))'' Palm Springs Art Museum, Desert Center, CA\n\n2014 Various Small Fires, Los Angeles\n\n2014 Los Angeles Contemporary Archive, Los Angeles\n\n2014 Maccarone, New York\n\n2013 ''LAAIR / The Traveller\u2019s Companion Addenda'' Shanaynay, Paris\n\n2013 ''\u201cScott Benzel\u201d and What does Possession Mean to You?'' Human Resources, Los Angeles\n\n2013 ''\u2026plays selections from\u2026'' Dem  Passwords, Los Angeles\n\n2013 ''W.W.A.R./ Die Dritte Generation'' Art Los Angeles Contemporary, Los Angeles\n\n2012 ''The Academy / The Chthonic at Eleusis'' Public Fiction, Los Angeles\n\n2012 ''(Threnody) A beginner\u2019s guide to Mao Tse-Tung'' Made in LA 2012, Hammer Museum, Los Angeles\n\n2012 ''Funhouse after the Penultimate Sequence of The Lady from Shanghai'' Ball of Artists, LAXART/Hammer\n\n2012 ''Recombinant Folk History and Non-genre I'' Black Box, curated by Liz Glynn, Pacific Standard Time, Los Angeles\n\n2011 Contemporary Art Museum St. Louis, Front Room\n\n2011 ''Maldistribution'' Human Resources at Cottage Home, Los Angeles\n\n2011 ''Concentric Circles (before and after David Smith)'' Los Angeles County Museum of Art, Los Angeles\n\n2010  sound. series concert at King\u2019s Road Park, commission by SASSAS, Los Angeles\n\n===Selected Group Exhibitions===\n\n2019 ''Garland'' Treignac Projet, Treignac, France, curated by Sabrina Tarasoff\n\n2018 ''#followme''  Desert Center, Los Angeles, organized by Michael Slenzke\n\n2018 ''Home Bodies, Away Teams''  UMOCA Salt Lake City, UT, organized by Earl Gravy\n\n2017 ''Imagining Tellus 28''  Harvestworks, New York, curated by Tom Leeser\n\n2017 ''Ours is a City of Writers''  Los Angeles Municipal Gallery, selected by John Tain\n\n2016 ''Nostalgia for the Present: Two Years of LACA''  Los Angeles Contemporary Archive, curated by Eli Diner\n\n2014 ''Golden State''  Museum of Contemporary Art Tucson, curated by Drew Heitzler, Tucson, AZ\n\n2014 ''\u201cAnd yes, I even remember you.\u201d''  Aran Cravey, Los Angeles, curated by Eric Kim\n\n2013 ''\u201cWould you ever Write a Tract?\u201d''  Autocenter, Berlin, curated by Marcel Dickhage and Daniel Horn\n\n2013 ''The Stand In''  Public Fiction, Los Angeles, curated by Alexandra Gaty and Lauren Mackler\n\n2013 ''In the Good Name of the Company''  For Your Art, Los Angeles, curated by Jan Tumlir, Brian Roettinger, Christopher Michlig\n\n2012 ''An Homage to Mike Kelley''  presented by Gagosian Gallery, MOMA PS1, New York\n\n2012 ''Venice Beach Biennial''  with Mark Hagen, curated by Ali Subotnick, Venice, CA\n\n2012 ''Print Imprint''   Actual Size and Cirrus Gallery, Los Angeles\n\n2010 ''Endless Bummer/Surf Elsewhere''  Blum and Poe, Los Angeles, curated by Drew Heitzler\n\n===Selected Collaborations===\n\n2014 ''Split Chorale for Viljo Revell'' with Kathryn Andrews, Nuit Blanche, Toronto, CN\n\n2013 ''Part-Objects'' with Anita Pace, Perform Chinatown, Los Angeles\n\n2012 ''A|D'' with Liz Glynn, also with Corey Fogel, Giles Miller, Public Fiction, Los Angeles\n\n2012 ''Venice Beach Biennial'' with Mark Hagen, curated by Ali Subotnick, Venice, CA\n\n2009 ''Judson Church Horse Dances'' Co-composer, Producer, with Mike Kelley, Performa 09, New York\n\n2009 ''Destroy All Monsters at \u201dA Fantastic World Superimposed on Reality\u201d'' Gramercy Theatre, Performa 09, New York\n\n2009 ''A Voyage of Growth and Discovery'' Original Score Co-composer with Mike Kelley, Sculpture Center, New York\n\n2006 ''Profondeurs Vertes'' Original Score Co-Composer with Mike Kelley, Musee Louvre, Paris\n\n2005 ''Day is Done'' Original Score Co-Composer with Mike Kelley, Gagosian, New York\n\n2004 ''Destroy All Monsters at \u201dAll Tomorrow\u2019s Parties\u201d'' curated by Jake and Dinos Chapman, Camber Sands, UK\n\n2004 ''Into the Sun'' Live Performance w/Sam Durant and Tom Recchion, Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles\n\n2001 ''Democracy\u2019s Body'' Original Score Composer for Andrea Bowers exhibition, Art Basel Statements, Basel, Switzerland\n\n==Musical Work==\nBenzel's performances often incorporate live musicians performing his original compositions. Since 2017, he has been employing limited AI, Machine Learning, and generative algorithmic platforms as part of the composition process. Live performances of compositions include ''Torcat Tiqaucrat Mytics Ahtrae'' Blum and Poe, Los Angeles, 2018''Mathesis and Mathematikoi, for string quartet, anvil, dancers, and telescope operator'', at Mt. Wilson Observatory, Knowledges 2017,<ref>{{cite web|title=Kholti, Hedi El, Frieze, Bad and Good times in L.A., a year of protest and performance in Los Angeles, 2017|url=https://frieze.com/article/bad-and-good-times-la/}}</ref>''The Kouroi/The Society of Dilettani, for string trio, experimental punk trio, voice, and live stream'', at the J. Paul Getty Museum, Los Angeles, 2017, ''Op. 21: Inner Experience Fellowship/Friends of Crime'', at the MAK Center for Art and Architecture, Los Angeles, 2015, ''Desert Center (Composition I10 Mvmt IV (Dusk))'', at the Palm Springs Art Museum, Palm Springs, CA, and Desert Center, CA, 2015, and ''Split Chorale for Viljo Revell for 300 voices'', at Toronto City Hall, Nuit Blanche, Toronto, ON, 2014\n\nMusical projects have included [[Destroy All Monsters (band)|Destroy All Monsters]], the band led by American artist Mike Kelley and [[Machines of Loving Grace]].\n\nIn 2009, Benzel released ''Blak Bloc'', a composition for string quartet and guitar feedback and synthesizer, chosen by Artforum magazine as a Best of 2009: Music.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prina, Stephen, Artforum: Best of 2009: Music: Scott Benzel Blak Bloc\u2019, Dec. 2009|url=http://artforum.com/inprint/id=24235}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to production and remix work with [[The Red Krayola]], [[Destroy All Monsters]], [[Jon Spencer Blues Explosion]], [[Lucinda Williams]], [[Boss Hog]], and various others, Benzel has produced albums for [[Fat Possum Records]] and [[Plug Research]] in Los Angeles.<ref>[http://www.allmusicguide.com/ All Music Guide] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091001075157/http://www.allmusicguide.com/ |date=2009-10-01 }}</ref>\n\n==Curatorial==\nIn 2019 Benzel organized ''Hoard Inaugural'' at Los Angeles Contemporary Archive, featuring works by Anonymous, Autonomous Oral History Group, Kelman Duran, Arshia Haq, Nick Kochornswasdi, Halldora Miyoko Magnusdottir, Olivia Mole, Misael Oquendo, Rapterotica/Cephalerotica Index, Hande Sever, Alan Tofighi, and Adam Wand. According to the press release, ''Hoard Inaugural\u2019s works function on a vector divorced from the model of the standardized, refined index or \u2018complete\u2019 artwork. They are works and collections that tarry with the hoard and sometimes succumb. The works suggest the possibility of endless conjugation and the impossibility of final categorization, they contain evidence of digging, of obsession, and in some cases unresolvable moral quandaries.'' In 2015, Benzel organized ''Sonatine Bureaucratique'' at Los Angeles Contemporary Archive. According to the press release, ''The show features found and archived material from seemingly disparate spheres presented in conjunction to illuminate how the works of certain conceptual artists ultimately prefigured contemporary systems that have become thoroughly aligned with an administration of social control. Including original catalogs and artist\u2019s books by Guy De Cointet, [[Charles Gaines]], [[Douglas Huebler]], and [[Seth Siegelaub]].''\n\nIn 2012 Benzel curated (in conjunction with SASSAS) ''Welcome Inn Time Machine'', part of the Pacific Standard TIme Performance Festival<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome Inn Time Machine, Pacific Standard Time|url=http://pacificstandardtimefestival.org/events/welcome-inn-time-machine/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115095754/http://pacificstandardtimefestival.org/events/welcome-inn-time-machine/|archivedate=2015-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Swed, Mark, John Cage in a Motel Room as Part of PST, Los Angeles Times, Jan. 30, 2012|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2012/01/music-review-john-cage-in-a-motel-room-as-part-of-pst.html/}}</ref> and, in 2013, ''Tape Music: .sound at the Schindler House''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tape Music: .sound at the Schindler House|url=http://makcenter.org/programming/sound-at-the-schindler-house-tape-music/}}</ref> Both shows presented historical and contemporary experimental musical works in unusual settings.\n\nIn 2011 Benzel organized ''Sublimated Los Angeles'': a film series highlighting little-seen films with strong ties to Los Angeles and suppressed for a variety of reasons, including: Play it as it Lays (1972), [[Let there be light]] (1946), [[Dial M for Murder]] in 3D (1954), [[Pumping Iron]] (1977) at Fellows of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles. In 2011, Benzel curated Seven Los Angeles Artists featuring artists Kathryn Andrews, Anonymous, Anonymous, Erin Cosgrove, Mark Hagen, [[Mike Kelley (artist)|Mike Kelley]], [[Rodney McMillian]], at Fellows of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles from Oct.15-Dec.17\n\n==Teaching==\nBenzel is a member of the faculty of the School of Art at [[California Institute of the Arts]], Valencia, CA.<ref>{{cite web|title=Faculty and Staff Calarts School of Art|url=https://art.calarts.edu/faculty-and-staff/}}</ref> He previously taught at the [[University of California Riverside]], Riverside, CA, and [[California State University, Long Beach]], Long Beach, CA.\n\nBenzel has lectured and taught seminars at Escuela Incierta, [[Cali, Colombia]], 2018, [[Claremont College]], Claremont, CA, 2014, and [[University of Southern California]], Los Angeles, CA, 2012\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.scottbenzel.net/] Website\n* [http://scottbenzel.tumblr.com/] Tumblr\n* [https://frieze.com/article/bad-and-good-times-la] Frieze Bad and Good Times in L.A. 2018\n* [http://www.blouinartinfo.com/news/story/1123391/sonic-highways-scott-benzel-and-the-manifest-destiny] Artinfo/Modern Painters Feature 2015\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141204202111/http://www.flashartonline.com/interno.php?pagina=onweb_det&id_art=1330&det=ok&articolo=Scott-Benzel] Flash Art Maccarone 2014 Review\n* [http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/reviews/scott-benzel/] Art in America Maccarone 2014 Review\n* [http://scottbenzel.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/ArtReview-Benzel-Review.pdf] ArtReview Review 2011\n* [http://artforum.com/inprint/issue=201108&id=39222&section=los-angeles] Artforum Review 2011\n* {{IMDb name|2308794}}\n* [http://www.mikekelley.com/] with Mike Kelley\n* [http://numerodeuxrecordings.com/] Numero Deux Recordings\n* [http://www.joaap.org/1/technoscience/index.html] Technoscience and the Avant-Garde, Journal of Aesthetics and Protest, Vol.1 Number 1, 2002\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benzel, Scott}}\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Arizona]]\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:California Institute of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| bgcolour      = #6495ED\n| name          = Scott Benzel\n| image         = Scott Benzel, Mathesis and Mathematikoi, Mt. Wilson Observatory, 2017.jpg\n|alt=Scott Benzel, Mathesis and Mathematikoi, Mt. Wilson Observatory, 2017\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = Scott Benzel, Mathesis and Mathematikoi, Mt. Wilson Observatory, 2017\n| birth_name     =\n| birth_date     = {{birth-date|1968}}\n| birth_place      = [[Scottsdale, Arizona]]\n| death_date     =\n| death_place    =\n| nationality   = [[United States|American]]\n| field         = [[contemporary art]], [[sculpture]], [[photography]],[[performance art]], and [[video art]].\n| training      =  University of Arizona, BA 1995, California Institute of the Arts, M.F.A, 2001\n| movement      =\n| works         = \n| patrons       =\n| influenced by = \n| influenced    =\n| awards        = \n}}\n'''Scott Benzel''' (born 1968 in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]], lives and works in [[Los Angeles]]), is an American [[visual artist]], musician, [[performance artist]], and [[composer]]. Benzel is a member of the faculty of the School of Art at [[California Institute of the Arts]], Valencia, CA.<ref>{{cite web|title=Faculty and Staff Calarts School of Art|url=https://art.calarts.edu/faculty-and-staff/}}</ref> \n\n==Biography==\nBenzel was born in [[Scottsdale, Arizona]] and raised in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]]. He graduated from the [[University of Arizona]] after undergraduate work at [[California Institute of the Arts]]. In 1998, Benzel returned to [[California Institute of the Arts]] and received his [[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]] in 2001. Benzel is a member of the faculty of the School of Art at [[California Institute of the Arts]].\n\n==Work==\nBenzel's work explores the processes and contradictions inherent in mass media systems of production, the development of collective cultural imaginations and identification, and mythologized cultural histories.\n\nBenzel's work has been shown or performed at The [[J. Paul Getty Museum]], Los Angeles, the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], [[The Hammer Museum]], Los Angeles, The Contemporary Art Museum of St. Louis,<ref>{{cite web|title=Contemporary Art Museum St. Louis, Front Room, Scott Benzel|url=http://camstl.org/exhibitions/front-room/scott-benzel/}}</ref> LAXART, Los Angeles, Maccarone, New York,<ref>{{cite web|title=Maccarone, New York|url=http://www.maccarone.net}}</ref> [[Various Small Fires]], Los Angeles,<ref>{{cite web|title=Various Small Fires, Los Angeles, Scott Benzel|url=http://www.vsf.la/scott-benzel/}}</ref> [[Blum & Poe]], Los Angeles, Human Resources, Los Angeles, the Bard Center for Curatorial Studies,<ref>{{cite web|title=Bard Center for Curatorial Studies, Scott Benzel|url=http://www.bard.edu/ccs/exhibitions/scott-benzel-ivory-neige-lorigine-du-monde-magic-eraser-2/}}</ref> The Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles (in collaboration with Sam Durant and Tom Recchion), Performa 09, New York (in collaboration with [[Mike Kelley (artist)|Mike Kelley]]),<ref>{{cite web|title=Roberta Smith, Performa 09: Mike Kelley\u2019s Extracurricular Activity\", The New York Times,2009|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/11/19/performa-09-mike-kelleys-extracurricular-activity/}}</ref> Mandrake, Los Angeles, Art Basel, Miami, and Art Basel: Statements (in collaboration with Andrea Bowers).\n\nBenzel collaborated with Mike Kelley on the scores and soundtracks to Kelley\u2019s installations ''Day is Done'' at Gagosian Gallery, New York, ''Profondeurs Vertes'' at the Musee Louvre, Paris, and Kelley and Michael Smith\u2019s ''A Voyage of Growth and Discovery'' at the Sculpture Center, New York and West of Rome, Los Angeles. With Kelley, he composed and produced ''Judson Church Dances'', a live performance of the music of ''Day is Done'' with Kelley at [[Judson Church]] for Performa 09, New York.\n\n===Mathesis and Mathematikoi, for string quartet, anvil, dancers, and telescope operator===\nPerformed on the rotating deck of the 100 inch telescope at Mt. Wilson Observatory, CA, part of Knowledges 2017 <ref>{{cite web|title=Kholti, Hedi El, Frieze, Bad and Good times in L.A., a year of protest and performance in Los Angeles, 2017|url=https://frieze.com/article/bad-and-good-times-la/}}</ref>\n\n===The Kouroi/The Society of Dilettanti, for string trio, experimental hardcore trio, voice, and live stream===\nMusical performance/lecture at the J. Paul Getty Museum, Los Angeles, 2017\n\n===Op. 21: Inner Experience Fellowship/Friends of Crime===\nFitzpatrick/Leland House, MAK Center for Art and Architecture, Los Angeles\n\n===Split Chorale for Viljo Revell===\nBenzel collaborated with Kathryn Andrews on the performance for 300 choristers and video in [[Toronto City Hall]], Toronto, ON, as part of Nuit Blanche, Toronto, 2014\n\n===(Threnody) A beginner\u2019s guide to Mao Tse-Tung===\nBenzel was selected for inclusion in the first Los Angeles biennial, Made in L.A. 2012 at the Hammer Museum,<ref>{{cite web|title=Made in L.A. 2012, Hammer Museum|url=http://hammer.ucla.edu/exhibitions/2012/made-in-la-2012/}}</ref> 2012\n\n===Maldistribution===\nBenzel's solo show at Human Resources, Los Angeles, was selected by Artforum and Frieze magazines in their year-end Best of 2011 lists.<ref>{{cite web|title=Holte, Michael Ned, Artforum Best of 2011:Scott Benzel, December, 2011|url=http://scottbenzel.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/11/ArtforumBestof2011-Benzel.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Griffin, Jonathan, Frieze Best of 2011|url=http://blog.frieze.com/best-of-2011-part-6/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140910013914/http://blog.frieze.com/best-of-2011-part-6/|archivedate=2014-09-10}}</ref>\n\n==Exhibitions==\n\n===Selected Solo Exhibitions and Performance===\n\n2020 ''Mindless Pleasures'' Bel Ami, Los Angeles\n\n2018 ''V.I.T.R.I.O.L.'' Los Angeles Contemporary Exhibitions, Los Angeles\n\n2018 ''Torcat Tiqaucrat Mytics Ahtrae'' Acid Free, Blum and Poe, Los Angeles\n\n2017 ''The Kouroi / The Society of Dilettanti'' J. Paul Getty Museum, Los Angeles\n\n2017 ''Mathesis and Mathematikoi'' Mt. Wilson Observatory, CA, Knowledges 2017, curated by Christina Ondrus\n\n2016 ''(Mayakovsky) for Instrumental Transcommunication, Voice, and Autotune'' Rainbow in Spanish, Los Angeles\n\n2015 ''Op. 21: Inner Experience Fellowship/Friends of Crime'' MAK Center for Art and Architecture, Los Angeles\n\n2015 ''Desert Center (Composition I10 Mvmt IV (Dusk))'' Palm Springs Art Museum, Desert Center, CA\n\n2014 Various Small Fires, Los Angeles\n\n2014 Los Angeles Contemporary Archive, Los Angeles\n\n2014 Maccarone, New York\n\n2013 ''LAAIR / The Traveller\u2019s Companion Addenda'' Shanaynay, Paris\n\n2013 ''\u201cScott Benzel\u201d and What does Possession Mean to You?'' Human Resources, Los Angeles\n\n2013 ''\u2026plays selections from\u2026'' Dem  Passwords, Los Angeles\n\n2013 ''W.W.A.R./ Die Dritte Generation'' Art Los Angeles Contemporary, Los Angeles\n\n2012 ''The Academy / The Chthonic at Eleusis'' Public Fiction, Los Angeles\n\n2012 ''(Threnody) A beginner\u2019s guide to Mao Tse-Tung'' Made in LA 2012, Hammer Museum, Los Angeles\n\n2012 ''Funhouse after the Penultimate Sequence of The Lady from Shanghai'' Ball of Artists, LAXART/Hammer\n\n2012 ''Recombinant Folk History and Non-genre I'' Black Box, curated by Liz Glynn, Pacific Standard Time, Los Angeles\n\n2011 Contemporary Art Museum St. Louis, Front Room\n\n2011 ''Maldistribution'' Human Resources at Cottage Home, Los Angeles\n\n2011 ''Concentric Circles (before and after David Smith)'' Los Angeles County Museum of Art, Los Angeles\n\n2010  sound. series concert at King\u2019s Road Park, commission by SASSAS, Los Angeles\n\n===Selected Group Exhibitions===\n\n2019 ''Garland'' Treignac Projet, Treignac, France, curated by Sabrina Tarasoff\n\n2018 ''#followme''  Desert Center, Los Angeles, organized by Michael Slenzke\n\n2018 ''Home Bodies, Away Teams''  UMOCA Salt Lake City, UT, organized by Earl Gravy\n\n2017 ''Imagining Tellus 28''  Harvestworks, New York, curated by Tom Leeser\n\n2017 ''Ours is a City of Writers''  Los Angeles Municipal Gallery, selected by John Tain\n\n2016 ''Nostalgia for the Present: Two Years of LACA''  Los Angeles Contemporary Archive, curated by Eli Diner\n\n2014 ''Golden State''  Museum of Contemporary Art Tucson, curated by Drew Heitzler, Tucson, AZ\n\n2014 ''\u201cAnd yes, I even remember you.\u201d''  Aran Cravey, Los Angeles, curated by Eric Kim\n\n2013 ''\u201cWould you ever Write a Tract?\u201d''  Autocenter, Berlin, curated by Marcel Dickhage and Daniel Horn\n\n2013 ''The Stand In''  Public Fiction, Los Angeles, curated by Alexandra Gaty and Lauren Mackler\n\n2013 ''In the Good Name of the Company''  For Your Art, Los Angeles, curated by Jan Tumlir, Brian Roettinger, Christopher Michlig\n\n2012 ''An Homage to Mike Kelley''  presented by Gagosian Gallery, MOMA PS1, New York\n\n2012 ''Venice Beach Biennial''  with Mark Hagen, curated by Ali Subotnick, Venice, CA\n\n2012 ''Print Imprint''   Actual Size and Cirrus Gallery, Los Angeles\n\n2010 ''Endless Bummer/Surf Elsewhere''  Blum and Poe, Los Angeles, curated by Drew Heitzler\n\n===Selected Collaborations===\n\n2014 ''Split Chorale for Viljo Revell'' with Kathryn Andrews, Nuit Blanche, Toronto, CN\n\n2013 ''Part-Objects'' with Anita Pace, Perform Chinatown, Los Angeles\n\n2012 ''A|D'' with Liz Glynn, also with Corey Fogel, Giles Miller, Public Fiction, Los Angeles\n\n2012 ''Venice Beach Biennial'' with Mark Hagen, curated by Ali Subotnick, Venice, CA\n\n2009 ''Judson Church Horse Dances'' Co-composer, Producer, with Mike Kelley, Performa 09, New York\n\n2009 ''Destroy All Monsters at \u201dA Fantastic World Superimposed on Reality\u201d'' Gramercy Theatre, Performa 09, New York\n\n2009 ''A Voyage of Growth and Discovery'' Original Score Co-composer with Mike Kelley, Sculpture Center, New York\n\n2006 ''Profondeurs Vertes'' Original Score Co-Composer with Mike Kelley, Musee Louvre, Paris\n\n2005 ''Day is Done'' Original Score Co-Composer with Mike Kelley, Gagosian, New York\n\n2004 ''Destroy All Monsters at \u201dAll Tomorrow\u2019s Parties\u201d'' curated by Jake and Dinos Chapman, Camber Sands, UK\n\n2004 ''Into the Sun'' Live Performance w/Sam Durant and Tom Recchion, Museum of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles\n\n2001 ''Democracy\u2019s Body'' Original Score Composer for Andrea Bowers exhibition, Art Basel Statements, Basel, Switzerland\n\n==Musical Work==\nBenzel's performances often incorporate live musicians performing his original compositions. Since 2017, he has been employing limited AI, Machine Learning, and generative algorithmic platforms as part of the composition process. Live performances of compositions include ''Torcat Tiqaucrat Mytics Ahtrae'' Blum and Poe, Los Angeles, 2018''Mathesis and Mathematikoi, for string quartet, anvil, dancers, and telescope operator'', at Mt. Wilson Observatory, Knowledges 2017,<ref>{{cite web|title=Kholti, Hedi El, Frieze, Bad and Good times in L.A., a year of protest and performance in Los Angeles, 2017|url=https://frieze.com/article/bad-and-good-times-la/}}</ref>''The Kouroi/The Society of Dilettani, for string trio, experimental punk trio, voice, and live stream'', at the J. Paul Getty Museum, Los Angeles, 2017, ''Op. 21: Inner Experience Fellowship/Friends of Crime'', at the MAK Center for Art and Architecture, Los Angeles, 2015, ''Desert Center (Composition I10 Mvmt IV (Dusk))'', at the Palm Springs Art Museum, Palm Springs, CA, and Desert Center, CA, 2015, and ''Split Chorale for Viljo Revell for 300 voices'', at Toronto City Hall, Nuit Blanche, Toronto, ON, 2014\n\nMusical projects have included [[Destroy All Monsters (band)|Destroy All Monsters]], the band led by American artist Mike Kelley and [[Machines of Loving Grace]].\n\nIn 2009, Benzel released ''Blak Bloc'', a composition for string quartet and guitar feedback and synthesizer, chosen by Artforum magazine as a Best of 2009: Music.<ref>{{cite web|title=Prina, Stephen, Artforum: Best of 2009: Music: Scott Benzel Blak Bloc\u2019, Dec. 2009|url=http://artforum.com/inprint/id=24235}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to production and remix work with [[The Red Krayola]], [[Destroy All Monsters]], [[Jon Spencer Blues Explosion]], [[Lucinda Williams]], [[Boss Hog]], and various others, Benzel has produced albums for [[Fat Possum Records]], [[Plug Research]] in Los Angeles.<ref>[http://www.allmusicguide.com/ All Music Guide] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091001075157/http://www.allmusicguide.com/ |date=2009-10-01 }}</ref>\n\n==Curatorial==\nIn 2019 Benzel organized ''Hoard Inaugural'' at Los Angeles Contemporary Archive, featuring works by Anonymous, Autonomous Oral History Group, Kelman Duran, Arshia Haq, Nick Kochornswasdi, Halldora Miyoko Magnusdottir, Olivia Mole, Misael Oquendo, Rapterotica/Cephalerotica Index, Hande Sever, Alan Tofighi, and Adam Wand. According to the press release, ''Hoard Inaugural\u2019s works function on a vector divorced from the model of the standardized, refined index or \u2018complete\u2019 artwork. They are works and collections that tarry with the hoard and sometimes succumb. The works suggest the possibility of endless conjugation and the impossibility of final categorization, they contain evidence of digging, of obsession, and in some cases unresolvable moral quandaries.'' In 2015, Benzel organized ''Sonatine Bureaucratique'' at Los Angeles Contemporary Archive. According to the press release, ''The show features found and archived material from seemingly disparate spheres presented in conjunction to illuminate how the works of certain conceptual artists ultimately prefigured contemporary systems that have become thoroughly aligned with an administration of social control. Including original catalogs and artist\u2019s books by Guy De Cointet, [[Charles Gaines]], [[Douglas Huebler]], and [[Seth Siegelaub]].''\n\nIn 2012 Benzel curated (in conjunction with SASSAS) ''Welcome Inn Time Machine'', part of the Pacific Standard TIme Performance Festival<ref>{{cite web|title=Welcome Inn Time Machine, Pacific Standard Time|url=http://pacificstandardtimefestival.org/events/welcome-inn-time-machine/|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150115095754/http://pacificstandardtimefestival.org/events/welcome-inn-time-machine/|archivedate=2015-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Swed, Mark, John Cage in a Motel Room as Part of PST, Los Angeles Times, Jan. 30, 2012|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/culturemonster/2012/01/music-review-john-cage-in-a-motel-room-as-part-of-pst.html/}}</ref> and, in 2013, ''Tape Music: .sound at the Schindler House''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Tape Music: .sound at the Schindler House|url=http://makcenter.org/programming/sound-at-the-schindler-house-tape-music/}}</ref> Both shows presented historical and contemporary experimental musical works in unusual settings.\n\nIn 2011 Benzel organized ''Sublimated Los Angeles'': a film series highlighting little-seen films with strong ties to Los Angeles and suppressed for a variety of reasons, including: Play it as it Lays (1972), [[Let there be light]] (1946), [[Dial M for Murder]] in 3D (1954), [[Pumping Iron]] (1977) at Fellows of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles. In 2011, Benzel curated Seven Los Angeles Artists featuring artists Kathryn Andrews, Anonymous, Anonymous, Erin Cosgrove, Mark Hagen, [[Mike Kelley (artist)|Mike Kelley]], [[Rodney McMillian]], at Fellows of Contemporary Art, Los Angeles from Oct.15-Dec.17\n\n==Teaching==\nBenzel is a member of the faculty of the School of Art at [[California Institute of the Arts]], Valencia, CA.<ref>{{cite web|title=Faculty and Staff Calarts School of Art|url=https://art.calarts.edu/faculty-and-staff/}}</ref> He previously taught at the [[University of California Riverside]], Riverside, CA, and [[California State University, Long Beach]], Long Beach, CA.\n\nBenzel has lectured and taught seminars at Escuela Incierta, [[Cali, Colombia]], 2018, [[Claremont College]], Claremont, CA, 2014, and [[University of Southern California]], Los Angeles, CA, 2012\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.scottbenzel.net/] Website\n* [http://scottbenzel.tumblr.com/] Tumblr\n* [https://frieze.com/article/bad-and-good-times-la] Frieze Bad and Good Times in L.A. 2018\n* [http://www.blouinartinfo.com/news/story/1123391/sonic-highways-scott-benzel-and-the-manifest-destiny] Artinfo/Modern Painters Feature 2015\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141204202111/http://www.flashartonline.com/interno.php?pagina=onweb_det&id_art=1330&det=ok&articolo=Scott-Benzel] Flash Art Maccarone 2014 Review\n* [http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/reviews/scott-benzel/] Art in America Maccarone 2014 Review\n* [http://scottbenzel.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/07/ArtReview-Benzel-Review.pdf] ArtReview Review 2011\n* [http://artforum.com/inprint/issue=201108&id=39222&section=los-angeles] Artforum Review 2011\n* {{IMDb name|2308794}}\n* [http://www.mikekelley.com/] with Mike Kelley\n* [http://numerodeuxrecordings.com/] Numero Deux Recordings\n* [http://www.joaap.org/1/technoscience/index.html] Technoscience and the Avant-Garde, Journal of Aesthetics and Protest, Vol.1 Number 1, 2002\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Benzel, Scott}}\n[[Category:American singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Record producers from Arizona]]\n[[Category:American artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:California Institute of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n", "name_user": "Andr\u00e9Fr\u00e9derique82", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scott_Benzel"}
{"title_page": "Oggy and the Cockroaches", "text_new": "{{short description|French animated comedy series}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = \n| image                    = Oggy and the Cockroaches tittle.jpg\n| caption                  = OgkbvccccvvbnbnOgkbvccccvvbnbngy\n\ngy (left) with Dee Dee, Marky, and Joey\n| genre                    = [[Surreal comedy]]<br>[[Slapstick]]\n| creator                  = [[Jean-Yves Raimbaud]]\n| developer                = [[Marc du Pontavice]]\n| director                 = [[Olivier Jean-Marie]]<br>Jean-Christophe Dessaint\n| country                  = [[France]]\n| language                 = No dialogue (text in English or French)\n| music                    = Herv\u00e9 Lavandier <small>(seasons 1\u20132)</small><br />[[Hugues Le Bars]] (seasons 1\u20134)<br />Vincent Artaud (season 5\u20137)\n| num_seasons              = 7 <!--This value to be incremented once an episode from a new season airs-->\n| num_episodes             = 501 <!--This value to be incremented as new episodes air, not before.-->\n| list_episodes            = List of Oggy and the Cockroaches episodes\n| executive_producer       = [[Marc du Pontavice]]\n| producer                 = [[Marc du Pontavice]]\n| editor                   = Laure Charossuett<br>Lou Bouniol<br>Patrick Ducruet\n| runtime                  = 7 minutes\n| company                  = [[Gaumont Film Company|Gaumont Multimedia]] (seasons 1-2)<br>[[Xilam Animation]] (season 3 onwards)\n| distributor              = <!-- Please provide sourced prose in article body before adding to infobox -->\n| network                  = [[France 3]] (season 1-2)<br>[[Canal+ Family]] (season 3-4)<br>[[Gulli]] (season 1-onwards) <!--Parameter is for original broadcast network only. As this is a French production, this would likely only be a French network.-->\n| picture_format           = ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]]) (seasons 1\u20133)<br>([[High-definition television|HDTV]]) (season 4-onwards)<br>([[Ultra-high-definition television|UHDTV [4K]]]) (remastered episodes of season 1-3, with season 5, season 6 and season 7-onwards)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xilam.com/portfolio/oggy-and-the-cockroachesseason-5/?lang=en|title=Oggy and the Cockroaches \u2013 Xilam|work=xilam.com|accessdate=24 August 2015}}</ref>\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|df=yes|1998|9|6}}\n| last_aired               = present\n| website                  = https://oggy.com\n| image_size               = \n| name                     = Oggy and the Cockroaches\n}}\n\n'''''Oggy and the Cockroaches''''' (known as {{lang|fr|'''Oggy et les Cafards'''}} in French, often referred to as simply ''Oggy'') is a French comedy animated [[children's television series]] produced by [[Gaumont Film Company|Gaumont Multimedia]] (first two seasons) and [[Xilam Animation]] (third season onwards), and created by [[Jean-Yves Raimbaud]]. The show revolves around the titular characters: the cats Oggy, Jack and the cockroaches Joey, Marky, and Dee Dee. When the show started airing in 1998, it was successful in France and was eventually broadcast worldwide.\n\n==Synopsis==\nOggy, an [[anthropomorphic]] cat, would prefer to spend his days watching television and eating, but is continuously pestered by three roaches, Joey, Dee Dee and Marky (all named after members of the [[punk rock]] band [[Ramones]]). The Cockroaches' slapstick mischief ranges from plundering Oggy's refrigerator to hijacking the train he just boarded. There are two additional main characters: Oggy's cousin Jack, who is more violent and short-tempered than him and is also annoyed by the Cockroaches; and Bob, a short-tempered bulldog who is Oggy's neighbor.\n\n==Episodes==\n{{main|List of Oggy and the Cockroaches episodes}}\n{{section#h|Series overview|page=List of Oggy and the Cockroaches episodes}}\n\n==Characters==\n===Main===\n* Oggy is a cat with a light blue body, green eyes, grey tummy and white feet. Oggy usually spends his time either watching TV or doing housework \u2014 when not chasing the cockroaches. Despite the constant mayhem caused by the cockroaches, Oggy has developed a sort of [[love\u2013hate relationship]] with them, having lived with them for a long time. In the episode \"The Ghost Hunter\", Oggy kills the cockroaches but is terrorized by the spirits. Whenever he finds himself alone in his house, he will eventually begin to miss the cockroaches along with their pranks (as seen in the episode \"Priceless Roaches\" and \"So Lonely\") followed by nothing interesting happening in his life. Oggy's house appears bigger on the inside, mainly featured in the roller coaster-like staircase scenes. According to executive producer [[Marc du Pontavice]] and [[France Info]], the character of Oggy was named after punk rock musician [[Iggy Pop]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.commeaucinema.com/interviews/oggy-et-les-cafards-le-film-animation-comedie,289933|title=Interview with Marc du Pontavice|accessdate=14 January 2014|language=French}}</ref> and the rock album [[The Rise and Fall of Ziggy Stardust and the Spiders from Mars]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.franceinfo.fr/emission/cartoon-story/2014-ete/oggy-et-les-cafards-08-06-2014-09-55|title=Article on Oggy and the Cockroaches|date=29 July 2014|accessdate=10 August 2014|language=French}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ladepeche.fr/article/2014/09/18/1954159-oggy-superstar-made-in-france.html|title=La D\u00e9p\u00eache interview|accessdate=19 September 2014|language=French}}</ref> In early episodes, Oggy, like his   [[Tom Cat|Tom and Jerry counterpart]] was the main punching bag in the series. However, in more recent episodes, Oggy has been portrayed as heroic, often triumphing over the cockroaches despite the beatings he takes from them and Bob. Notable other accomplishments include winning the Formula 1, placing first in a marathon, and ultimately winning over his girlfriend Olivia.\n*The Cockroaches are three brothers who antagonize other characters, mainly Oggy and Jack. The cockroaches love pranking them so much, that if the cats were to leave, they would miss them (as seen in the episode \"Moving Out\"). It is also implied that the roaches are named after members of the rock band, [[The Ramones]].\n** Joey (born 15 June 1991)<ref>{{cite episode|season=4|title=Let's Party, Guys!|series=Oggy and the Cockroaches|number=201|credits=Olivier Jean-Marie (director, writer), Fred Mintoff (storyboard)|date=15 July 2012|network=Gulli}}</ref> is a purple-pink body, purple-blue head roach with a [[Heterochromia iridum|pink right eye (originally red) and yellow left eye]], and the oldest brother. Even though he's the smallest roach in the group, most of the time he's the most intelligent, always being the brain in the plans, but is sometimes forced to go solo, because his brothers often think that his plans are stupid. He loves money, but his efforts always fall short, usually ending with him getting swatted or beaten up. He is named after lead singer [[Joey Ramone]].\n** Marky is a suave heartbreaking, silvery-grey body, green head roach with pink eyes (originally red, but returned in the ending of the episode \"Teleportation\" where he is stuck in the ice cubes); he is the tallest and middle brother of the three roaches and often doesn't really care about what the two others are doing. While he originally used to love causing mischief just like his brothers, he has grown to be more laid-back in later episodes, though he still enjoys hanging out with Joey and Dee Dee and causing general mayhem like he has always done. His hobbies are dating puppets and reading books. He also has bad breath, as revealed in the season 1 and season 6 episode \"It's A Small World\". He is named after drummer [[Marky Ramone]].\n** Dee Dee is the ever-hungry cockroach and youngest of the three. He has a blue body, orange head and green eyes. His appetite sometimes reaches insane proportions, often resulting in the consumption of larger animals or other things that would otherwise be inedible (such as [[hyena]]s in one case and, due to the effects of a poisonous mushroom in another case, an insect. Other instances include the fish on the wallpaper \"Oggy's Clone\",\" and a [[clownfish]] in \"Scuba Diving\"). He is known to like opera. Sometimes it is shown that his feet are so foul-smelling, the juice they produce is toxic and melt objects, as shown in \"Caught in a Trap\". He is named after bassist [[Dee Dee Ramone]]\n* Jack is Oggy's cousin, He is a cat who has an olive green body, yellow eyes, pale Salmon pink tummy and white feet, in the show. He is like the complete opposite of Oggy, as he is more short-tempered, violent and arrogant than him \u2013 a perfect target for the roaches to annoy. He often finds himself building huge machinery, such as roach-catching contraptions, most of the time resulting in them backfiring, making him less lucky than Oggy in most situations. He is also very interested in chemistry (that is, the more explosive parts of it). Jack often sleeps over at Oggy's house. At times, he bullies Oggy. Jack seems to be the strongest character in the show. He likes to show off, challenge the roaches and date girls \u2013 mainly Oggy's sister Monica. He is sometimes seen trying to propose to Monica, but the cockroaches' pranks always make him stop short. In one episode, they seem to have a baby together and ask Oggy to babysit their child. Jack also has a morbid fear of heights, as shown in several episodes like the season 4 episode \"The Lighthouse Keeper\". However, in the season 1 episode \"The Rise & The Fall\" Oggy has a fear of heights instead of Jack.\n\n===Recurring===\n* Bob is a fierce brown [[bulldog]] and Oggy's neighbour. He has severe anger management issues.  A running gag in the show has Oggy or Jack doing something that accidentally crushes Bob or shaves his fur or destroys his house, with Bob then pummeling Oggy or Jack off-screen. He does not always pummel Oggy, as seen in a few episodes. He has some sort of friendship with them, as notably seen in ''Olivia'' and ''Back to the Past!''. He is known to like boxing.\n* Olivia is a white cat (also mainly wearing a yellow bow on her head), who is Oggy's new neighbour and new love interest introduced in season 4. She loves nature, even Oggy's main enemies, the cockroaches, leading to Oggy acting nice to them every time she's around. She is aware of their mischief, so she does stop them when they are around by using some aggressive methods, from her anger to even an painful-looking fly swatter. She always breaks down when someone hurts any part of nature. She also cares a lot about her looks, as seen in the episode \"Olivia's Pimple\", where when she saw a pimple on her face, she refused to leave her house. In the season 4 finale episode \"Oggy Is Getting Married (Featuring Olivia)\", as the episode title implies, Olivia and Oggy get married after a trip to [[Venice, Italy|Venice]], [[Italy]].\n* Oggy's grandma is a very rarely seen character only appearing in three episodes; \"Granny's Day\" in season 1 and \"Oggy's Grandma\" in season 3, where she appears to be very strict with Oggy's mannerisms and in \"Deep Trouble\" beside Monica, as they support Oggy and Jack. In the episodes Granny's Day and Oggy's Grandma, she attacks the cockroaches, and is actually attacked by them in Oggy's Grandma, one time being her head flattened by the lid of Oggy's toilet. She also gets frequent, short lasting bursts of energy from coffee, which aids her in defeating the cockroaches. In Granny's Day, she captures Joey and Marky, but feels sympathy for them, when Dee Dee cries on a picture of them with Joey and Marky crossed out. She is the least seen member of Oggy's family except for Oggy's parents, who were seen in a picture in \"Oggy's Grandma\". Oggy's grandma is the only female character to appear on the show to intentionally want to kill/defeat the cockroaches.\n* Monica is Oggy's twin sister and Jack's love-interest. In one episode \"Don't Rock The Cradle\", they seem to have a child together. She visits Oggy's house every now and then. She is well known for being very active and likes to take on physical challenges such as [[sky diving]] and [[bungee jumping]]. She's always seen skating around on her [[inline skates]]. Out of all the main characters, she has the least number of appearances; even fewer than Bob. Monica has rarely appeared onscreen with the cockroaches or Bob (until her cameo only with Bob at the end of the 4th-season finale episode \"Oggy is Getting Married! (Featuring Olivia)\"). In the show's Hindi dubbed version, Monica is instead introduced as Oggy's childhood friend, which might be a glitch. After Season 2, she's only appeared in two other episodes, them being \"Deep Trouble\". In a Season 3 episode, she's instead seen wearing a magenta skirt and shoes instead of her rollerskates. This also marks her first appearance without them since her latest appearance in the season 2 episode \"Don't Rock The Cradle\". This also marks her first appearance without her baby in a later episode who, as mentioned before, also originated from that episode. The second and latest appearance after season 2 was the season 4 finale \"Oggy Is Getting Married (Featuring Olivia)\", where she makes a brief appearance at Oggy and Olivia's wedding as she sits next to Bob. It is unknown, but it is easier to assume she split up with Jack, as their child has never been seen again, that they've never been seen together or have been talking since season 2 and that during that same episode, Jack is staring/ogling at his new partner. She soon became friends with Olivia as in episode of Season 7, \"Sharing Oggy\".\n* Lady K is a light yellow female cockroach introduced in the season 4 episode \"Lady K\", and the roaches' new love interest (mainly Joey). She's the cockroach that lives in Olivia's house, by which Olivia is not aware of. She hates Olivia. She use the cockroaches as her pawns to get what she wants or to get her job done.\n* Bobette is the daughter of Bob who is introduced in Season 5. She is Jack's love interest, as seen in the episodes, \" Marky's Tournament\", and \"Jackromeo and Bobette\". She is seen in the episode, \"Emperor for a Day\" as Napoleon's love interest.\n\n==Production==\nAfter a four-year gap in production, Season 5 is planned for release in late 2017 with two more seasons coming later.<ref>{{cite news|title=Xilam makes debut appearance at BLE 2016|url=http://www.xilam.com/xilamwp/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/Xilam-makes-debut-appearance-at-BLE-2016-FINAL-V5-23.08.pdf|accessdate=14 September 2016|date=23 August 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011044542/http://www.xilam.com/xilamwp/wp-content/uploads/2016/08/Xilam-makes-debut-appearance-at-BLE-2016-FINAL-V5-23.08.pdf|archive-date=11 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Xilam steers international growth with debut at BLE 2016 and PR agency appointment|url=http://www.xilam.com/xilamwp/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/340-Xilam-steers-international-growth-at-BLE-and-appoints-PR-experts-091....pdf|accessdate=14 September 2016|date=13 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011044802/http://www.xilam.com/xilamwp/wp-content/uploads/2016/09/340-Xilam-steers-international-growth-at-BLE-and-appoints-PR-experts-091....pdf|archive-date=11 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Season 6 episodes have begun airing on K2<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.k2tv.it/programmi/oggy-forever/|title=Oggy Forever|language=Italian|accessdate=8 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170628014934/http://www.k2tv.it/programmi/oggy-forever/|archive-date=28 June 2017|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> while Season 5 will be previewed on Gulli.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.leblogtvnews.com/2017/06/saison-5-inedite-d-oggy-et-les-cafards-avant-premiere-le-30-juin-sur-gulli.html|title=Saison 5 in\u00e9dite d'Oggy et les cafards : avant-premi\u00e8re le 30 juin sur Gulli.|language=French|accessdate=8 June 2017|date=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast==\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2012}}\n''Oggy and the Cockroaches'' originates in France, where it aired on networks [[France 3]], [[Canal+]], [[Gulli]] and [[Canal J]].\n\n* In the United States, ''Oggy and the Cockroaches'' initially aired on [[Fox Broadcasting Company]]'s [[Fox Kids]] block on September 12, 1998, six days after the original French airdate.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oltX9DmpLX8&t=11s</ref> It was soon moved to then-sister channel [[Freeform (TV channel)|Fox Family Channel]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kidscreen.com/2016/04/04/oggy-gets-exclusive-broadcasting-deal-with-lagardere/|title=Oggy gets exclusive broadcasting deal with Lagard\u00e8re|publisher=}}</ref> in 1999. The program did not return to television in the United States until February 2015 when it launched on [[Nickelodeon]] for the first time in 16 years. The show aired using certain episodes of Season 4 until its last episode (''High-Rise Nightmare'') was aired on 20 March 2015. Reruns of the show aired on [[Nicktoons]] until the show was taken off the air on May 2015 and has not aired since, until 18 June 2018, when [[KidsClick]] picked up the show for its weekday morning block, until KidsClick's demise on March 31, 2019, making this show not available on American over-the-air television for the first time since 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kidsclick.com/shows/oggy-and-the-cockroaches|title=Oggy and the Cockroaches \u2013 Free Episodes & Games {{!}} KidsCLICK.com|website=KidsCLICK|language=en|access-date=16 June 2018}}</ref> The series is available on Netflix for streaming in the United States.\n* The show also aired on [[Cartoon Network (Japan)|Cartoon Network]] in Japan back in 1999.\n* In South Korea, it aired in [[Tooniverse]] and [[Cartoon Network (South Korea)|Cartoon Network]].\n* ''Oggy and the Cockroaches'' also originally aired on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] on their children's block [[CITV]] and [[Disney XD (UK and Ireland)|Fox Kids]] in the United Kingdom, before moving to [[Pop (UK and Ireland)|Pop]] and eventually [[Pop Max]]. Currently, the show airs on [[Nicktoons (UK and Ireland)|Nicktoons]] in the country, mainly at late nights.\n* In Ireland, the show aired on [[RT\u00c92]] in Ireland as part of ''[[The Den (Ireland)|The Den]]''.\n* It aired in Australia on [[Fox Kids]] and later on the [[ABC1]],  [[ABC3]], [[ABC Me]], [[ABC2]] and [[American Broadcasting Company#ABC HD|ABC HD]] networks, and in [[Canada]] on [[YTV (TV channel)|YTV]] and [[Vrak|Vrak.tv]] (now [[Vrak]]). [[Cartoon Network Asia]] and [[Disney Channel Asia]] also carried the series in Hong Kong, Singapore, Malaysia, Indonesia, the Philippines, and Thailand.\n* ''Oggy and the Cockroaches'' was broadcast in New Zealand on [[TV3 (New Zealand)|TV3]].\n* It also aired in India on [[Nickelodeon India|Nickelodeon]] from 2009 until 2012, when it was moved to [[Cartoon Network India|Cartoon Network]]. However, the network removed all airings from older episodes of the series, just focusing on premieres, while Nickelodeon started broadcasting the show on its older episodes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.afaqs.com/news/story/42795_Oggy-and-the-Cockroaches-to-be-back-on-Nickelodeon|title=Oggy and the Cockroaches to be back on Nickelodeon|website=www.afaqs.com|language=en|access-date=4 May 2018}}</ref> Later, the series was also picked up by [[Sonic Nickelodeon]], resulting in three channels simultaneously airing Oggy. In early 2017, Nickelodeon picked up the rights to air season 4 and Cartoon Network temporarily stopped airing the show. Season 5 started airing on Cartoon Network from 14 August 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.animationxpress.com/index.php/latest-news/asli-fun-asli-hero-asli-oggy-returns-to-cartoon-network|title=Asli Hero with Asli Fun, Asli Oggy returns to Cartoon Network \u2013 AnimationXpressAnimationXpress|website=www.animationxpress.com|date=12 August 2017|language=en-US|access-date=4 May 2018}}</ref> The Indian version of the show is unique in that it has [[Hindi]] dialogues dubbed by voice actor Sourav Chakraborty (imitating famous Bollywood actors), whereas the original version of the show does not feature any spoken dialogue.\n* It is also aired in Pakistan on [[Nickelodeon Pakistan|Nickelodeon]] and [[Cartoon Network Pakistan|Cartoon Network]].\n* In Israel, ''Oggy and the Cockroaches'' aired on [[Arutz HaYeladim]]. \n* In Spain, it aired in [[La 2 (Spanish TV channel)|La 2]].\n* It has aired in Malaysia on numerous channels, including [[TV3 (Malaysia)|TV3]] and formerly [[NTV7]], despite having aired in that country on [[Cartoon Network (Southeast Asia)|Cartoon Network]] and [[Disney Channel (Southeast Asia)|Disney Channel]].\n* [[Super RTL]] aired ''Oggy and the Cockroaches'' in Germany. [[Alter Channel]] also aired the series in Greece, with [[Jetix]] following suit. However, as of 2009, Jetix has ceased operations, and as of December 2011, Alter Channel also has ceased operations as well. As such, ''Oggy and the Cockroaches'' currently no longer airs in Greece.\n* ''Oggy and the Cockroaches'' started streaming through Rovio's [[Rovio Entertainment|toons.tv]] service on December 2013 and continued to stream on the service until November 2015, when it was removed along with other Xilam-related shows such as ''[[Hubert and Takako]]'' and ''[[Zig and Sharko]]''.\n*It is airing on [[Teletoon+|TeleTOON+]] and [[Puls 2]] in Poland.\n*It has aired in Morocco on [[2M (TV channel)|2M]].\n*In Vietnam, BRT, a local television in [[B\u00e0 R\u1ecba-V\u0169ng T\u00e0u Province]] became the first local (non-regional/non-national) television channel to broadcast this show, although Disney Channel Asia formerly aired it. As of 2019, only BRT and Cartoon Network Asia are broadcasting the show, although they recently didn't air any new seasons due to Q.net owning Cartoon Network's Vietnam feed, forcing some shows to not air in Vietnam.\n\n==Adaptations==\n\n===Album===\nAn album, {{lang|fr|Oggy et les Cafards : Le Show du Chat}}, was released in France<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://archives-lepost.huffingtonpost.fr/article/2010/12/29/2354353_oggy-et-ses-cafards-le-dessin-anime-culte-enfin-en-cd-et-dvd.html |title=Oggy et ses cafards, le dessin anim\u00e9 culte enfin en cd et dvd ! |publisher={{Interlanguage link multi|Le Post|fr|3=Le Post|vertical-align=sup}} |author=Jeansanteuil |date=29 December 2010 |accessdate=30 November 2012 |language=French|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121108141354/http://archives-lepost.huffingtonpost.fr/article/2010/12/29/2354353_oggy-et-ses-cafards-le-dessin-anime-culte-enfin-en-cd-et-dvd.html|archivedate=8 November 2012 }}</ref> on CD and for digital download on 6 September 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.feminactu.com/index.php?post/2010/07/15/NOUVEAU-EN-DVD-ET-CD-%3A-Oggy-et-les-cafards-! |title=Nouveau en DVD et CD : Oggy et les cafards ! |publisher={{lang|fr|F\u00e9min Actu}} |author= |date=15 July 2010 |accessdate=30 November 2012|language=French}}</ref>\n\n{{Track listing\n| collapsed = yes\n| headline = 2010 : {{lang|fr|Oggy et les Cafards : Le Show du Chat}} <small>(Sony Music Entertainment)</small>\n| all_writing = \n| all_lyrics = \n| all_music = \n| title1 = {{lang|fr|G\u00e9n\u00e9rique Oggy et les Cafards}}\n| length1 = 0:39\n| title2 = {{lang|fr|Gaga des Gags d'Oggy}}\n| length2 = 2:48\n| title3 = {{lang|fr|Interlude \u00ab Le R\u00e9veil d'Oggy \u00bb}}\n| length3 = 0:19\n| title4 = {{lang|fr|Matez le Matou}}\n| length4 = 2:19\n| title5 = {{lang|fr|Interlude \u00ab Un Chat Bien Bott\u00e9 \u00bb}}\n| length5 = 0:21\n| title6 = [[The Love Cats (song)|Love Cats]]\n| length6 = 3:20\n| title7 = {{lang|fr|Interlude \u00ab Jack, un Ami qui vous Veut du Bien \u00bb}}\n| length7 = 0:22\n| title8 = {{lang|fr|Jack le Pote}}\n